WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.620
[Amit Varma]: Here's a question I sometimes ask myself, how often in my life have I been actually

00:00:09.620 --> 00:00:10.620
[Amit Varma]: alive?

00:00:10.620 --> 00:00:14.660
[Amit Varma]: By which I mean engaged in what I am doing, living in the moment, questioning what I really

00:00:14.660 --> 00:00:17.500
[Amit Varma]: want and not just following a groove set out for me.

00:00:17.500 --> 00:00:22.040
[Amit Varma]: Here's the thing, through our lives, we often get on a path and follow a default.

00:00:22.040 --> 00:00:26.160
[Amit Varma]: As young people in our society, we look at our parents and the people around us and sometimes

00:00:26.160 --> 00:00:28.960
[Amit Varma]: become those men and women and don't think for ourselves.

00:00:28.960 --> 00:00:33.360
[Amit Varma]: If the conventional way is to get married and have kids, we get married and have kids.

00:00:33.360 --> 00:00:36.960
[Amit Varma]: We get the education we are supposed to get and then embark on the career we are supposed

00:00:36.960 --> 00:00:37.960
[Amit Varma]: to have.

00:00:37.960 --> 00:00:40.840
[Amit Varma]: In our workplace, we tick the boxes we are supposed to tick.

00:00:40.840 --> 00:00:44.000
[Amit Varma]: In our personal lives, we play the roles we are supposed to play.

00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:48.080
[Amit Varma]: It's as if we have been coded to live in a particular way and we are machines of flesh

00:00:48.080 --> 00:00:50.320
[Amit Varma]: and blood following that code.

00:00:50.320 --> 00:00:54.960
[Amit Varma]: But sometimes, we can step back for a moment and see the matrix we are stuck inside.

00:00:54.960 --> 00:00:59.920
[Amit Varma]: We can question our choices, think about what we truly want and not just what we are supposed

00:00:59.920 --> 00:01:02.120
[Amit Varma]: to or expected to want.

00:01:02.120 --> 00:01:10.400
[Amit Varma]: Are those moments the only moments when we are truly free, when we are truly alive?

00:01:10.400 --> 00:01:15.600
[Unknown]: Welcome to The Seen and The Unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics and behavioral

00:01:15.600 --> 00:01:16.600
[Unknown]: science.

00:01:16.600 --> 00:01:22.880
[Amit Varma]: Please welcome your host, Amit Verma.

00:01:22.880 --> 00:01:24.040
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to The Seen and The Unseen.

00:01:24.040 --> 00:01:28.360
[Amit Varma]: My guest today is Samarth Bansal, a journalist known for his skill with data, but someone

00:01:28.360 --> 00:01:33.120
[Amit Varma]: whose journalism goes well beyond numbers and whose thinking goes well beyond journalism.

00:01:33.120 --> 00:01:37.700
[Amit Varma]: Samarth was into math and computing when he was young, went to IIT, decided not to follow

00:01:37.700 --> 00:01:42.480
[Amit Varma]: the typical IIT path, became a journalist, decided not to follow the typical journalist

00:01:42.480 --> 00:01:43.480
[Amit Varma]: path.

00:01:43.480 --> 00:01:47.560
[Amit Varma]: And he now lives in the hills, working on the stories he wants to work on, taking breaks

00:01:47.560 --> 00:01:52.080
[Amit Varma]: when he wants, still visiting Delhi once in a while with a different gaze than the one

00:01:52.080 --> 00:01:53.960
[Amit Varma]: he had when he was growing up here.

00:01:53.960 --> 00:01:58.560
[Amit Varma]: I've always found Samarth's journalism thought-provoking, and when I met him at a recent conference

00:01:58.560 --> 00:02:00.840
[Amit Varma]: in Udaipur, I invited him on the show.

00:02:00.840 --> 00:02:03.080
[Amit Varma]: I think we also gelled well on that first meeting.

00:02:03.080 --> 00:02:07.080
[Amit Varma]: I found Samarth thoughtful, straightforward and curious.

00:02:07.080 --> 00:02:12.240
[Amit Varma]: And when we finally recorded in Delhi, I was so, so impressed by the quality of his self-reflection.

00:02:12.240 --> 00:02:16.360
[Amit Varma]: In this episode, he talks about his journaling habit and how that helped him question everything

00:02:16.360 --> 00:02:18.240
[Amit Varma]: about his life and choices.

00:02:18.240 --> 00:02:22.820
[Amit Varma]: He talks a lot about journalism, going back to first principles, asking questions like

00:02:22.820 --> 00:02:26.840
[Amit Varma]: how do we define newsworthiness, how do we decide what stories to do.

00:02:26.840 --> 00:02:31.880
[Amit Varma]: He speaks about ethics in his life, on the college campus, in the newsroom.

00:02:31.880 --> 00:02:36.120
[Amit Varma]: He speaks about the choice he has made to live an examined life and how that involves

00:02:36.120 --> 00:02:38.940
[Amit Varma]: walking away from the expectations of others.

00:02:38.940 --> 00:02:44.480
[Amit Varma]: He speaks in detail about his time in IIT and in the media, so other IITians and journalists

00:02:44.480 --> 00:02:46.520
[Amit Varma]: would find a lot to relate to.

00:02:46.520 --> 00:02:51.060
[Amit Varma]: But the first half of our conversation is about life itself, and I found much wisdom

00:02:51.060 --> 00:02:53.200
[Amit Varma]: there and much to think about.

00:02:53.200 --> 00:02:57.140
[Amit Varma]: For some reason, there's an honesty and warmth and a connection in this episode that reminded

00:02:57.140 --> 00:03:02.280
[Amit Varma]: me of the ones I recorded with Prem Panikkar and Amitabh Kumar and Chandrahar Choudhary.

00:03:02.280 --> 00:03:05.920
[Amit Varma]: Except those guys were old friends of mine, and I was meeting Samarth here for the second

00:03:05.920 --> 00:03:06.920
[Amit Varma]: time.

00:03:06.920 --> 00:03:10.340
[Amit Varma]: So I'm touched by the trust he placed in me and in all of you because you're all listening

00:03:10.340 --> 00:03:11.340
[Amit Varma]: as well.

00:03:11.340 --> 00:03:15.940
[Amit Varma]: By the way, this episode was recorded in August, and the story we discussed in it about the

00:03:15.940 --> 00:03:17.400
[Amit Varma]: wire was an older one.

00:03:17.400 --> 00:03:21.780
[Amit Varma]: And now we're releasing it in October, when the wire is in the center of another storm.

00:03:21.780 --> 00:03:24.980
[Amit Varma]: I'm reserving judgment on it till I read what Samarth has to say.

00:03:24.980 --> 00:03:28.380
[Amit Varma]: I know he sees angles and nuances that no one else does.

00:03:28.380 --> 00:03:32.260
[Amit Varma]: Anyway, before we begin this conversation, let's take a quick commercial break.

00:03:32.260 --> 00:03:36.960
[Amit Varma]: There are no commercials because but let's take a break anyway.

00:03:36.960 --> 00:03:40.020
[Amit Varma]: Have you always wanted to be a writer, but never quite gotten down to it?

00:03:40.020 --> 00:03:41.340
[Amit Varma]: Well, I'd love to help you.

00:03:41.340 --> 00:03:46.300
[Amit Varma]: Since April 2020, I've taught 20 cohorts of my online course, the art of clear writing.

00:03:46.300 --> 00:03:50.900
[Amit Varma]: An online community has now sprung up of all my past students, we have workshops, a newsletter

00:03:50.900 --> 00:03:55.540
[Amit Varma]: to showcase the work of students and vibrant community interaction in the course itself

00:03:55.540 --> 00:04:00.000
[Amit Varma]: through four webinars spread over four weekends, I share all I know about the craft and practice

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:01.000
[Amit Varma]: of clear writing.

00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:05.020
[Amit Varma]: There are many exercises, much interaction, a lovely and lively community at the end of

00:04:05.020 --> 00:04:06.020
[Amit Varma]: it.

00:04:06.020 --> 00:04:10.140
[Amit Varma]: The course costs rupees 10,000 plus GST, or about $150 and is a monthly thing.

00:04:10.140 --> 00:04:15.060
[Amit Varma]: So if you're interested, head on over to register at indiancut.com slash clear writing.

00:04:15.060 --> 00:04:17.820
[Amit Varma]: It's indiancut.com slash clear writing.

00:04:17.820 --> 00:04:22.620
[Amit Varma]: Being a good writer doesn't require God given talent, just the willingness to work hard

00:04:22.620 --> 00:04:26.180
[Amit Varma]: and a clear idea of what you need to do to refine your skills.

00:04:26.180 --> 00:04:27.180
[Amit Varma]: I can help you.

00:04:27.180 --> 00:04:31.460
[Amit Varma]: Samarth, welcome to the scene on The Unsealed.

00:04:31.460 --> 00:04:32.900
[Amit Varma]: Thank you Amit for having me.

00:04:32.900 --> 00:04:37.260
[Amit Varma]: So it's just to let the listeners know I bumped into Samarth at this conference where, you

00:04:37.260 --> 00:04:39.620
[Amit Varma]: know, everybody wore these name tags with them.

00:04:39.620 --> 00:04:42.700
[Amit Varma]: And I looked at her name tag and straightaway, obviously, I've been following your work.

00:04:42.700 --> 00:04:46.660
[Amit Varma]: And I thought, okay, this is kind of going to be interesting.

00:04:46.660 --> 00:04:50.020
[Amit Varma]: And I think we also when we were talking in a session there just got into this really

00:04:50.020 --> 00:04:51.020
[Amit Varma]: comfortable groove.

00:04:51.020 --> 00:04:53.980
[Amit Varma]: So I was looking forward to this conversation.

00:04:53.980 --> 00:04:55.820
[Amit Varma]: And I think we'll both enjoy it.

00:04:55.820 --> 00:05:00.940
[Amit Varma]: So let's start by you telling me or you telling us, you know, more about yourself, like, kaan

00:05:00.940 --> 00:05:01.940
[Amit Varma]: se aayo?

00:05:01.940 --> 00:05:02.940
[Amit Varma]: Where did you grow up?

00:05:02.940 --> 00:05:03.940
[Amit Varma]: What's your background?

00:05:03.940 --> 00:05:04.940
[Guest]: Sure.

00:05:04.940 --> 00:05:10.980
[Guest]: So I was born and brought up in Delhi, North Delhi, specifically, I like to make that distinction,

00:05:10.980 --> 00:05:14.620
[Guest]: because there is this big, I think, cultural difference in different parts of Delhi, I

00:05:14.620 --> 00:05:21.900
[Guest]: went to a school close to my house, English medium private school, medium sized school.

00:05:21.900 --> 00:05:28.220
[Guest]: But right from that time, you had some sort of, I would say, inferiority complex that

00:05:28.220 --> 00:05:33.300
[Guest]: you know, you are not one of those kids from the DPS archipelago or modern school Parakhamba.

00:05:33.300 --> 00:05:37.860
[Guest]: So you know, and like, it was a very homogenous group in the school, everyone in the Pitampura

00:05:37.860 --> 00:05:41.580
[Guest]: area is, you know, same kind of backgrounds.

00:05:41.580 --> 00:05:45.580
[Guest]: So that's the kind of school I went to my family.

00:05:45.580 --> 00:05:51.980
[Guest]: My dad is a businessman, he grew up in a village near Ludhiana, there were seven brothers and

00:05:51.980 --> 00:05:52.980
[Guest]: one sister.

00:05:52.980 --> 00:05:58.660
[Guest]: When he was 1884 riots happened in Punjab.

00:05:58.660 --> 00:06:03.660
[Guest]: And so around that time, three of these brothers moved to Imphal.

00:06:03.660 --> 00:06:09.940
[Guest]: And like my grandfather didn't really have like, in terms of finances, the very, very

00:06:09.940 --> 00:06:11.060
[Guest]: modest beginning.

00:06:11.060 --> 00:06:16.020
[Guest]: So my dad, and two brothers, they didn't, they like built up a business from scratch

00:06:16.020 --> 00:06:17.020
[Guest]: in Imphal.

00:06:17.020 --> 00:06:22.940
[Guest]: He was telling me, you know, they had these dealership of like fruity and other brands.

00:06:22.940 --> 00:06:29.420
[Guest]: So one of the they build their credibility, and, you know, used to drive a truck all across

00:06:29.420 --> 00:06:34.220
[Guest]: Imphal and Manipur, and, you know, made good fortune for himself there.

00:06:34.220 --> 00:06:40.500
[Guest]: And then, after six, seven years in the early 90s, early 90s, what I think in 91, came to

00:06:40.500 --> 00:06:41.500
[Guest]: Delhi.

00:06:41.500 --> 00:06:48.260
[Guest]: And yeah, then, slowly, other other brothers came, and they built a business here.

00:06:48.260 --> 00:06:51.460
[Guest]: And I think post liberalization, you know, their business grew up.

00:06:51.460 --> 00:06:56.500
[Guest]: So I sometimes retrospectively think that somehow, you know, my father's journey is

00:06:56.500 --> 00:07:02.420
[Guest]: in a way, you know, that moment where liberalization was giving opportunities to people.

00:07:02.420 --> 00:07:05.020
[Guest]: So my father was one of the beneficiaries.

00:07:05.020 --> 00:07:08.100
[Guest]: And my mom, she grew up in Delhi.

00:07:08.100 --> 00:07:12.300
[Guest]: And my nana ji was a gazette officer.

00:07:12.300 --> 00:07:17.380
[Guest]: And she, again, like both my dad didn't go to college, my mom did a correspondence course

00:07:17.380 --> 00:07:19.460
[Guest]: from Delhi University.

00:07:19.460 --> 00:07:22.180
[Guest]: And then they got married, arranged marriage setup.

00:07:22.180 --> 00:07:30.220
[Guest]: So after that, I think, since I was a, you know, right from early childhood, I was told

00:07:30.220 --> 00:07:34.980
[Guest]: that education is the thing that matters the most.

00:07:34.980 --> 00:07:41.060
[Guest]: And one of the things that was that my mom felt like a victim of patriarchy, right?

00:07:41.060 --> 00:07:43.100
[Guest]: So we have a massive family.

00:07:43.100 --> 00:07:46.220
[Guest]: It's a I told you already, right, like seven brothers.

00:07:46.220 --> 00:07:50.100
[Guest]: Then my grandfather had like four brothers, so it's a big family.

00:07:50.100 --> 00:07:52.300
[Guest]: And my mom was somehow not able to fit in.

00:07:52.300 --> 00:07:59.260
[Guest]: So for her, the success, quote unquote, success of me, and I'm the elder kid, my sister is,

00:07:59.260 --> 00:08:05.940
[Guest]: you know, eight years younger to me, was kind of, you know, to show that kids can be on

00:08:05.940 --> 00:08:11.040
[Guest]: their own, and they don't need the, you know, like what she felt.

00:08:11.040 --> 00:08:18.420
[Guest]: So her, what I'm trying to articulate here is that my education and the investment that

00:08:18.420 --> 00:08:25.700
[Guest]: my mom did, was in some way, a reflection of a rebellion, you know, about what she didn't

00:08:25.700 --> 00:08:30.940
[Guest]: feel about, you know, things that she didn't feel right, and her response to that.

00:08:30.940 --> 00:08:36.860
[Guest]: So I gave this context, because all through my school time, you know, this was a big push

00:08:36.860 --> 00:08:39.980
[Guest]: that and she invested a lot I can see in retrospection.

00:08:39.980 --> 00:08:43.340
[Guest]: So again, I told you in the beginning about that inferiority complex.

00:08:43.340 --> 00:08:49.140
[Guest]: So I have this vivid memory where I'm sitting in front of the school, I got the admission,

00:08:49.140 --> 00:08:53.620
[Guest]: and my mom was so angry because some other elite schools rejected me.

00:08:53.620 --> 00:09:03.180
[Guest]: So you know, you have to prove yourself in academics, and do well, all sorts of things.

00:09:03.180 --> 00:09:04.420
[Guest]: So that's the long context.

00:09:04.420 --> 00:09:07.140
[Guest]: And I think, I don't know where it came from.

00:09:07.140 --> 00:09:12.060
[Guest]: But right from the beginning, I just absolutely loved studying, you know, since a kid, you

00:09:12.060 --> 00:09:16.620
[Guest]: know, you know, that classmate, you're a topper, you're doing other things.

00:09:16.620 --> 00:09:19.820
[Guest]: My mom used to take me to extracurricular activities.

00:09:19.820 --> 00:09:25.900
[Guest]: So I learned, you know, music, dance, all of those things, they were all happening simultaneously.

00:09:25.900 --> 00:09:29.140
[Guest]: So that's how it, you know, I was growing up.

00:09:29.140 --> 00:09:32.220
[Guest]: And yeah, always on top of the class.

00:09:32.220 --> 00:09:36.220
[Guest]: And I think sometime, so yeah, school went like this.

00:09:36.220 --> 00:09:42.340
[Guest]: And in retrospection, I think that somehow, like then, you know, until like fifth grade

00:09:42.340 --> 00:09:48.620
[Guest]: or sixth grade, the way you just assessed myself, I assessed myself was primarily through

00:09:48.620 --> 00:09:51.340
[Guest]: your exam scores, right?

00:09:51.340 --> 00:09:56.420
[Guest]: Now that, like, I'm trying to build a career in journalism and writing, and I hear so many

00:09:56.420 --> 00:09:58.660
[Guest]: writers about their childhoods.

00:09:58.660 --> 00:10:03.180
[Guest]: So many of them, you know, read books, they grew up reading books.

00:10:03.180 --> 00:10:04.580
[Guest]: Like I didn't grow up in that environment.

00:10:04.580 --> 00:10:08.900
[Guest]: Like for me, books always meant textbooks, even again, you know, culturally, if you look

00:10:08.900 --> 00:10:15.180
[Guest]: at North Delhi, we don't have a bookshop, like, you know, it was only after I became

00:10:15.180 --> 00:10:18.420
[Guest]: a journalist, I learned that, okay, there is a bhaari sansin khan market, where now

00:10:18.420 --> 00:10:19.820
[Guest]: I'm a regular.

00:10:19.820 --> 00:10:25.020
[Guest]: So I'm saying that was the kind of environment you, I grew up in, it was just textbooks.

00:10:25.020 --> 00:10:29.580
[Guest]: But again, my, I remember like, you know, I was so engrossed in my math classes and

00:10:29.580 --> 00:10:32.580
[Guest]: science classes, it was never forced.

00:10:32.580 --> 00:10:36.740
[Guest]: But yeah, there were things like my cousins and my friends would play cricket in the evening.

00:10:36.740 --> 00:10:40.580
[Guest]: But I was told that, you know, it's important to study.

00:10:40.580 --> 00:10:46.100
[Guest]: So I think maybe early class three, class four, I would have felt, why is this happening?

00:10:46.100 --> 00:10:50.340
[Guest]: But I think in the larger scheme of things, I was very happy with what I was doing.

00:10:50.340 --> 00:10:53.020
[Guest]: So that's the academic part kept going on.

00:10:53.020 --> 00:10:54.020
[Guest]: And we can do details later.

00:10:54.020 --> 00:11:00.300
[Guest]: But I think somehow in fifth grade to eighth grade, you know, I became like, really passionate

00:11:00.300 --> 00:11:02.620
[Guest]: about computers.

00:11:02.620 --> 00:11:07.180
[Guest]: There's a whole series of things that happened while I was growing up, which led to that.

00:11:07.180 --> 00:11:14.220
[Guest]: And in seventh grade, I requested my parents that please, I want a computer at home, I

00:11:14.220 --> 00:11:15.300
[Guest]: want a desktop.

00:11:15.300 --> 00:11:18.420
[Guest]: And it was a big deal to ask them.

00:11:18.420 --> 00:11:23.140
[Guest]: And one of the things I told them is that I really want to learn things and I will never

00:11:23.140 --> 00:11:24.860
[Guest]: play a computer game.

00:11:24.860 --> 00:11:28.460
[Guest]: Okay, so I promise you just get me a computer.

00:11:28.460 --> 00:11:29.460
[Guest]: And they did.

00:11:29.460 --> 00:11:33.020
[Guest]: And the funny thing is that I was not even interested in gaming, you know, so it was

00:11:33.020 --> 00:11:35.300
[Guest]: not something that I had to give something up.

00:11:35.300 --> 00:11:38.260
[Guest]: But that's just the way of telling them that I really want this.

00:11:38.260 --> 00:11:39.620
[Guest]: And I think that opened the world for me.

00:11:39.620 --> 00:11:47.740
[Guest]: I remember telling myself that this is seventh grade, that God made humans, right?

00:11:47.740 --> 00:11:52.660
[Guest]: Like at the time, like now I'm an atheist, so going back that there's God, God created

00:11:52.660 --> 00:11:56.640
[Guest]: humans and humans created this machine.

00:11:56.640 --> 00:12:03.780
[Guest]: So I can now play God, you know, I can do things with it, I can create anything I want.

00:12:03.780 --> 00:12:08.180
[Guest]: And that I clearly remember the day when I told my parents, I'm going to be a software

00:12:08.180 --> 00:12:09.580
[Guest]: engineer.

00:12:09.580 --> 00:12:10.580
[Guest]: This is seventh grade.

00:12:10.580 --> 00:12:11.580
[Guest]: So it became very organically.

00:12:11.580 --> 00:12:15.700
[Guest]: And then I did a lot of stuff on my computer back home in school, all of those things were

00:12:15.700 --> 00:12:16.700
[Guest]: happening.

00:12:16.700 --> 00:12:21.900
[Guest]: And in eighth grade, I learned one of my cousins was preparing for this exam called IIT JEE.

00:12:21.900 --> 00:12:27.340
[Guest]: And then I learned that if in India, you want to study engineering, then you have to the

00:12:27.340 --> 00:12:30.860
[Guest]: best school is Indian Institute of Technology.

00:12:30.860 --> 00:12:31.860
[Guest]: And that was it.

00:12:31.860 --> 00:12:35.620
[Guest]: I think in eighth grade, I realized that, you know, there is this college, I want to

00:12:35.620 --> 00:12:36.880
[Guest]: become an engineer.

00:12:36.880 --> 00:12:42.140
[Guest]: And I was told that the exam, you need to be good at math and science, which I was.

00:12:42.140 --> 00:12:46.700
[Guest]: And I think there was some again, it's a whole diversion into details, but there's an exam

00:12:46.700 --> 00:12:50.340
[Guest]: that I qualified in eighth grade, which gave me the confidence that I have a standing beyond

00:12:50.340 --> 00:12:51.580
[Guest]: my school.

00:12:51.580 --> 00:12:55.100
[Guest]: And then I think, grade ninth, I joined coaching.

00:12:55.100 --> 00:12:59.700
[Guest]: And it was like, you know, it was brilliant, you know, my coaching days preparing for JEE.

00:12:59.700 --> 00:13:05.620
[Guest]: And fortunately, I got into, got admission to IIT Kanpur, studied math and computing.

00:13:05.620 --> 00:13:10.540
[Guest]: And yeah, so that's the, that's, that's my childhood till I went to college.

00:13:10.540 --> 00:13:14.680
[Amit Varma]: So let's go back to, you know, the early part of the story where you mentioned your huge

00:13:14.680 --> 00:13:18.660
[Amit Varma]: family and your mom and the patriarchy and all of that.

00:13:18.660 --> 00:13:24.140
[Amit Varma]: And what I realized looking back at my own life, for example, is that we figure out a

00:13:24.140 --> 00:13:29.620
[Amit Varma]: lot of this stuff in retrospect, like you said, you know, in that, you know, the world

00:13:29.620 --> 00:13:35.220
[Amit Varma]: that we are in, it is normal for us, everything there is normalized, this is how people kind

00:13:35.220 --> 00:13:36.540
[Amit Varma]: of live their lives.

00:13:36.540 --> 00:13:40.500
[Amit Varma]: So is it all, you know, through retrospect, when you look at your mom that you realize

00:13:40.500 --> 00:13:43.900
[Amit Varma]: what she was going through, and this narrative is there that she was struggling against that

00:13:43.900 --> 00:13:50.460
[Amit Varma]: and all of that, or in the moment, could you also sense her frustration and the stuff that

00:13:50.460 --> 00:13:51.460
[Amit Varma]: was happening to her?

00:13:51.460 --> 00:13:53.100
[Amit Varma]: And this is such a common story, right?

00:13:53.100 --> 00:13:57.980
[Amit Varma]: This is basically India's story, that women are trapped in situations.

00:13:57.980 --> 00:14:02.220
[Amit Varma]: And you know, they look at different ways to gain escape.

00:14:02.220 --> 00:14:04.260
[Amit Varma]: And sometimes those are invisible ways.

00:14:04.260 --> 00:14:07.660
[Amit Varma]: Sometimes those are just tortured interior lives, right?

00:14:07.660 --> 00:14:13.100
[Amit Varma]: And so tell me a little bit, you know, more about your mom, firstly, and and also, you

00:14:13.100 --> 00:14:18.260
[Amit Varma]: know, did you resent what you might sometimes have thought was overbearing, ki padhai karo,

00:14:18.260 --> 00:14:20.700
[Amit Varma]: cricket mat khelo, all of that.

00:14:20.700 --> 00:14:24.420
[Amit Varma]: And, and you know, how much like you mentioned before we started that you've been journaling

00:14:24.420 --> 00:14:25.420
[Amit Varma]: for four years.

00:14:25.420 --> 00:14:28.860
[Amit Varma]: And that's, you know, kind of useful and in a sense is dangerous, because you're kind

00:14:28.860 --> 00:14:33.360
[Amit Varma]: of constructing yourself as it were through the through what you choose your memories

00:14:33.360 --> 00:14:34.360
[Amit Varma]: to be.

00:14:34.360 --> 00:14:35.360
[Amit Varma]: Right.

00:14:35.360 --> 00:14:40.260
[Amit Varma]: But at the same time, I think like in journaling, you know, I did an episode with Amitabh Kumar,

00:14:40.260 --> 00:14:44.260
[Amit Varma]: and we spoke a lot about journaling, and it's something I recommend to everyone, because

00:14:44.260 --> 00:14:48.700
[Amit Varma]: it's a way of not just knowing yourself, but kind of shaping yourself.

00:14:48.700 --> 00:14:55.420
[Amit Varma]: So how much does, you know, introspection at this stage, self reflection, looking back,

00:14:55.420 --> 00:14:59.100
[Amit Varma]: how much does it sort of shape your understanding of that world?

00:14:59.100 --> 00:15:03.780
[Amit Varma]: I mean, and how much did you know in the moment ki yeh aisa hai and all of that?

00:15:03.780 --> 00:15:05.500
[Guest]: So I knew in the moment.

00:15:05.500 --> 00:15:09.220
[Guest]: So have you heard of this term, parentified kids?

00:15:09.220 --> 00:15:17.700
[Guest]: So, the first time I heard this term, I think, actually, it was on a Tyler Cohen podcast.

00:15:17.700 --> 00:15:22.420
[Guest]: I can't pronounce the name of this author, but one of her book, Strangers Drowning, it's

00:15:22.420 --> 00:15:27.660
[Guest]: a book on moral philosophy, you know, seven or eight profiles, deep profiles and Larissa

00:15:27.660 --> 00:15:30.780
[Guest]: something, I'm forgetting the name, sorry.

00:15:30.780 --> 00:15:37.380
[Guest]: So the parentified kid, when the term I heard, it just blew my mind, because it is something

00:15:37.380 --> 00:15:43.180
[Guest]: that, again, I try to think a lot about like, who I am I today, what can I trace back to

00:15:43.180 --> 00:15:45.140
[Guest]: my childhood?

00:15:45.140 --> 00:15:50.000
[Guest]: What are the roots of who I am as a person, what goes back?

00:15:50.000 --> 00:15:56.980
[Guest]: And one of the things that hit me was empathy, that, you know, there is a, like, if I go,

00:15:56.980 --> 00:16:01.540
[Guest]: when I was a student in college, you know, there was this sense of deep sense of right

00:16:01.540 --> 00:16:05.420
[Guest]: and wrong, that, you know, I want to make an impact, I want to change things, I'm a

00:16:05.420 --> 00:16:10.300
[Guest]: very different person now, but 10 years ago, that was me, where you had the sense of, you

00:16:10.300 --> 00:16:16.020
[Guest]: know, may occur, right, or, you know, this whole Steve Jobs sense of changing the world,

00:16:16.020 --> 00:16:20.860
[Guest]: or, you know, you see, you know, you see injustice around and you feel I have to do something

00:16:20.860 --> 00:16:21.860
[Guest]: to help.

00:16:21.860 --> 00:16:23.660
[Guest]: So where is that empathy coming from?

00:16:23.660 --> 00:16:28.300
[Guest]: So one of the this idea of parentified kids is that, sorry, I didn't even describe what

00:16:28.300 --> 00:16:35.660
[Guest]: it is, but it's something like, when you're growing up, you start, at an early age, start

00:16:35.660 --> 00:16:40.100
[Guest]: acting as a parent to your parents.

00:16:40.100 --> 00:16:41.620
[Guest]: Okay.

00:16:41.620 --> 00:16:50.420
[Guest]: And I, you know, I always say, you know, that, to put it simply, there is the, it's a dysfunctional

00:16:50.420 --> 00:16:51.420
[Guest]: family.

00:16:51.420 --> 00:16:52.420
[Guest]: Okay.

00:16:52.420 --> 00:16:56.060
[Guest]: And the way to, I see that with my friends is that, you know, I talk about films.

00:16:56.060 --> 00:17:02.860
[Guest]: So there's this friend of mine and I was talking to her about Zoya Akhtar's movie, Dil Dhadak

00:17:02.860 --> 00:17:03.940
[Guest]: Ne Do.

00:17:03.940 --> 00:17:08.620
[Guest]: And she was like, what a stupid movie, you know, have you seen the movie?

00:17:08.620 --> 00:17:09.620
[Amit Varma]: I haven't.

00:17:09.620 --> 00:17:10.620
[Amit Varma]: I love her other films.

00:17:10.620 --> 00:17:12.660
[Guest]: I think I've seen it in passing, but I didn't like it as much.

00:17:12.660 --> 00:17:13.660
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:17:13.660 --> 00:17:16.780
[Guest]: So, you know, she was like, aise thodi hota hai, this is not how families work.

00:17:16.780 --> 00:17:19.380
[Guest]: You know, aise ladhai kare ja rahe hain.

00:17:19.380 --> 00:17:26.700
[Guest]: And you know, Amit, when my sister, like both of us watched that movie, we were like, wow,

00:17:26.700 --> 00:17:27.700
[Guest]: someone gets us.

00:17:27.700 --> 00:17:30.740
[Guest]: Same with Kapoor and Sons, you know.

00:17:30.740 --> 00:17:31.740
[Amit Varma]: Which is a lovely film.

00:17:31.740 --> 00:17:32.740
[Guest]: Which is a lovely film.

00:17:32.740 --> 00:17:33.740
[Guest]: Right.

00:17:33.740 --> 00:17:39.900
[Guest]: But what you see in all of these situations is just that, you know, deep, you know, like

00:17:39.900 --> 00:17:44.460
[Guest]: dysfunctional families, which from the outside, you won't know what is happening.

00:17:44.460 --> 00:17:45.460
[Guest]: Right.

00:17:45.460 --> 00:17:48.100
[Guest]: But anything can break at any time.

00:17:48.100 --> 00:17:51.260
[Guest]: And you can't, you don't even know how to talk about it to someone.

00:17:51.260 --> 00:17:55.100
[Guest]: Even the fact that I am telling it to you now.

00:17:55.100 --> 00:18:00.740
[Guest]: It's because now I have, over the course of journaling over four years, I have now understood

00:18:00.740 --> 00:18:01.740
[Guest]: what it is.

00:18:01.740 --> 00:18:02.740
[Guest]: Right.

00:18:02.740 --> 00:18:06.500
[Guest]: Five years, six years ago, I could not even talk about it to my friends.

00:18:06.500 --> 00:18:11.380
[Guest]: But now I could because I'm not comfortable with what that was, what that did to me.

00:18:11.380 --> 00:18:15.580
[Guest]: So that's where I'm saying that when you are a parentified kid, when you see dysfunction

00:18:15.580 --> 00:18:21.100
[Guest]: in family, and you're, but you are not smart enough to know that who is right, who is wrong.

00:18:21.100 --> 00:18:24.660
[Guest]: You're just a kid, but you have to take that responsibility.

00:18:24.660 --> 00:18:27.900
[Guest]: So you see that things are off.

00:18:27.900 --> 00:18:37.020
[Guest]: And that channelization is that you are responsible for like my, if I do well, my mom will feel

00:18:37.020 --> 00:18:38.020
[Guest]: happy.

00:18:38.020 --> 00:18:39.020
[Guest]: Right.

00:18:39.020 --> 00:18:40.020
[Guest]: So these things are happening.

00:18:40.020 --> 00:18:43.780
[Guest]: And the culmination was, you know, I remember the day I graduated from college and it was

00:18:43.780 --> 00:18:46.140
[Guest]: my convocation, right.

00:18:46.140 --> 00:18:50.740
[Guest]: That day when my mom told me that I think I was 21 when you graduate, I graduated, that

00:18:50.740 --> 00:18:56.580
[Guest]: like, and I, when I got my first check from the Hindu that, you know, like she felt she

00:18:56.580 --> 00:19:02.840
[Guest]: finally had agency because she had started earning because after, you know, she used

00:19:02.840 --> 00:19:04.960
[Guest]: to work at an office.

00:19:04.960 --> 00:19:09.760
[Guest]: It was a very, it was not a fancy job, but my mom, she just loved what she did.

00:19:09.760 --> 00:19:12.980
[Guest]: She proudly remembers that I used to do this.

00:19:12.980 --> 00:19:17.580
[Guest]: She would get a small salary, but, you know, used to spend it on others, not on herself.

00:19:17.580 --> 00:19:18.580
[Guest]: Right.

00:19:18.580 --> 00:19:24.300
[Guest]: So that sense of agency, when you see has gone away, right when, and my dad is the youngest.

00:19:24.300 --> 00:19:27.980
[Guest]: So, and again, it's a constructed story.

00:19:27.980 --> 00:19:33.300
[Guest]: So no, I just feel terrible because I don't want to paint like a, you know, a picture

00:19:33.300 --> 00:19:34.860
[Guest]: about other people in my family.

00:19:34.860 --> 00:19:35.860
[Guest]: That's not my objective.

00:19:35.860 --> 00:19:39.560
[Guest]: I'm just telling you what I felt, what I saw my mom going through.

00:19:39.560 --> 00:19:41.940
[Amit Varma]: And there are of course, multiple facets to the story.

00:19:41.940 --> 00:19:43.660
[Amit Varma]: It's not even a story about other people.

00:19:43.660 --> 00:19:46.900
[Guest]: It's a story about structures and society and just processes.

00:19:46.900 --> 00:19:47.900
[Guest]: Exactly.

00:19:47.900 --> 00:19:49.940
[Guest]: And, you know, and so all of that was happening.

00:19:49.940 --> 00:19:54.100
[Guest]: So, you know, to answer your question, yes, a lot of it, I was feeling back when I was

00:19:54.100 --> 00:19:59.460
[Guest]: growing up, but things started making, you know, you need to connect the dots that happened,

00:19:59.460 --> 00:20:02.060
[Guest]: I think, over the last four or five years.

00:20:02.060 --> 00:20:08.980
[Guest]: And I will end on this note on this question that, you know, the interesting thing about

00:20:08.980 --> 00:20:16.620
[Guest]: journaling is that when you dump your thoughts on paper, you also, and you are just honest

00:20:16.620 --> 00:20:17.700
[Guest]: when you are in your diary, right?

00:20:17.700 --> 00:20:19.580
[Guest]: Like no one is going to read my diary.

00:20:19.580 --> 00:20:21.660
[Guest]: So you're so brutally honest.

00:20:21.660 --> 00:20:28.820
[Guest]: So the discomforting thoughts about the present, right?

00:20:28.820 --> 00:20:35.580
[Guest]: About what happened in childhood, like that, you know, this, let me put it this way that

00:20:35.580 --> 00:20:40.180
[Guest]: I think a lot about as an individual, what is my relationship with society?

00:20:40.180 --> 00:20:42.020
[Guest]: What is, what do I owe to Amit Verma?

00:20:42.020 --> 00:20:43.020
[Guest]: Right?

00:20:43.020 --> 00:20:44.020
[Guest]: We are sitting next to each other.

00:20:44.020 --> 00:20:47.540
[Guest]: You know, I believe in individual as a center of society.

00:20:47.540 --> 00:20:50.900
[Guest]: That's my worldview and individual, individual freedom.

00:20:50.900 --> 00:20:56.020
[Guest]: But then I'm also a member of the society, but then my parents, right?

00:20:56.020 --> 00:20:57.980
[Guest]: That's a different sort of relationship.

00:20:57.980 --> 00:21:04.740
[Guest]: I can't, the way I would think about Amit Verma or say my best friend, the relationship

00:21:04.740 --> 00:21:06.420
[Guest]: with parents is different.

00:21:06.420 --> 00:21:08.580
[Guest]: So where does that agency come in?

00:21:08.580 --> 00:21:14.500
[Guest]: Because when I was growing up, my mom and how, you know, I remember, right?

00:21:14.500 --> 00:21:20.660
[Guest]: You know, it's almost like she gave in everything, but is that something I asked for?

00:21:20.660 --> 00:21:21.660
[Guest]: Right?

00:21:21.660 --> 00:21:24.620
[Guest]: You know, you get this question and it's, it's a very discomforting thought because

00:21:24.620 --> 00:21:31.980
[Guest]: today, how do you manifest that relationship when you are a child, when you're not an adult

00:21:31.980 --> 00:21:33.340
[Guest]: and now.

00:21:33.340 --> 00:21:35.700
[Guest]: So how do you think about your responsibility?

00:21:35.700 --> 00:21:37.660
[Guest]: What do you owe to your parents?

00:21:37.660 --> 00:21:41.380
[Guest]: I don't have answers, but this is the, this is the struggle.

00:21:41.380 --> 00:21:46.020
[Guest]: And this hit me for the first time when I went to college, like I thought that, you

00:21:46.020 --> 00:21:49.740
[Guest]: know, like for me, it was a dream, you know, to, to study at that Institute.

00:21:49.740 --> 00:21:55.620
[Guest]: And I think my years at IIT really shaped me in so many ways, but I went away from home,

00:21:55.620 --> 00:21:56.620
[Guest]: right?

00:21:56.620 --> 00:22:00.340
[Guest]: I went to Kanpur, my parents didn't realize that that will happen.

00:22:00.340 --> 00:22:03.780
[Guest]: They just thought it, it doesn't strike you, right?

00:22:03.780 --> 00:22:08.300
[Guest]: That like the kid will go away.

00:22:08.300 --> 00:22:12.060
[Guest]: So that left such a big void in my, you imagine, right?

00:22:12.060 --> 00:22:17.460
[Guest]: I mean, you do everything for 18 years for this one person, right?

00:22:17.460 --> 00:22:22.660
[Guest]: And my sister and I, you know, I joke with her that, I mean, I say you have a more comfortable

00:22:22.660 --> 00:22:27.460
[Guest]: life because you know, over the years, you know, the family prospered, but the love and

00:22:27.460 --> 00:22:32.980
[Guest]: affection I got, I feel, I mean, she would disagree that it was more because I'm the

00:22:32.980 --> 00:22:34.500
[Guest]: elder kid.

00:22:34.500 --> 00:22:41.420
[Guest]: So now when that creates this big void in her life, it changes things, right?

00:22:41.420 --> 00:22:47.060
[Guest]: And that had its own series of impressions that made me discomfort, you know, made me

00:22:47.060 --> 00:22:49.860
[Guest]: uncomfortable that, okay, what is happening?

00:22:49.860 --> 00:22:55.780
[Guest]: And now that, you know, I decided to live by myself, I don't live at my parents' house

00:22:55.780 --> 00:22:56.780
[Guest]: anymore.

00:22:56.780 --> 00:23:01.220
[Guest]: So that decision, you know, what would it mean for my parents, right?

00:23:01.220 --> 00:23:04.900
[Guest]: These are all questions that come to me and I am processing it in my journal.

00:23:04.900 --> 00:23:09.620
[Guest]: So again, that's, sorry, it's a long winding answer to your question, but I think, yeah,

00:23:09.620 --> 00:23:11.540
[Guest]: I realize it at that time.

00:23:11.540 --> 00:23:17.040
[Guest]: But now that I think about it, it has become such a central thing in organizing my life

00:23:17.040 --> 00:23:21.740
[Guest]: that I have to, I can't just ignore what happened in childhood, but then also think about what

00:23:21.740 --> 00:23:26.580
[Guest]: is happening in the present and then just find a way to navigate it.

00:23:26.580 --> 00:23:30.020
[Amit Varma]: And is this something you've spoken to your mom about or to your dad about, is it something

00:23:30.020 --> 00:23:34.860
[Amit Varma]: you can talk about or is a relationship sort of still in a groove, which is difficult to

00:23:34.860 --> 00:23:35.860
[Amit Varma]: break out of?

00:23:35.860 --> 00:23:37.340
[Guest]: So it's tricky.

00:23:37.340 --> 00:23:47.300
[Guest]: It's tricky because like, I don't know, because you see the tension, you know, so the sense

00:23:47.300 --> 00:23:52.780
[Guest]: that I always have had with them is that I say, you know, whatever I do, I love you.

00:23:52.780 --> 00:23:54.020
[Guest]: I care for you.

00:23:54.020 --> 00:23:56.420
[Guest]: I will always be there for you.

00:23:56.420 --> 00:24:04.740
[Guest]: But I have a life that is outside the idea of a family, right?

00:24:04.740 --> 00:24:10.980
[Guest]: Now how do you, and they understand, you know, I mean, the choices that I have been able

00:24:10.980 --> 00:24:13.460
[Guest]: to make, you know, I still don't have an answer to it.

00:24:13.460 --> 00:24:17.100
[Guest]: People keep asking me all the time, how did your parents react to X?

00:24:17.100 --> 00:24:20.420
[Guest]: You know, how did your parents react to Y?

00:24:20.420 --> 00:24:22.620
[Guest]: And is it because of them or is it because of you?

00:24:22.620 --> 00:24:24.700
[Guest]: I don't know.

00:24:24.700 --> 00:24:33.580
[Guest]: So I think they and I, we know what is going on, but, and there have been times when things

00:24:33.580 --> 00:24:40.100
[Guest]: go heated up and like we sit and we talk, but you know, it's almost like I realized

00:24:40.100 --> 00:24:43.860
[Guest]: after a while that look, both are right.

00:24:43.860 --> 00:24:47.380
[Guest]: You know, it's just worldviews are different.

00:24:47.380 --> 00:24:51.660
[Guest]: You know, they came from a certain background, they have a certain expectation.

00:24:51.660 --> 00:24:57.220
[Guest]: I grew up as a, you know, after like, after you leave home, you change.

00:24:57.220 --> 00:25:02.660
[Guest]: And after graduating from college, when I started reading, you know, reading just, it

00:25:02.660 --> 00:25:03.900
[Guest]: opens up the world for you.

00:25:03.900 --> 00:25:08.980
[Guest]: And that happened like, you know, the, since the time I started identifying myself as a

00:25:08.980 --> 00:25:11.300
[Guest]: reader, you know, the world changed for me, right?

00:25:11.300 --> 00:25:15.180
[Guest]: So your ideas expand, you just, you're just not the same person.

00:25:15.180 --> 00:25:19.020
[Guest]: So the trajectory of change, we went on different paths.

00:25:19.020 --> 00:25:24.340
[Guest]: And the problem is that, you know, within this giant family, like almost all my cousins,

00:25:24.340 --> 00:25:27.460
[Guest]: most of them, all of them are in family business, right?

00:25:27.460 --> 00:25:30.780
[Guest]: In my neighborhood, most of the kids are at home, right?

00:25:30.780 --> 00:25:36.580
[Guest]: That's how, that's how you're expected to be largely, you know, in the, in the zone

00:25:36.580 --> 00:25:40.540
[Guest]: of Delhi I come from, like, that's a norm, like people joke about it, you know, ki aisa

00:25:40.540 --> 00:25:41.940
[Guest]: hi hota hai.

00:25:41.940 --> 00:25:49.780
[Guest]: So when you see other kids around behaving just the way she would expect me to, right?

00:25:49.780 --> 00:25:57.820
[Guest]: But then she's also proud that he has an independent life and standing, something that she wanted,

00:25:57.820 --> 00:25:58.820
[Guest]: right?

00:25:58.820 --> 00:26:02.580
[Guest]: So I think she also has that conflict and I also have that conflict, right?

00:26:02.580 --> 00:26:03.620
[Guest]: So it's, it's there.

00:26:03.620 --> 00:26:10.460
[Guest]: So I don't, I mean, that conversation happens, but it's more of that, you know, to like something

00:26:10.460 --> 00:26:15.020
[Guest]: , something heated has happened, right?

00:26:15.020 --> 00:26:17.900
[Guest]: And you're trying to pacify it, right?

00:26:17.900 --> 00:26:23.180
[Guest]: And on an ongoing basis, I think she has, like, of course, like both of us have moved,

00:26:23.180 --> 00:26:24.180
[Guest]: you know?

00:26:24.180 --> 00:26:25.180
[Guest]: So I think, I don't know.

00:26:25.180 --> 00:26:29.180
[Guest]: I still sometimes feel like, like, I don't know the answer, honestly, Amit, that I don't

00:26:29.180 --> 00:26:30.180
[Guest]: know.

00:26:30.180 --> 00:26:34.900
[Guest]: And there've been other things that are too personal that I, I, you know, like, I, I don't

00:26:34.900 --> 00:26:38.820
[Guest]: have problems to share, but you know, it just feels like that's her story.

00:26:38.820 --> 00:26:40.740
[Guest]: And do, do I have the right to even tell it?

00:26:40.740 --> 00:26:41.740
[Guest]: I don't know.

00:26:41.740 --> 00:26:42.740
[Guest]: Right.

00:26:42.740 --> 00:26:48.660
[Guest]: They're like, there's so many, like, I've told you a lot, but I think there's this important

00:26:48.660 --> 00:26:52.820
[Guest]: things that I could not say, because I think I respect her privacy of things that I could

00:26:52.820 --> 00:26:54.660
[Guest]: say or I could not say.

00:26:54.660 --> 00:26:56.100
[Guest]: So that will remain the missing bit.

00:26:56.100 --> 00:27:01.700
[Guest]: But yeah, from my POV, I'm saying that it's, it's something that I've now accepted to live

00:27:01.700 --> 00:27:02.700
[Guest]: with.

00:27:02.700 --> 00:27:07.100
[Guest]: And I think my journaling is a way for me to build my own philosophy about, you know,

00:27:07.100 --> 00:27:08.980
[Guest]: also accept uncomfortable truths.

00:27:08.980 --> 00:27:13.980
[Guest]: And in all that, like, I think part of growing up is to realize that your parents are not

00:27:13.980 --> 00:27:14.980
[Guest]: always right.

00:27:14.980 --> 00:27:15.980
[Guest]: Right.

00:27:15.980 --> 00:27:20.620
[Guest]: They are as flawed humans as I am.

00:27:20.620 --> 00:27:28.020
[Guest]: So and in this whole mess, you just find a way to get through things and take hard decisions.

00:27:28.020 --> 00:27:29.780
[Guest]: You criticize yourself.

00:27:29.780 --> 00:27:35.380
[Guest]: So yeah, I am now at a fairly comfortable space in my head.

00:27:35.380 --> 00:27:38.900
[Guest]: I don't know what my parents think about it.

00:27:38.900 --> 00:27:40.260
[Guest]: Does that answer your question?

00:27:40.260 --> 00:27:46.660
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, it kind of illuminates a lot and also makes me very sad because I think and this

00:27:46.660 --> 00:27:50.500
[Amit Varma]: is not, you know, I mean, your story about your mom sparked this off.

00:27:50.500 --> 00:27:55.380
[Amit Varma]: But in general, this is, I think a lot of many Indian women that you don't have that

00:27:55.380 --> 00:27:59.020
[Amit Varma]: agency as a kid, then you get married, you lose that agency.

00:27:59.020 --> 00:28:02.420
[Amit Varma]: And then perhaps sometimes you seek a proxy.

00:28:02.420 --> 00:28:06.580
[Amit Varma]: And you know, and that could be your kids and you seek a proxy in your kids, but eventually

00:28:06.580 --> 00:28:07.580
[Unknown]: your kids go away.

00:28:07.580 --> 00:28:09.380
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, that's the nature of the world.

00:28:09.380 --> 00:28:10.380
[Amit Varma]: And then what do you do?

00:28:10.380 --> 00:28:13.540
[Amit Varma]: Do you, you know, how do you fill that particular void?

00:28:13.540 --> 00:28:17.580
[Amit Varma]: And this is not a specific question or something, I'm just kind of thinking aloud and wondering

00:28:17.580 --> 00:28:22.700
[Amit Varma]: because I don't think men in India sort of think about what the lives of the women in

00:28:22.700 --> 00:28:28.820
[Amit Varma]: India are like, right, it's, it's just to live a life without agency and to take refuge

00:28:28.820 --> 00:28:33.660
[Amit Varma]: in all of these things is like such a terrible, unspoken tragedy.

00:28:33.660 --> 00:28:36.700
[Guest]: And I see that around in my society, right?

00:28:36.700 --> 00:28:42.420
[Guest]: Because like, you know, when when I'm home, my mom tells me other stories about other

00:28:42.420 --> 00:28:44.740
[Guest]: women in the society, right?

00:28:44.740 --> 00:28:48.580
[Guest]: And it feels like everyone has the same story.

00:28:48.580 --> 00:28:49.580
[Guest]: Right?

00:28:49.580 --> 00:28:53.840
[Guest]: There's some neighbors who I'm sure they're not going to listen to this podcast.

00:28:53.840 --> 00:28:58.220
[Guest]: So I can just tell you that they are like super rich, like super rich, you know, they

00:28:58.220 --> 00:29:04.220
[Guest]: built a business and they just have now this really fancy house in our society.

00:29:04.220 --> 00:29:12.940
[Guest]: And what such deeply unhappy lives of women in that house, right?

00:29:12.940 --> 00:29:18.220
[Guest]: I know details because my mom told me and you see the, you know, the way, you know,

00:29:18.220 --> 00:29:23.780
[Guest]: in the evening when my mom and her friends, they just get together, right?

00:29:23.780 --> 00:29:27.900
[Guest]: These are the conversations that are happening that you know, how it's just that and I think,

00:29:27.900 --> 00:29:31.660
[Guest]: you know, Amit, and this is the thing that my sister has learned from all of this, right?

00:29:31.660 --> 00:29:36.540
[Guest]: That how, why financial independence matters so much because at the end of the day, right?

00:29:36.540 --> 00:29:42.340
[Guest]: Like, where do you go is the question that hits you, right?

00:29:42.340 --> 00:29:47.180
[Guest]: Like that's the lever through which lever of control in a way that you don't have independent

00:29:47.180 --> 00:29:51.700
[Guest]: agency, like economically, like you can't do anything.

00:29:51.700 --> 00:29:58.700
[Guest]: And that way, again, you know, I, at one point, you know, this whole thing about, she said,

00:29:58.700 --> 00:30:04.740
[Guest]: now that you've started earning, I have started earning that sense that, you know, you, you

00:30:04.740 --> 00:30:09.060
[Guest]: get that feeling that now I have become independent.

00:30:09.060 --> 00:30:14.700
[Guest]: So you know, in that way, I think that the factor of not, the factor of, you know, not

00:30:14.700 --> 00:30:18.540
[Guest]: having an independent source of income becomes a lever of control.

00:30:18.540 --> 00:30:22.100
[Guest]: And you know, all of that, Amit, when I started reporting and I was reporting on this data

00:30:22.100 --> 00:30:27.940
[Guest]: on suicides and I saw that I always heard about narratives about farmer suicides, but

00:30:27.940 --> 00:30:34.100
[Guest]: every year farmers and housewives compete among who has the highest number, right?

00:30:34.100 --> 00:30:40.660
[Guest]: And I think it was in 2017 when I saw that statistic and I was blown away because it

00:30:40.660 --> 00:30:46.260
[Guest]: just explains for me, at least that there could be hundreds of reasons why what is happening

00:30:46.260 --> 00:30:52.220
[Guest]: for my limited personal vantage of what I saw growing up in, not in my home, I'm saying

00:30:52.220 --> 00:30:58.340
[Guest]: in my neighborhood, in my society, where I grew up.

00:30:58.340 --> 00:31:02.820
[Guest]: That was a sense I was getting that it was so, the frustration that I could see in my

00:31:02.820 --> 00:31:07.620
[Guest]: house around me, that what it could lead to, you don't know, right?

00:31:07.620 --> 00:31:12.420
[Guest]: And you can't even talk about it, like in a party, I would see, not a party as in like

00:31:12.420 --> 00:31:17.860
[Guest]: a family gathering, every, every family is happy, right, everyone is happy, but you know,

00:31:17.860 --> 00:31:22.780
[Guest]: you go on one on one and then you see that the story is different.

00:31:22.780 --> 00:31:26.500
[Guest]: And things that happen in college, you know, when you get heart to heart with your friends,

00:31:26.500 --> 00:31:30.340
[Guest]: you know, different, like one of the best things about IIT is that you meet people from

00:31:30.340 --> 00:31:32.340
[Guest]: all across the country, right?

00:31:32.340 --> 00:31:37.340
[Guest]: In an environment, you grew up in Delhi, I told you, it's a small homogeneous, you know,

00:31:37.340 --> 00:31:41.820
[Guest]: community in school, everyone is from five kilometers and then you go to a college, kids

00:31:41.820 --> 00:31:48.700
[Guest]: from all cast, class, states, languages, and then you go heart to heart with friends.

00:31:48.700 --> 00:31:52.540
[Guest]: And then you see the same story, you know, and those are also the people with whom you

00:31:52.540 --> 00:31:54.260
[Guest]: deeply connect.

00:31:54.260 --> 00:32:00.340
[Guest]: Because you say, huh, you know, they get it, they get where we are coming from.

00:32:00.340 --> 00:32:04.340
[Guest]: So yeah, I think it's, it's, it's just so generic.

00:32:04.340 --> 00:32:09.020
[Guest]: And honestly, I think all of these questions have such a, now that we have spoken about

00:32:09.020 --> 00:32:12.380
[Guest]: it, it has had a big impact on how I think about the world.

00:32:12.380 --> 00:32:17.820
[Guest]: Because it just makes you, yeah, you know, the whole thing about what looks at the surface,

00:32:17.820 --> 00:32:22.220
[Guest]: you know, like now it's, it's, let me put it this way, when I see, it's a very weird

00:32:22.220 --> 00:32:23.220
[Guest]: thing to say.

00:32:23.220 --> 00:32:27.620
[Guest]: But when I see someone who is like extremely happy, you know, like he is very happy, he

00:32:27.620 --> 00:32:32.020
[Guest]: keeps laughing all the time, you know, I feel this, there's some, there's some problem

00:32:32.020 --> 00:32:33.020
[Amit Varma]: here.

00:32:33.020 --> 00:32:34.020
[Guest]: Why are you smiling so much?

00:32:34.020 --> 00:32:41.140
[Guest]: Yeah, it's like, you know, they have a backstory, you know, and, and now more that, now that

00:32:41.140 --> 00:32:45.580
[Guest]: I'm a journalist, you know, and I want to explore, you know, lives of people, it's like,

00:32:45.580 --> 00:32:51.820
[Guest]: I just wonder, I don't know, it's a, I feel happy that they're happy in the moment.

00:32:51.820 --> 00:32:55.860
[Guest]: But the question is in my mind, okay, what is their story like, you know, like, you know,

00:32:55.860 --> 00:33:01.020
[Guest]: the way you are asking me about my story, like, and I can't just go and talk to a random

00:33:01.020 --> 00:33:05.980
[Guest]: person and say, you know, but yeah, I think that has started happening.

00:33:05.980 --> 00:33:09.620
[Guest]: Because again, just to diverge in college, when all of this was happening, there was

00:33:09.620 --> 00:33:14.300
[Guest]: a moment I had to take a semester drop in my college because of something at home.

00:33:14.300 --> 00:33:18.780
[Guest]: And that phase, I went into that direction where I thought there is no such thing as

00:33:18.780 --> 00:33:19.780
[Guest]: happiness.

00:33:19.780 --> 00:33:25.020
[Guest]: Either you are unhappy, you are in the shades of unhappiness, that's it, there is no such

00:33:25.020 --> 00:33:26.740
[Guest]: thing as happiness.

00:33:26.740 --> 00:33:28.940
[Guest]: So for now, I don't think like that.

00:33:28.940 --> 00:33:33.660
[Guest]: But I'm saying that when all of these impressions build up, and you say, my friends even don't

00:33:33.660 --> 00:33:36.940
[Guest]: know about what is happening behind the scenes.

00:33:36.940 --> 00:33:43.420
[Guest]: So maybe something is happening behind the scenes with them that I don't know, right?

00:33:43.420 --> 00:33:47.020
[Guest]: So that way, you know, this started happening that there's always a deeper life, you know,

00:33:47.020 --> 00:33:48.320
[Guest]: I don't know what is happening.

00:33:48.320 --> 00:33:53.620
[Guest]: So even now today, you know, if I don't like a person, right, or I'm disagreeing with them,

00:33:53.620 --> 00:33:58.100
[Guest]: or I don't like, then you know, I just feel there's a part of me which is like, you know,

00:33:58.100 --> 00:34:02.980
[Guest]: what I don't know is, what is his story, you know, there is, you know, he is arguing like

00:34:02.980 --> 00:34:07.220
[Guest]: this, you know, and like, why does he or she have these views, but then a part of me tells,

00:34:07.220 --> 00:34:12.380
[Guest]: but you know, I don't know, like, what happened to their childhood, what has made them the

00:34:12.380 --> 00:34:14.340
[Guest]: way they are today.

00:34:14.340 --> 00:34:19.260
[Guest]: So I think, yeah, so long story short, I'm saying that the threads that I observed in

00:34:19.260 --> 00:34:23.740
[Guest]: my own journey now today as a journalist, somehow it impacts you because it just changes

00:34:23.740 --> 00:34:29.340
[Guest]: the way you look at people around you, and how you think about them, and the world.

00:34:29.340 --> 00:34:33.220
[Amit Varma]: And I'm just wondering from this, like what you said about, you know, initially, when

00:34:33.220 --> 00:34:37.540
[Amit Varma]: you go to school, sab 5 kilometer ke radius mein hai, then you go to college, it expands

00:34:37.540 --> 00:34:39.500
[Amit Varma]: a bit, you meet different kinds of people.

00:34:39.500 --> 00:34:43.380
[Amit Varma]: And there you make connections, where you make connections, and you find these common

00:34:43.380 --> 00:34:47.000
[Amit Varma]: threads, even though you could be from different places, different backgrounds.

00:34:47.000 --> 00:34:54.020
[Amit Varma]: And I'm wondering here about being the importance and dangers of transcending the limits of

00:34:54.020 --> 00:34:58.700
[Amit Varma]: geography, which we can more or less do in these current times, like earlier, in an earlier

00:34:58.700 --> 00:35:04.140
[Amit Varma]: age, like when I grew up in the 80s, for example, you're sort of limited by circumstance and

00:35:04.140 --> 00:35:10.100
[Amit Varma]: geography, you only know so many people, you know, and your circles may expand sometimes,

00:35:10.100 --> 00:35:13.380
[Amit Varma]: and sometimes they may not like you point out many of your school friends are still

00:35:13.380 --> 00:35:16.420
[Amit Varma]: living in the same place working in the family business.

00:35:16.420 --> 00:35:22.300
[Amit Varma]: And the good part of the circle expanding is that you can find like your sample size

00:35:22.300 --> 00:35:26.940
[Amit Varma]: of people with whom you could empathize with or learn something from or find that common

00:35:26.940 --> 00:35:31.340
[Amit Varma]: thread, that sample size grows up and those connections matter.

00:35:31.340 --> 00:35:32.620
[Amit Varma]: Because then you know, you're not alone.

00:35:32.620 --> 00:35:35.420
[Amit Varma]: These are common experiences and those connections matter.

00:35:35.420 --> 00:35:39.680
[Amit Varma]: The internet can do the same thing, even the act of reading can do the same thing by giving

00:35:39.680 --> 00:35:43.140
[Amit Varma]: you access to the lives and minds of others.

00:35:43.140 --> 00:35:46.380
[Amit Varma]: So that's one strand of it where it works.

00:35:46.380 --> 00:35:52.820
[Amit Varma]: But another strand is that even in this hyper connected world, we can sometimes choose to

00:35:52.820 --> 00:35:53.820
[Amit Varma]: be atomized.

00:35:53.820 --> 00:35:58.420
[Amit Varma]: Ki chaar log baithe hain kafe mein lekin ek doosra se baat nahi kar rahe hain, phone mein

00:35:58.420 --> 00:35:59.420
[Amit Varma]: dekh rahe hain.

00:35:59.420 --> 00:36:04.340
[Amit Varma]: You know, to instead of embracing the concrete interactions, where you can look into someone's

00:36:04.340 --> 00:36:08.260
[Amit Varma]: eye and have a conversation and say ki bhai kya baat hai, you're not looking good today.

00:36:08.260 --> 00:36:12.740
[Amit Varma]: You are instead trapped in the abstract worlds of the smartphone, which make you which give

00:36:12.740 --> 00:36:18.460
[Amit Varma]: this illusion of being connected and which give this illusion that you're gaining knowledge.

00:36:18.460 --> 00:36:20.300
[Amit Varma]: But those are on the surface.

00:36:20.300 --> 00:36:23.620
[Amit Varma]: So I mean, I'm just kind of thinking aloud is sparked off by what you said about, you

00:36:23.620 --> 00:36:27.780
[Amit Varma]: know, expanding those circles, going to college meeting those people.

00:36:27.780 --> 00:36:32.220
[Amit Varma]: And I think there are those trade offs, you know, it is possible that many of the self

00:36:32.220 --> 00:36:36.780
[Amit Varma]: doubts you might have or regrets you might have may not have been there if you had continued

00:36:36.780 --> 00:36:41.620
[Amit Varma]: living in that cocooned world in a pre internet time ki aap bhi chalo family business mein

00:36:41.620 --> 00:36:46.700
[Amit Varma]: kaam bata rahe ho, math mein achche ho, accounts dekh rahe ho aap and so on and so forth.

00:36:46.700 --> 00:36:50.420
[Amit Varma]: But on the other hand, there is this sort of expansiveness.

00:36:50.420 --> 00:36:51.980
[Amit Varma]: So what are sort of your thoughts on this?

00:36:51.980 --> 00:36:56.820
[Guest]: Yeah, so I read somewhere forgetting the author, but that there's a difference between connection

00:36:56.820 --> 00:36:57.820
[Guest]: and conversation.

00:36:57.820 --> 00:36:58.820
[Guest]: Right?

00:36:58.820 --> 00:37:05.540
[Guest]: So a connection is, I'm on Instagram and you know, someone posts posts and Instagram story

00:37:05.540 --> 00:37:08.140
[Guest]: and I send an emoji in reaction.

00:37:08.140 --> 00:37:10.580
[Guest]: So I'm connected.

00:37:10.580 --> 00:37:15.540
[Guest]: You know, someone I met seven years ago, we are in touch once in a while you can.

00:37:15.540 --> 00:37:17.540
[Guest]: Conversation is where you go deep, right?

00:37:17.540 --> 00:37:24.220
[Guest]: And what has happened with me over the last, I would say, I don't know, maybe, I don't

00:37:24.220 --> 00:37:30.940
[Guest]: know the time frame, but I just realized the value of deep relationships, especially friendships.

00:37:30.940 --> 00:37:31.940
[Guest]: Right?

00:37:31.940 --> 00:37:37.980
[Guest]: There was now, you know, I'm so proud that I have a bunch of four or five people in my

00:37:37.980 --> 00:37:43.060
[Guest]: life, you know, and they come from different time frames, like one from like a friend of

00:37:43.060 --> 00:37:44.060
[Guest]: mine.

00:37:44.060 --> 00:37:50.420
[Guest]: We went, we studied together since kindergarten, couple of friends from college, someone whom

00:37:50.420 --> 00:37:53.380
[Guest]: I met at workplace.

00:37:53.380 --> 00:37:54.580
[Guest]: So different.

00:37:54.580 --> 00:38:01.420
[Guest]: So they know different, we are connected to in different time, like they knew the different

00:38:01.420 --> 00:38:06.420
[Guest]: summer at different points, but they know today, like who I am, they know the trajectory

00:38:06.420 --> 00:38:10.180
[Guest]: and they know my deepest anxieties, they know who I am, what I do.

00:38:10.180 --> 00:38:14.180
[Guest]: And it doesn't, it, it, it, it doesn't happen by itself.

00:38:14.180 --> 00:38:18.340
[Guest]: You know, you, you make that effort, you know, when you say in a relationship, you have to

00:38:18.340 --> 00:38:22.340
[Guest]: put in an effort to cultivate those deep relationships.

00:38:22.340 --> 00:38:28.020
[Guest]: That's where you find for me, like most meaning in terms of interpersonal relationships.

00:38:28.020 --> 00:38:32.900
[Guest]: And in general, like, you know, it's funny because as a reporter, you have to be an extrovert.

00:38:32.900 --> 00:38:39.780
[Guest]: Like I describe my job as, you know, I'm consistently invading people's private lives, right?

00:38:39.780 --> 00:38:44.300
[Guest]: There was a story for which I just, you know, you land up at someone's house, unannounced,

00:38:44.300 --> 00:38:46.740
[Guest]: knock the door that I want to talk to you, right?

00:38:46.740 --> 00:38:49.380
[Guest]: So that's, that, that's my reporting.

00:38:49.380 --> 00:38:54.220
[Guest]: When I'm reporting, I'm that person, but in my private life, I'm very introvert, right?

00:38:54.220 --> 00:38:59.420
[Guest]: You know, like I'm the guy in a party would ideally like to stand in the corner.

00:38:59.420 --> 00:39:05.780
[Guest]: If I like someone, you know, then I will, okay, no, let's chat that kind of a personality,

00:39:05.780 --> 00:39:06.780
[Guest]: right?

00:39:06.780 --> 00:39:13.300
[Guest]: So when you become that person, you just want, you don't want a lot of people to have, like,

00:39:13.300 --> 00:39:16.860
[Guest]: I'm happy to go to a cafe and actually not talk to anyone.

00:39:16.860 --> 00:39:23.380
[Guest]: But if I want to, and if there is a connection, then, you know, I want to take it from a connection

00:39:23.380 --> 00:39:24.860
[Guest]: to a conversation.

00:39:24.860 --> 00:39:30.060
[Guest]: And one of my recent realizations, you know, that I figured is that when you find someone

00:39:30.060 --> 00:39:34.780
[Guest]: like that, you know, where you, there is a connection based on values, not on anything

00:39:34.780 --> 00:39:37.900
[Guest]: else, just ways to look at the world.

00:39:37.900 --> 00:39:44.020
[Guest]: And I like the person, then I don't want to lose them, you know, because it's hard to

00:39:44.020 --> 00:39:47.060
[Guest]: just find those people organically.

00:39:47.060 --> 00:39:50.980
[Guest]: And interestingly, all of the friends that I have, then none of them are internet friends.

00:39:50.980 --> 00:39:55.460
[Guest]: They're like my, I met them in a physical place.

00:39:55.460 --> 00:39:58.740
[Guest]: You know, I can, they're happy, you can, they just call me up.

00:39:58.740 --> 00:39:59.740
[Guest]: Right?

00:39:59.740 --> 00:40:04.820
[Guest]: I mean, I really, you know, it's just the, I don't know, I just, I'm a bit old school,

00:40:04.820 --> 00:40:09.820
[Guest]: but you know, this whole thing about friends sending me a calendar invite for scheduling

00:40:09.820 --> 00:40:13.620
[Guest]: a call, it is just insane.

00:40:13.620 --> 00:40:20.780
[Guest]: I just tell them, call me, I mean, you know, if I'm working, I will just tell you I'm busy.

00:40:20.780 --> 00:40:21.780
[Guest]: I will call you later.

00:40:21.780 --> 00:40:26.860
[Guest]: You know, in, when I was a kid and we didn't have mobile phones, we had our landline, so

00:40:26.860 --> 00:40:34.020
[Guest]: I put it up at 7.30, you know, and I anticipated it, right?

00:40:34.020 --> 00:40:39.140
[Guest]: So that, or sometimes randomly you just call, so at least there is this group of people

00:40:39.140 --> 00:40:42.260
[Guest]: who can just say, you know, like recently one of those friends, we have been talking

00:40:42.260 --> 00:40:48.620
[Guest]: a lot and he would just say that, can we talk, I really want to, something is going on and

00:40:48.620 --> 00:40:52.660
[Guest]: like work is work, but then you make time to talk to this person, right?

00:40:52.660 --> 00:40:58.700
[Guest]: So I'm saying that conversation, connection, so few conversations and then ignore connections

00:40:58.700 --> 00:41:00.780
[Guest]: is the frame that I have now.

00:41:00.780 --> 00:41:01.780
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:41:01.780 --> 00:41:02.780
[Amit Varma]: It's a, it's a lovely frame.

00:41:02.780 --> 00:41:07.380
[Amit Varma]: It's given me a lot to think about, you know, when I was going through all of your work,

00:41:07.380 --> 00:41:12.300
[Amit Varma]: the common thread that what I seem to notice in that is that you're living what I would

00:41:12.300 --> 00:41:17.020
[Amit Varma]: call the examined life, like Socrates once said, the unexamined life is not worth living,

00:41:17.020 --> 00:41:18.020
[Amit Varma]: right?

00:41:18.020 --> 00:41:22.180
[Amit Varma]: So what you're doing is you're asking questions all the time, whether they are questions about

00:41:22.180 --> 00:41:27.020
[Amit Varma]: media, whether they're questions about data, and we'll go into all of those also, or whether

00:41:27.020 --> 00:41:29.780
[Amit Varma]: they are questions about yourself.

00:41:29.780 --> 00:41:36.660
[Amit Varma]: And what you've sort of brought up here is the subject of intentionality that you decide

00:41:36.660 --> 00:41:40.100
[Amit Varma]: ki mujhe yeh friendship pe kaam karna hai.

00:41:40.100 --> 00:41:45.180
[Amit Varma]: And that's something I've been thinking about in the sense that, you know, earlier you spoke

00:41:45.180 --> 00:41:49.700
[Amit Varma]: about that natural empathy you discovered within yourself when you were a kid.

00:41:49.700 --> 00:41:53.540
[Amit Varma]: And we were also speaking about happiness and unhappiness, though I forget the context

00:41:53.540 --> 00:42:02.420
[Amit Varma]: now, but there is, it seems to me that in the natural flow of things, to feel empathy

00:42:02.420 --> 00:42:08.020
[Amit Varma]: or to feel unhappiness can sometimes be an act of self aggrandizement, where you put

00:42:08.020 --> 00:42:10.300
[Amit Varma]: yourself in the center of the universe.

00:42:10.300 --> 00:42:13.080
[Amit Varma]: So you are unhappy because bad things have happened to you.

00:42:13.080 --> 00:42:17.100
[Amit Varma]: And you feel empathy for someone because you are so virtuous, and I am good, I am feeling

00:42:17.100 --> 00:42:20.000
[Amit Varma]: empathy, main kuch karunga, right?

00:42:20.000 --> 00:42:26.620
[Amit Varma]: And what self examination does is, firstly, it forces you to see it for what it is.

00:42:26.620 --> 00:42:31.100
[Amit Varma]: And to say ki nahi, you know, maybe there's a if there's a practical value to the empathy,

00:42:31.100 --> 00:42:36.820
[Amit Varma]: then I will help this other person, instead of, you know, sort of delving in that empathy,

00:42:36.820 --> 00:42:42.260
[Amit Varma]: or, you know, if the because unhappiness and happiness, you spoke about how happiness is

00:42:42.260 --> 00:42:45.940
[Amit Varma]: can feel so nebulous, right, at one point, you thought there is nothing called happiness.

00:42:45.940 --> 00:42:51.100
[Amit Varma]: And I sometimes think about how you are, you can only construct happiness, you know, in

00:42:51.100 --> 00:42:55.060
[Amit Varma]: a you'll remember moment, like I remember moments in my life as happy moments.

00:42:55.060 --> 00:42:58.460
[Amit Varma]: Now, if you ask me happy moment kya tha, I'll say ye tha, wo tha.

00:42:58.460 --> 00:43:03.420
[Amit Varma]: But in the moment was I truly happy, right, you know, and for me to be truly happy in

00:43:03.420 --> 00:43:08.020
[Amit Varma]: the moment, I'm wondering if I would have had to tell myself in that moment that I am

00:43:08.020 --> 00:43:11.100
[Amit Varma]: happy, therefore taking myself out of that moment.

00:43:11.100 --> 00:43:15.980
[Amit Varma]: So this is sort of a kind of a conundrum to me, but what, you know, one of my guests in

00:43:15.980 --> 00:43:21.340
[Amit Varma]: a previous episode had mentioned how she decided when she was young to be happy.

00:43:21.340 --> 00:43:26.300
[Amit Varma]: She said when I was in school, I decided I am going to be happy, you know, and that act

00:43:26.300 --> 00:43:31.460
[Amit Varma]: of intentionality seems important, where you also decide ki, I want good friends with whom

00:43:31.460 --> 00:43:34.300
[Amit Varma]: I can have a conversation or a connection.

00:43:34.300 --> 00:43:40.380
[Amit Varma]: And when I identify someone like that, I will make sure it happens, you know, that intentionality

00:43:40.380 --> 00:43:41.380
[Amit Varma]: is there.

00:43:41.380 --> 00:43:46.940
[Amit Varma]: So is this, you know, and I don't, I don't often see it in myself, like the way I see

00:43:46.940 --> 00:43:52.580
[Amit Varma]: myself as having lived my life is ki bas mein through circumstances and whatever mein groove

00:43:52.580 --> 00:43:58.220
[Amit Varma]: mein baith gaya, ussi groove pe chalta gaya, accidents hote gaye, random cheeze hote gaye,

00:43:58.220 --> 00:44:02.180
[Amit Varma]: and I kind of land up and once in a while, I might do some self reflection and even that

00:44:02.180 --> 00:44:06.740
[Amit Varma]: can be an act of self aggrandizement, right, ki aarey, I'm doing self reflection and whatever.

00:44:06.740 --> 00:44:13.580
[Amit Varma]: Whereas in your case, it seems that whether by thinking about it, or whether through practices

00:44:13.580 --> 00:44:17.820
[Amit Varma]: like journaling, where you're forcing yourself to kind of examine yourself, that you worked

00:44:17.820 --> 00:44:19.300
[Amit Varma]: at it in a more systematic way.

00:44:19.300 --> 00:44:23.980
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a little bit about this that, you know, can self awareness also be then an act

00:44:23.980 --> 00:44:28.980
[Amit Varma]: of intention ki mujhe yeh karna hai, so journaling being a part of that, or is it part of your

00:44:28.980 --> 00:44:32.700
[Amit Varma]: basic nature that you're always getting meta and questioning these things?

00:44:32.700 --> 00:44:35.900
[Guest]: Or is it something you've tried to cultivate?

00:44:35.900 --> 00:44:37.940
[Guest]: So so I'll tell you.

00:44:37.940 --> 00:44:42.540
[Guest]: So I think there are two phases to this one, I think it's pre actually three phases.

00:44:42.540 --> 00:44:46.140
[Guest]: One is pre graduation, you know, school IIT.

00:44:46.140 --> 00:44:50.700
[Guest]: And then I think from 2016 to I think 2018-19.

00:44:50.700 --> 00:44:56.420
[Guest]: So I left my job at the Hindustan Times in January 2019, you know, just before the Republic

00:44:56.420 --> 00:44:57.420
[Guest]: Day.

00:44:57.420 --> 00:44:59.180
[Guest]: And then I have my third life.

00:44:59.180 --> 00:45:03.980
[Guest]: I mean, I don't want to say third life, but a third phase, you know, sorry.

00:45:03.980 --> 00:45:08.140
[Guest]: And where you know, I was outside, you know, it just changed.

00:45:08.140 --> 00:45:11.900
[Guest]: I mean, you have gone from being a by yourself, right?

00:45:11.900 --> 00:45:15.340
[Guest]: It just changes you like work is no more the center of what you are.

00:45:15.340 --> 00:45:17.580
[Guest]: So I had a lot of time to just think.

00:45:17.580 --> 00:45:19.740
[Guest]: And I you know, I say that I actually have a very boring life.

00:45:19.740 --> 00:45:22.380
[Guest]: I just sit, read, write and think.

00:45:22.380 --> 00:45:23.380
[Guest]: That's it.

00:45:23.380 --> 00:45:25.300
[Guest]: You know, there's nothing happening apart from this.

00:45:25.300 --> 00:45:31.100
[Guest]: So when you have so much time by yourself, you know, and it also some sometimes feels

00:45:31.100 --> 00:45:35.820
[Guest]: narcissistic that, you know, there is so much to understand in the world, you are just sitting

00:45:35.820 --> 00:45:36.820
[Unknown]: and analyzing yourself.

00:45:36.820 --> 00:45:41.260
[Guest]: But, you know, but what intention, you know, so the intention thing came.

00:45:41.260 --> 00:45:42.700
[Guest]: I don't know the roots of it.

00:45:42.700 --> 00:45:49.340
[Guest]: I remember during school, during college, these thoughts have always been with me.

00:45:49.340 --> 00:45:55.020
[Guest]: The structure came in the recent years, you know, where like again to talk about journaling,

00:45:55.020 --> 00:45:56.900
[Guest]: you know, one of the best things about it.

00:45:56.900 --> 00:45:59.820
[Guest]: Now I capture every single thought in my head on notebook.

00:45:59.820 --> 00:46:02.460
[Guest]: You know, I'm walking and I get a thought.

00:46:02.460 --> 00:46:03.840
[Guest]: It could be an idea.

00:46:03.840 --> 00:46:04.840
[Guest]: It could be an observation.

00:46:04.840 --> 00:46:09.780
[Guest]: So if I'm walking, I just quickly dump it on my note taking app on my phone.

00:46:09.780 --> 00:46:12.580
[Guest]: I don't want because what what it does.

00:46:12.580 --> 00:46:17.300
[Guest]: And I realized this that if things are in my head, and I don't capture it, then you

00:46:17.300 --> 00:46:20.020
[Guest]: know, it just it keeps lingering around.

00:46:20.020 --> 00:46:23.860
[Guest]: But if it's on paper, then it goes away like my brain is clear.

00:46:23.860 --> 00:46:30.660
[Guest]: So there is I just want to dump my brain and have it, you know, my brain should be empty.

00:46:30.660 --> 00:46:37.180
[Guest]: You know, and the more things start appearing on paper, I can do time travel.

00:46:37.180 --> 00:46:41.300
[Guest]: You know, so whenever so every year on my birthday, I read all my journals, just to

00:46:41.300 --> 00:46:45.380
[Guest]: see, okay, you know, what has changed?

00:46:45.380 --> 00:46:46.380
[Guest]: What has stayed the same?

00:46:46.380 --> 00:46:48.780
[Guest]: What are the questions I've been able to answer?

00:46:48.780 --> 00:46:50.700
[Guest]: What are the questions that remain open?

00:46:50.700 --> 00:46:53.900
[Guest]: And it just gives me this deep sense of progress.

00:46:53.900 --> 00:46:55.540
[Guest]: And you know, it's just brilliant.

00:46:55.540 --> 00:46:59.300
[Guest]: You know, I think I tell everyone that they should journal it's life changing.

00:46:59.300 --> 00:47:06.700
[Guest]: So when vast intentionality because you see a chameleon, you know, if this is constant,

00:47:06.700 --> 00:47:09.340
[Guest]: this is something I want, I want to do this.

00:47:09.340 --> 00:47:13.620
[Guest]: So that is where, you know, this intention thing started coming in.

00:47:13.620 --> 00:47:19.300
[Guest]: And also, parallelly, you know, this absurdity of modern life with technology, right, which

00:47:19.300 --> 00:47:25.460
[Guest]: has taken over, you know, our, you know, platforms and smartphone, you know, you can't totally

00:47:25.460 --> 00:47:27.060
[Guest]: escape it.

00:47:27.060 --> 00:47:28.540
[Guest]: But you have to live with it.

00:47:28.540 --> 00:47:33.380
[Guest]: And there, actually, even while I was reporting on platforms, you start seeing what they do

00:47:33.380 --> 00:47:34.660
[Guest]: to you.

00:47:34.660 --> 00:47:39.580
[Guest]: And then you realize that actually, I have to fight this, this whole attention economy

00:47:39.580 --> 00:47:40.580
[Guest]: thing.

00:47:40.580 --> 00:47:45.980
[Guest]: That's actually one of my I describe my work as a fight against the attention economy.

00:47:45.980 --> 00:47:50.540
[Guest]: I don't agree with it, and I have to fight it.

00:47:50.540 --> 00:47:55.260
[Guest]: Because the attention economy is trying to manipulate me to do things I don't want to

00:47:55.260 --> 00:47:56.260
[Guest]: do.

00:47:56.260 --> 00:47:59.500
[Guest]: And that sense of I mean, I don't know if there is a free will or not, I don't have

00:47:59.500 --> 00:48:00.820
[Guest]: an answer to that question.

00:48:00.820 --> 00:48:08.220
[Guest]: But you know, to the extent I can say that, you know, I want to do this, now, I have to

00:48:08.220 --> 00:48:09.220
[Guest]: make it happen.

00:48:09.220 --> 00:48:10.220
[Guest]: I think that came from journaling.

00:48:10.220 --> 00:48:12.740
[Guest]: Like, last year, I took an eight month sabbatical.

00:48:12.740 --> 00:48:13.740
[Guest]: Okay.

00:48:13.740 --> 00:48:18.700
[Guest]: And I was thinking for a long time that I want a sabbatical, I want to study stats,

00:48:18.700 --> 00:48:21.980
[Guest]: like a good math undergrad student, I was not getting the time.

00:48:21.980 --> 00:48:25.980
[Guest]: Because as a reporter, you know, you're always thinking about story ideas.

00:48:25.980 --> 00:48:29.020
[Guest]: It's that it's a drug, you know, reporting is a drug, you always want to report.

00:48:29.020 --> 00:48:30.500
[Guest]: So how did I come up with it?

00:48:30.500 --> 00:48:35.300
[Guest]: So I saw in my diary that, you know, how many times I'm writing that, you know, I used to

00:48:35.300 --> 00:48:39.500
[Guest]: say I want a zero story moment, where there shouldn't be a story in my mind.

00:48:39.500 --> 00:48:41.620
[Guest]: I want to eliminate everything.

00:48:41.620 --> 00:48:46.140
[Guest]: So you start and I took a sabbatical and then two months later, COVID second wave hit, right?

00:48:46.140 --> 00:48:51.300
[Guest]: And then my mind is like, no, my responsibility as a reporter is to go out and report, you

00:48:51.300 --> 00:48:57.580
[Guest]: know, that sense of, but I was like, nahi, abhi, I have decided, you know, that I have

00:48:57.580 --> 00:49:00.460
[Guest]: to study, I have to take the sabbatical.

00:49:00.460 --> 00:49:01.460
[Guest]: So stick to it.

00:49:01.460 --> 00:49:05.620
[Guest]: Don't let your whatever impulses, good, bad doesn't matter.

00:49:05.620 --> 00:49:06.620
[Guest]: Stick to it.

00:49:06.620 --> 00:49:11.020
[Guest]: So I think, and the more you practice it, you see the effect.

00:49:11.020 --> 00:49:17.620
[Guest]: So now when I go for my regular walks and I'm like, I'm walking, so I live in the hills

00:49:17.620 --> 00:49:22.060
[Guest]: now and I'm looking at mountains.

00:49:22.060 --> 00:49:27.420
[Guest]: I mean, I don't know, it may sound weird, but you know, I have these, on a daily basis,

00:49:27.420 --> 00:49:32.560
[Guest]: I have moments when there is nothing in my head, you know, it's like, you know, the sense

00:49:32.560 --> 00:49:36.380
[Guest]: of emptiness that I'm not thinking about anything.

00:49:36.380 --> 00:49:42.620
[Guest]: I'm just standing, looking at a hill, and one day I just started smiling, you know,

00:49:42.620 --> 00:49:45.260
[Guest]: for reasons I don't know.

00:49:45.260 --> 00:49:50.380
[Guest]: It is just a feeling that you have to experience that aapke dimaag mein kuch nahi hai, you

00:49:50.380 --> 00:49:55.020
[Guest]: are standing, there's no one around, like no one knows you, you know, you're not even

00:49:55.020 --> 00:49:56.020
[Guest]: listening to songs.

00:49:56.020 --> 00:50:01.060
[Guest]: You're just looking at a hill and you can do this every day and you're smiling, right?

00:50:01.060 --> 00:50:07.580
[Guest]: When I experienced that state, right, it was magical.

00:50:07.580 --> 00:50:11.780
[Guest]: And then again, I can tell you because it's in my diary, I was like, I don't know what

00:50:11.780 --> 00:50:12.780
[Guest]: I want.

00:50:12.780 --> 00:50:16.220
[Guest]: I mean, I have everything, you know, there's nothing that I'm chasing, you know, so when

00:50:16.220 --> 00:50:23.380
[Guest]: you exit that zone, it's just different because like, you don't know, like there is nothing

00:50:23.380 --> 00:50:27.140
[Guest]: that you want, you know, things are happening, you're sorted.

00:50:27.140 --> 00:50:30.300
[Guest]: So I tell it to a friend, they said, oh, so you are being less ambitious.

00:50:30.300 --> 00:50:36.940
[Guest]: I was like, I don't know boss, you know, my diary is telling me ki yeh yeh karna hai aur

00:50:36.940 --> 00:50:38.260
[Guest]: mera toh ho gaya hai.

00:50:38.260 --> 00:50:39.260
[Guest]: So I'm sorted.

00:50:39.260 --> 00:50:41.380
[Guest]: I'm not going to be aur mujhe kuch chahiye nahi.

00:50:41.380 --> 00:50:46.020
[Guest]: So I think, does that answer your question about intentionality, that how, or did I go

00:50:46.020 --> 00:50:47.020
[Amit Varma]: into...

00:50:47.020 --> 00:50:51.300
[Amit Varma]: No, it does and it goes off into this delightful direction also because then I'm wondering

00:50:51.300 --> 00:50:54.180
[Amit Varma]: is ki was that moment a temporary moment?

00:50:54.180 --> 00:50:58.340
[Amit Varma]: Did you get back to wanting things when you got home, you know, and even though you're

00:50:58.340 --> 00:51:04.460
[Amit Varma]: saying there's nothing in your head, you are absorbing yourself.

00:51:04.460 --> 00:51:05.460
[Amit Varma]: But does that help?

00:51:05.460 --> 00:51:11.540
[Amit Varma]: Did going off into the hills, did taking the sabbatical help in terms of coming to terms

00:51:11.540 --> 00:51:13.660
[Amit Varma]: with not following the conventional route?

00:51:13.660 --> 00:51:17.980
[Amit Varma]: Because what you've done, and like, you know, I left the conventional route fine, I decided

00:51:17.980 --> 00:51:22.620
[Amit Varma]: full time job nahi karunga, yeh nahi karunga, but it came from a place of I want to do this

00:51:22.620 --> 00:51:23.620
[Amit Varma]: instead.

00:51:23.620 --> 00:51:27.540
[Amit Varma]: Like first, I want to write a book and then I played poker for five years, which I think

00:51:27.540 --> 00:51:30.620
[Amit Varma]: you would be very good at and we can talk about that later.

00:51:30.620 --> 00:51:37.340
[Amit Varma]: But so there was stuff I was doing, that phase of being at peace with oneself and feeling

00:51:37.340 --> 00:51:40.620
[Amit Varma]: that I'm okay, I'm good with the universe.

00:51:40.620 --> 00:51:41.620
[Unknown]: I never had that.

00:51:41.620 --> 00:51:43.640
[Amit Varma]: And I'm jealous that you had it.

00:51:43.640 --> 00:51:47.180
[Amit Varma]: So did that change you in a fundamental way?

00:51:47.180 --> 00:51:51.540
[Amit Varma]: Like, you know, you know how difficult causality is to pin down.

00:51:51.540 --> 00:51:56.900
[Amit Varma]: So is it the case that when you left HD, when you left that track, it was because you were

00:51:56.900 --> 00:51:59.760
[Amit Varma]: transitioning into a certain phase of life?

00:51:59.760 --> 00:52:05.660
[Amit Varma]: Or do you feel that the person you became later was shaped by the act of leaving?

00:52:05.660 --> 00:52:12.100
[Guest]: So details possibly later, if you're interested, but I think what started happening since college,

00:52:12.100 --> 00:52:15.580
[Guest]: and then at HD, and then I worked at India today for two months and all of that.

00:52:15.580 --> 00:52:22.460
[Guest]: And then even my freelance, I started seeing that this is my feeling, okay, I'm not saying

00:52:22.460 --> 00:52:27.940
[Guest]: this is how it is, but I started feeling that there are these that we are trapped in a matrix

00:52:27.940 --> 00:52:32.460
[Guest]: in a way that there are these structures, key, you know, we are told that this is how

00:52:32.460 --> 00:52:33.460
[Guest]: things are.

00:52:33.460 --> 00:52:39.580
[Guest]: You know, essay karna hota hai, you go to an IIT and you said that your goal is to crack

00:52:39.580 --> 00:52:43.260
[Guest]: that consulting job or you know, work at Facebook, right.

00:52:43.260 --> 00:52:48.620
[Guest]: And what happened with me at IIT and then at newsrooms, is that there are moments where

00:52:48.620 --> 00:52:56.340
[Guest]: I start, it just feels absurd to me that, you know, like I'm a first principles thinker,

00:52:56.340 --> 00:53:00.460
[Guest]: you know, matlab jo hai wo theek hai, main first principles se sochunga, achha college

00:53:00.460 --> 00:53:04.540
[Guest]: aaye toh kyu aaye, uska kya point hai, engineering kar rahe hain toh kyu kar rahe hain, right.

00:53:04.540 --> 00:53:08.060
[Guest]: If I'm doing journalism, what is the point of journalism?

00:53:08.060 --> 00:53:10.220
[Guest]: When it began, what happened, right?

00:53:10.220 --> 00:53:14.780
[Guest]: And then you start seeing, okay, if you're in Instagram, so what are you doing, right?

00:53:14.780 --> 00:53:15.780
[Guest]: All of those things.

00:53:15.780 --> 00:53:18.940
[Guest]: So I ask myself that question and then I see what is happening.

00:53:18.940 --> 00:53:22.460
[Guest]: And in most cases, I find a disconnect.

00:53:22.460 --> 00:53:27.540
[Guest]: That first principles toh keh rahe hain, aisa hona chahiye, but I'm looking around me, that

00:53:27.540 --> 00:53:28.740
[Guest]: is not happening.

00:53:28.740 --> 00:53:32.380
[Guest]: So then I get into that zone where I say, I need to exit this.

00:53:32.380 --> 00:53:38.460
[Guest]: So you know, it's absurd because I am part of that ecosystem and in that structure, but

00:53:38.460 --> 00:53:43.060
[Guest]: I'm like also exiting it and trying to see that structure from the outside.

00:53:43.060 --> 00:53:47.740
[Guest]: So when you see, so it's, you imagine I am like, I'm just doing these hand gestures,

00:53:47.740 --> 00:53:51.900
[Guest]: but I'm here, you know, outside and there's this big giant circle.

00:53:51.900 --> 00:53:55.100
[Guest]: And I'm also observing myself in that movie, what is happening.

00:53:55.100 --> 00:54:00.580
[Guest]: And it feels like this is just a big delusion that you know what, and I, you know, I feel,

00:54:00.580 --> 00:54:04.700
[Guest]: I don't feel good to say all of this because, you know, this is a very self-righteous way

00:54:04.700 --> 00:54:07.860
[Guest]: of saying that, you know, everyone is trapped and I have exited.

00:54:07.860 --> 00:54:11.940
[Guest]: That's not, I mean, I don't know if that is what I'm implying, but I'm saying that is

00:54:11.940 --> 00:54:12.940
[Guest]: what I felt.

00:54:12.940 --> 00:54:17.020
[Guest]: And I said, it's structures I have to get out, right?

00:54:17.020 --> 00:54:19.140
[Guest]: So you get out of that structure.

00:54:19.140 --> 00:54:22.820
[Guest]: It happened with me at IIT, it happened with me at newsrooms, right?

00:54:22.820 --> 00:54:26.660
[Guest]: And I think there was a point when I started feeling, you know, this whole thing is a trap,

00:54:26.660 --> 00:54:31.820
[Guest]: you know, everything that is happening, like, why are we doing, what are we doing?

00:54:31.820 --> 00:54:36.500
[Guest]: And when those questions start coming in, there is a phase of deep discontent, you don't

00:54:36.500 --> 00:54:37.500
[Guest]: know what is happening.

00:54:37.500 --> 00:54:44.660
[Guest]: So at that time, I decided, boss, I want, I want to just think about these questions

00:54:44.660 --> 00:54:52.100
[Guest]: and I don't want external influences on my thinking, okay?

00:54:52.100 --> 00:54:57.860
[Guest]: And or like, that was not the only reason why I moved to the hills, but that was one

00:54:57.860 --> 00:54:58.860
[Guest]: of the reasons.

00:54:58.860 --> 00:55:03.380
[Guest]: Now, when you do that, right, you have seen up, ek trap se nikal rahe ho, duse trap se

00:55:03.380 --> 00:55:06.660
[Guest]: nikal rahe ho, and you keep thinking, maybe I'm in a delusion.

00:55:06.660 --> 00:55:10.340
[Guest]: There are like, mujhe lag raha hai that, you know, I have exited these two traps, maybe

00:55:10.340 --> 00:55:11.340
[Guest]: there are a hundred others.

00:55:11.340 --> 00:55:12.340
[Guest]: So you want a distance.

00:55:12.340 --> 00:55:16.580
[Guest]: Now, what the magical thing about hills, which is not just that, you know, mountains are

00:55:16.580 --> 00:55:18.740
[Guest]: nice, air is clean, woh toh hai.

00:55:18.740 --> 00:55:23.500
[Guest]: The biggest thing is that in a city like Delhi, even though I don't want, there's always a

00:55:23.500 --> 00:55:25.780
[Guest]: status game that is being played.

00:55:25.780 --> 00:55:32.700
[Guest]: I don't know how that happens, but there is something in this air, right?

00:55:32.700 --> 00:55:36.220
[Guest]: Like I am at a, I often work at Blue Tokai's, you know, here and there.

00:55:36.220 --> 00:55:41.900
[Guest]: Waha pe toh I don't know anyone, but still, subconsciously, you know, there is this, you

00:55:41.900 --> 00:55:46.980
[Guest]: know, maybe there's this girl sitting on the next table and I am reading a book and I would

00:55:46.980 --> 00:55:53.380
[Guest]: be unconsciously, I said, you know, no one is bothered about what I am doing, you know,

00:55:53.380 --> 00:55:57.420
[Guest]: sab apna kaam kar rahe hain, they're meeting friends, but you feel you are being observed.

00:55:57.420 --> 00:56:00.300
[Guest]: At least I feel that, that, you know, people are watching me.

00:56:00.300 --> 00:56:04.020
[Guest]: So I, in a way that's good, because then I'm like, you know, I have to read my book.

00:56:04.020 --> 00:56:06.700
[Guest]: I can't, you know, be looking at Instagram in between.

00:56:06.700 --> 00:56:10.900
[Guest]: So in that way, it's, you know, positive force, but I'm saying it's weird in that way.

00:56:10.900 --> 00:56:14.980
[Guest]: Like, I can tell you a story which really irritated me recently.

00:56:14.980 --> 00:56:21.460
[Guest]: So I came to Delhi, I was visiting and I go to cult, you know, chain of gyms, yeah, Cultfit.

00:56:21.460 --> 00:56:25.420
[Guest]: And there is this, I hope this person does not listen to this podcast, but there's this

00:56:25.420 --> 00:56:28.540
[Guest]: young guy, he's like 22 years old, okay.

00:56:28.540 --> 00:56:34.140
[Guest]: And there was COVID, so we, he came, he used to come at the same center where I go for

00:56:34.140 --> 00:56:35.740
[Guest]: my fitness class.

00:56:35.740 --> 00:56:41.020
[Guest]: And he saw me, I, you know, after the cult class in Punjabi Bagh, I went to a blue tukai

00:56:41.020 --> 00:56:42.580
[Guest]: and he saw me and he says, you know, I remember you.

00:56:42.580 --> 00:56:44.580
[Guest]: I said, yeah, I also remember you.

00:56:44.580 --> 00:56:47.540
[Guest]: And for some reason, he's super nerdy about headphones.

00:56:47.540 --> 00:56:50.140
[Guest]: So he, you know, and I'm also nerdy about headphones.

00:56:50.140 --> 00:56:51.940
[Guest]: So he took my headphones, did all of that.

00:56:51.940 --> 00:56:52.940
[Guest]: And then he started a conversation.

00:56:52.940 --> 00:56:54.260
[Guest]: He said, okay, so what do you do?

00:56:54.260 --> 00:56:56.260
[Guest]: I never asked you.

00:56:56.260 --> 00:56:59.260
[Guest]: Unfortunately, I told him I'm a journalist.

00:56:59.260 --> 00:57:00.700
[Guest]: So he's like, oh, you're a journalist.

00:57:00.700 --> 00:57:02.300
[Guest]: So what do you do?

00:57:02.300 --> 00:57:05.220
[Guest]: So I said, you know, I can, I write about various things.

00:57:05.220 --> 00:57:06.540
[Guest]: I'm a long form writer.

00:57:06.540 --> 00:57:10.060
[Guest]: You can, if you want, you know, happy to share my samples of work.

00:57:10.060 --> 00:57:13.180
[Guest]: So before that happened, he said, you know what, I study law.

00:57:13.180 --> 00:57:14.180
[Guest]: Okay.

00:57:14.180 --> 00:57:16.580
[Guest]: You should write about data privacy.

00:57:16.580 --> 00:57:20.060
[Guest]: You should write about platforms and social media, you know, do you know what is happening

00:57:20.060 --> 00:57:21.060
[Guest]: in parliament right now?

00:57:21.060 --> 00:57:24.060
[Guest]: It is such an important topic.

00:57:24.060 --> 00:57:28.700
[Guest]: And I was thinking in my head that, boss, I covered that for two years.

00:57:28.700 --> 00:57:29.700
[Guest]: Okay.

00:57:29.700 --> 00:57:34.500
[Guest]: I was a reporter at the Hindustan Times and as a freelancer, I've written across.

00:57:34.500 --> 00:57:38.900
[Guest]: And now, no offense to young people, and I'm also like just 29.

00:57:38.900 --> 00:57:43.900
[Guest]: But this 22 year old is telling me, this is what you should do.

00:57:43.900 --> 00:57:47.540
[Guest]: So I was like, then I said, I know a few things about this.

00:57:47.540 --> 00:57:48.740
[Guest]: This is an article I've written.

00:57:48.740 --> 00:57:49.740
[Guest]: You tell me what you think.

00:57:49.740 --> 00:57:50.740
[Guest]: They said, I will.

00:57:50.740 --> 00:57:53.820
[Guest]: So he said, oh, you have written such a long article.

00:57:53.820 --> 00:57:57.420
[Guest]: I think there is a book in you.

00:57:57.420 --> 00:58:04.140
[Guest]: And before I could say anything, he's like, okay, Samarth, tell me, what is that one thing

00:58:04.140 --> 00:58:05.860
[Guest]: you feel very passionate about?

00:58:05.860 --> 00:58:06.860
[Guest]: Okay.

00:58:06.860 --> 00:58:08.860
[Guest]: What is that thing that troubles you?

00:58:08.860 --> 00:58:09.860
[Guest]: That is the book.

00:58:09.860 --> 00:58:12.340
[Guest]: I see a writer in you.

00:58:12.340 --> 00:58:19.900
[Guest]: And Amit, I was speechless because like, I did not know what to make of it.

00:58:19.900 --> 00:58:23.300
[Guest]: You know, I did not want, and no offense to that person.

00:58:23.300 --> 00:58:25.420
[Guest]: He's just, he's just extrovert.

00:58:25.420 --> 00:58:30.780
[Guest]: So he's just coming and telling me things, but I don't want this external input in my

00:58:30.780 --> 00:58:31.780
[Guest]: brain.

00:58:31.780 --> 00:58:37.020
[Guest]: You know, garbage in, garbage out, like, why should there be garbage in my brain?

00:58:37.020 --> 00:58:38.020
[Unknown]: Right?

00:58:38.020 --> 00:58:42.020
[Guest]: I went to this conference, not conference, it was a book launch.

00:58:42.020 --> 00:58:43.020
[Guest]: And I was visiting.

00:58:43.020 --> 00:58:47.620
[Guest]: And I went and I felt so uncomfortable because there are these, after a long while, I met

00:58:47.620 --> 00:58:51.700
[Guest]: journalist friends and others, and everyone is curious, what are you doing?

00:58:51.700 --> 00:58:52.700
[Guest]: Okay.

00:58:52.700 --> 00:58:53.700
[Guest]: How do you manage your finances?

00:58:53.700 --> 00:58:54.700
[Guest]: Okay.

00:58:54.700 --> 00:58:55.700
[Guest]: Why are you doing this?

00:58:55.700 --> 00:58:58.980
[Guest]: So you're always, in a sense, constantly explaining.

00:58:58.980 --> 00:59:00.540
[Guest]: Now, then you feel like an idiot.

00:59:00.540 --> 00:59:01.540
[Guest]: Is it me?

00:59:01.540 --> 00:59:04.540
[Guest]: That, you know, like, you don't have to explain, just ignore.

00:59:04.540 --> 00:59:09.660
[Guest]: But how do you do it when everyone around you is just asking these questions?

00:59:09.660 --> 00:59:14.260
[Guest]: And then, because they're nice people, right, they're not evil, they're nice people.

00:59:14.260 --> 00:59:18.020
[Guest]: And they would say something that would stick in your head.

00:59:18.020 --> 00:59:22.180
[Guest]: In Hills, nothing happens because no one gives a damn about who I am.

00:59:22.180 --> 00:59:27.220
[Guest]: All people who know me there, it's like, yes, a boy from the city lives here.

00:59:27.220 --> 00:59:30.220
[Guest]: They have no idea about my background, there's zero status game.

00:59:30.220 --> 00:59:32.940
[Guest]: And Amit, I cannot tell you.

00:59:32.940 --> 00:59:39.260
[Guest]: It is just magical when you're not performing at any moment in the day, because no one gives

00:59:39.260 --> 00:59:40.260
[Guest]: a damn.

00:59:40.260 --> 00:59:41.260
[Guest]: Right?

00:59:41.260 --> 00:59:45.940
[Guest]: So, and once you see that, you know, you don't have to perform, like you can be an idiot

00:59:45.940 --> 00:59:51.460
[Guest]: one time, and you can be, you know, reading your book, and no one is asking any question.

00:59:51.460 --> 00:59:53.380
[Guest]: It's just liberating.

00:59:53.380 --> 00:59:58.980
[Guest]: So that, I think, was one of the biggest things that I realized that started happening.

00:59:58.980 --> 01:00:02.260
[Guest]: You come back home, and then people are commenting on my body.

01:00:02.260 --> 01:00:04.380
[Guest]: You know, they're, yeah, it happens all the time.

01:00:04.380 --> 01:00:07.140
[Guest]: You have lost so much weight, don't do this, don't do that.

01:00:07.140 --> 01:00:10.900
[Guest]: So again, you know, they'll start talking about like, I think this is a very late 20s

01:00:10.900 --> 01:00:11.900
[Guest]: thing.

01:00:11.900 --> 01:00:15.060
[Guest]: I think every people would relate to it, you know, they start talking about marriage, that's

01:00:15.060 --> 01:00:18.540
[Guest]: the only thing, you know, a problem that doesn't exist in your life, but people want to solve

01:00:18.540 --> 01:00:19.540
[Guest]: it for you.

01:00:19.540 --> 01:00:21.700
[Guest]: That kind of things, that happens in Delhi.

01:00:21.700 --> 01:00:28.060
[Guest]: So I'm seeing this aspect of being away, and then observing, and then, you know, asking

01:00:28.060 --> 01:00:29.060
[Guest]: all.

01:00:29.060 --> 01:00:33.420
[Guest]: So that way, when you're outside the structure, you can actually think about those questions,

01:00:33.420 --> 01:00:34.780
[Guest]: at least, so that helps me.

01:00:34.780 --> 01:00:39.380
[Guest]: So it's not a temporary moment when I said that, you know, that thoughtless, I mean,

01:00:39.380 --> 01:00:42.180
[Guest]: kuch hoga, I don't know, but that happens repeatedly.

01:00:42.180 --> 01:00:48.020
[Guest]: When I see my diary, four years ago, usme jo sawal the, agar wo answer ho gaye hain,

01:00:48.020 --> 01:00:51.020
[Guest]: or like, I have at least a framework to think about it, to woh ho raha hai na, that you

01:00:51.020 --> 01:00:52.620
[Guest]: are like, you're progressing.

01:00:52.620 --> 01:00:57.020
[Guest]: So that way, I think a mixture of all of these things is what, yeah, that's where it comes

01:00:57.020 --> 01:01:01.860
[Guest]: that, you know, you stop wanting, because the wants I somehow feel are created by people

01:01:01.860 --> 01:01:07.740
[Guest]: around us, you know, they influence what you want, but when you're away, like, who will

01:01:07.740 --> 01:01:10.580
[Guest]: influence what you want?

01:01:10.580 --> 01:01:15.340
[Amit Varma]: I'm feeling very attracted to the hills now, because they seem like a physical answer to

01:01:15.340 --> 01:01:20.420
[Amit Varma]: the existential question of, you know, that fundamental human anxiety is the anxiety of

01:01:20.420 --> 01:01:21.940
[Unknown]: what other people will think of you.

01:01:21.940 --> 01:01:22.940
[Unknown]: Yeah, right.

01:01:22.940 --> 01:01:24.820
[Amit Varma]: And it is so hard to let it go.

01:01:24.820 --> 01:01:28.900
[Amit Varma]: And it's only I think, when I reached middle age, that at least at an intellectual level,

01:01:28.900 --> 01:01:31.580
[Amit Varma]: I understood that, boss, no one is thinking of you.

01:01:31.580 --> 01:01:35.180
[Amit Varma]: Everyone has a head up their own ass, kisi ko nahi par hi hai.

01:01:35.180 --> 01:01:40.380
[Amit Varma]: And you just, you know, you just have to chill and do whatever the hell you kind of want.

01:01:40.380 --> 01:01:42.900
[Amit Varma]: And you've spoken about wants a number of times.

01:01:42.900 --> 01:01:46.900
[Amit Varma]: And there is a theme that I have been exploring so much on my podcast ki mujhe lag raha tha

01:01:46.900 --> 01:01:49.580
[Amit Varma]: ki bahut cliche ho gaya hai, abhi main nahi bolunga.

01:01:49.580 --> 01:01:52.620
[Amit Varma]: But I feel that you're the right person to talk to about this.

01:01:52.620 --> 01:01:57.860
[Amit Varma]: And you know, this is something that so I was, you know, I had gone to Greece and Macedonia

01:01:57.860 --> 01:01:59.580
[Amit Varma]: earlier in the year.

01:01:59.580 --> 01:02:04.620
[Amit Varma]: And the background of that is even though I retired from poker few years ago, there's

01:02:04.620 --> 01:02:08.260
[Amit Varma]: a form of poker which had come up called match poker, which is very different from regular

01:02:08.260 --> 01:02:11.340
[Amit Varma]: poker looks and feels the same completely different.

01:02:11.340 --> 01:02:16.500
[Amit Varma]: And like you, I love solving things from first principles to one of my friends got in touch

01:02:16.500 --> 01:02:21.340
[Amit Varma]: with me and he said ki is cheez ka ek IPL type tournament ho raha hai.

01:02:21.340 --> 01:02:25.420
[Amit Varma]: And I am I'm running he was he owned a team called Haryana Hawks.

01:02:25.420 --> 01:02:28.820
[Amit Varma]: He said come and help me solve this because everybody's going to play it like poker.

01:02:28.820 --> 01:02:30.060
[Amit Varma]: So solve it for me.

01:02:30.060 --> 01:02:34.540
[Amit Varma]: So I joined the team, do baar hum jeet gaye Haryana Hawks ke saath, then I, we played

01:02:34.540 --> 01:02:37.060
[Amit Varma]: for the Indian team and we won the Asian championship.

01:02:37.060 --> 01:02:41.980
[Amit Varma]: Covid times mein tha online tha but I was like I was damn happy ki as and representing

01:02:41.980 --> 01:02:44.340
[Unknown]: India Asian championship jeet gaye.

01:02:44.340 --> 01:02:48.420
[Amit Varma]: Toh is saal kya hua ki hum world championship mein gaye jo Macedonia mein hua.

01:02:48.420 --> 01:02:52.660
[Amit Varma]: And side by side, I also scheduled a personal vacation in Greece right after that.

01:02:52.660 --> 01:02:58.540
[Amit Varma]: Toh Macedonia mein gaye and we were unfortunate in a sense ki three of our regular team members

01:02:58.540 --> 01:03:01.780
[Amit Varma]: had their visas denied, we had to get new people.

01:03:01.780 --> 01:03:05.660
[Amit Varma]: And it this particular form of the game, you kind of have to play it as a team everybody's

01:03:05.660 --> 01:03:07.500
[Amit Varma]: got to be really clued in.

01:03:07.500 --> 01:03:13.100
[Amit Varma]: And we got massacred like every team we had beaten at the Asian level destroyed us right.

01:03:13.100 --> 01:03:17.620
[Amit Varma]: And I was feeling gutted at the end of it absolutely gutted.

01:03:17.620 --> 01:03:25.220
[Amit Varma]: And then I read this great book by Luke Burgess called Wanting or Wanting mein his framework

01:03:25.220 --> 01:03:29.580
[Amit Varma]: is that he's influenced by the works of Rene Girard, who was also an influence on Peter

01:03:29.580 --> 01:03:30.580
[Amit Varma]: Thiel.

01:03:30.580 --> 01:03:36.420
[Amit Varma]: And Girard had come up with this concept of mimetic desire, which is that you want something

01:03:36.420 --> 01:03:39.940
[Amit Varma]: because somebody else wants it, you don't really intrinsically want it.

01:03:39.940 --> 01:03:43.580
[Amit Varma]: And the frame I got from Burgess there was of thick and thin desires, right?

01:03:43.580 --> 01:03:47.100
[Amit Varma]: So thick desires are things that you intrinsically want.

01:03:47.100 --> 01:03:49.740
[Amit Varma]: And obviously creature comforts like food and all are not part of it.

01:03:49.740 --> 01:03:54.140
[Amit Varma]: But thick desires is something that you deeply want and it's not influenced by anything.

01:03:54.140 --> 01:03:59.100
[Amit Varma]: And thin desires are desires which you have because they are the done thing somebody else

01:03:59.100 --> 01:04:03.380
[Amit Varma]: have them like Mercedes or if you're a young person, you might say I want to get married

01:04:03.380 --> 01:04:05.740
[Amit Varma]: and have kids, but you're not really questioning that.

01:04:05.740 --> 01:04:10.260
[Amit Varma]: Or if you're in IIT and you're stuck in that game, you're thinking, I want to go to America

01:04:10.260 --> 01:04:11.700
[Amit Varma]: and become a software engineer.

01:04:11.700 --> 01:04:16.180
[Amit Varma]: All those kind of different games are thin desires, which you've spoken about so much.

01:04:16.180 --> 01:04:20.020
[Amit Varma]: And that made me reflect on why I was so gutted.

01:04:20.020 --> 01:04:24.060
[Amit Varma]: And I realized that I was gutted because of a thin desire, right?

01:04:24.060 --> 01:04:29.460
[Amit Varma]: The thin desire was that I want that glory that I have won the World Championships with

01:04:29.460 --> 01:04:30.460
[Amit Varma]: Team India.

01:04:30.460 --> 01:04:35.740
[Amit Varma]: I will tweet, 2000 people will retweet, which when we won the Asian Championship was kind

01:04:35.740 --> 01:04:37.020
[Amit Varma]: of what happened.

01:04:37.020 --> 01:04:38.260
[Amit Varma]: And it was an intense desire.

01:04:38.260 --> 01:04:41.260
[Amit Varma]: I wanted how many people get this, right?

01:04:41.260 --> 01:04:42.860
[Amit Varma]: And but it was a thin desire.

01:04:42.860 --> 01:04:48.260
[Amit Varma]: It was, you know, premised on that old anxiety of getting the approval of others.

01:04:48.260 --> 01:04:52.580
[Amit Varma]: And I realized that my thick desire was what my thick desire was to figure it out, to figure

01:04:52.580 --> 01:04:54.380
[Amit Varma]: out the game, to go back to first principles.

01:04:54.380 --> 01:04:58.020
[Amit Varma]: My thick desire was to understand something.

01:04:58.020 --> 01:04:59.780
[Amit Varma]: And I understood why we lost.

01:04:59.780 --> 01:05:03.580
[Amit Varma]: I understood why we lost.

01:05:03.580 --> 01:05:05.620
[Amit Varma]: I understood why the winning team won.

01:05:05.620 --> 01:05:08.700
[Amit Varma]: I could look at everyone's strategy and figure out what happened.

01:05:08.700 --> 01:05:10.500
[Amit Varma]: That was understanding.

01:05:10.500 --> 01:05:13.500
[Amit Varma]: But the thing is, the thin desire was intense.

01:05:13.500 --> 01:05:19.700
[Amit Varma]: And the thick desire was very, you know, unseen and subterranean and all of that.

01:05:19.700 --> 01:05:25.580
[Amit Varma]: And this then made me introspect beyond that, that life me jo wants hai, woh kyu hai?

01:05:25.580 --> 01:05:28.980
[Amit Varma]: Like I discussed the same thing with Nilanjan Aroy and we were speaking about the desire

01:05:28.980 --> 01:05:30.460
[Amit Varma]: to be a writer.

01:05:30.460 --> 01:05:33.820
[Amit Varma]: And you can have thick and thin desires simultaneously coexisting.

01:05:33.820 --> 01:05:38.340
[Amit Varma]: Your thin desire is to be known as a writer, woh branding ho jati hai, main yeh prize jeetunga,

01:05:38.340 --> 01:05:44.020
[Amit Varma]: book launch mein jaunga, jacket pehnunga, panel mein gyaan doonga, all that shit.

01:05:44.020 --> 01:05:49.020
[Amit Varma]: And that seems to me to be thin, while the thick desire is I want to tell a story.

01:05:49.020 --> 01:05:53.700
[Amit Varma]: I want to sit down and I want to tell a story, or I want to uncover some part of the unseen

01:05:53.700 --> 01:05:55.980
[Amit Varma]: world or whatever it is.

01:05:55.980 --> 01:05:59.780
[Amit Varma]: And I've realized that if you chase thin desires, you cannot be happy.

01:05:59.780 --> 01:06:03.740
[Amit Varma]: That happiness really lies outside of that of giving them up.

01:06:03.740 --> 01:06:08.540
[Amit Varma]: Whether or not you find a thick desire, you have to let the thin desires go.

01:06:08.540 --> 01:06:12.160
[Amit Varma]: Because then you're chasing somebody else's dream, really, or you're chasing something

01:06:12.160 --> 01:06:13.840
[Amit Varma]: that is superficial.

01:06:13.840 --> 01:06:18.980
[Amit Varma]: So since you've been speaking so much about desires and wanting and you've clearly figured

01:06:18.980 --> 01:06:25.620
[Amit Varma]: this out and escaped a lot of these thin desires that one might have in either IIT or in journalism

01:06:25.620 --> 01:06:28.900
[Amit Varma]: and so on, you know, what are your thoughts?

01:06:28.900 --> 01:06:31.780
[Amit Varma]: Can you kind of go further along this path for me?

01:06:31.780 --> 01:06:32.780
[Guest]: Sure.

01:06:32.780 --> 01:06:35.940
[Guest]: So just to be clear, I'm not a saint, so it's not a complete escape.

01:06:35.940 --> 01:06:42.860
[Guest]: I think it's a spectrum on this, if we take thin and thick on two ends.

01:06:42.860 --> 01:06:47.500
[Guest]: And I just feel based on this framework, I'm closer to the thick spectrum.

01:06:47.500 --> 01:06:51.860
[Guest]: Okay, still, you know, I write a story like, you know, I started a newsletter earlier this

01:06:51.860 --> 01:06:56.620
[Guest]: year, and I am so happy with, you know, that whole process of what I did there.

01:06:56.620 --> 01:07:00.780
[Guest]: But you know, every time before I'm pressing that send button, you know, the process of

01:07:00.780 --> 01:07:03.940
[Guest]: writing that story and reporting is just absolutely thrilling.

01:07:03.940 --> 01:07:09.440
[Guest]: Like one of the reasons I started my newsletter was that I want to do original reporting.

01:07:09.440 --> 01:07:13.620
[Guest]: And I don't want anyone's permission of what is a story.

01:07:13.620 --> 01:07:18.240
[Guest]: There are stories that I want to tell, right, and I don't want anyone's permission.

01:07:18.240 --> 01:07:22.660
[Guest]: So it's it came like every idea came from ye mujhe batana hai, there's a style of writing

01:07:22.660 --> 01:07:28.260
[Guest]: I want to try in my own journey as becoming the writer that I want to become.

01:07:28.260 --> 01:07:34.860
[Guest]: So baha se, but the moment I'm pressing the send button, I know, okay, this is, you know,

01:07:34.860 --> 01:07:38.900
[Guest]: it's like, you know, like, what will these subscribers think?

01:07:38.900 --> 01:07:41.300
[Guest]: Will it work for them?

01:07:41.300 --> 01:07:42.620
[Guest]: Right?

01:07:42.620 --> 01:07:43.620
[Guest]: What if I fucked up?

01:07:43.620 --> 01:07:44.620
[Guest]: Right?

01:07:44.620 --> 01:07:45.620
[Guest]: What if?

01:07:45.620 --> 01:07:50.220
[Guest]: You know, all sorts of questions come so that the moment I press the send button, you know,

01:07:50.220 --> 01:07:55.140
[Guest]: I just sometimes feel chaubis ghante ke lena I should just disappear because that sense

01:07:55.140 --> 01:07:59.900
[Guest]: remains that okay, maine apna kaam kar diya because this I wanted to do, but I can't isolate

01:07:59.900 --> 01:08:04.980
[Guest]: myself from the feedback to the work actually, you know, so that part remains.

01:08:04.980 --> 01:08:11.680
[Guest]: And once I started thinking that a cognitive dissonance hits you, because you create an

01:08:11.680 --> 01:08:16.860
[Guest]: impression that, you know, I am doing this because I want to do this, right?

01:08:16.860 --> 01:08:22.300
[Guest]: And then once you start getting these thoughts, that no, I'm also thinking, what will the

01:08:22.300 --> 01:08:25.300
[Guest]: other person think about my writing?

01:08:25.300 --> 01:08:29.980
[Guest]: So wahan pe aage na aapka about that I am being dictated by the world.

01:08:29.980 --> 01:08:33.840
[Guest]: So and this, I observed Amit more closely.

01:08:33.840 --> 01:08:37.820
[Guest]: So my Instagram activity has now increased, okay, not increased, it's not that I'm all

01:08:37.820 --> 01:08:42.700
[Guest]: the time on Instagram, but if someone does the stats, the time I spent has gone up and

01:08:42.700 --> 01:08:43.700
[Guest]: I enjoy it.

01:08:43.700 --> 01:08:47.340
[Guest]: Instagram, I think I really love the platform compared to others, and there's a way I use

01:08:47.340 --> 01:08:48.340
[Guest]: it.

01:08:48.340 --> 01:08:54.220
[Guest]: But wahan pe I felt this, that there were moments when I perform on Instagram about

01:08:54.220 --> 01:09:01.020
[Guest]: and it just performed like just to be more clear, that unconsciously or consciously,

01:09:01.020 --> 01:09:12.060
[Guest]: I don't know, but like if I'm posting a meaningless meme on reposting on my Instagram story, right?

01:09:12.060 --> 01:09:15.620
[Guest]: I don't know why I'm doing it, okay?

01:09:15.620 --> 01:09:20.340
[Guest]: I post pictures, I go for this hike, love it, and I just post it.

01:09:20.340 --> 01:09:24.500
[Guest]: So then I started thinking, am I doing this, like, why am I posting this?

01:09:24.500 --> 01:09:30.260
[Guest]: Do I want to show people that, you know, okay, I have this beautiful zen of a life, right?

01:09:30.260 --> 01:09:34.340
[Guest]: So then usmein main ek pattern dekha that there are two things happening, one which

01:09:34.340 --> 01:09:39.940
[Guest]: is pure self-expression, right, I recently watched Dead Poets Society, okay, just loved

01:09:39.940 --> 01:09:40.940
[Amit Varma]: the movie.

01:09:40.940 --> 01:09:44.540
[Amit Varma]: Favourite film of my childhood, woh jab last scene aati hai na abhi bhi, main roh padta

01:09:44.540 --> 01:09:45.540
[Guest]: ho.

01:09:45.540 --> 01:09:46.540
[Guest]: I know, right?

01:09:46.540 --> 01:09:49.620
[Guest]: So it just, and that was the moment there was a, in my own, something recently happened

01:09:49.620 --> 01:09:53.460
[Guest]: where I just told myself that, you know, I want to become a writer, you know, I want

01:09:53.460 --> 01:09:57.500
[Guest]: to do this, this, this, and ussi time pe main movie dekhi, so it was so, so I, uswaqt I

01:09:57.500 --> 01:10:02.380
[Guest]: just took a screenshot of, you know, one of the scenes and I just posted it on Instagram,

01:10:02.380 --> 01:10:04.020
[Guest]: not for anyone.

01:10:04.020 --> 01:10:10.500
[Guest]: That was for me to tell, you know, to timestamp that aaj is din main yeh soch raha tha and

01:10:10.500 --> 01:10:15.540
[Guest]: I didn't care about who likes it, who doesn't like it, but there are other times when it's

01:10:15.540 --> 01:10:18.160
[Guest]: not always self-expression, right?

01:10:18.160 --> 01:10:22.220
[Guest]: So I'm saying that it's a mix and it's a cognitive dissonance because you want to be

01:10:22.220 --> 01:10:23.720
[Guest]: this person, but that happens.

01:10:23.720 --> 01:10:29.580
[Guest]: So I think I don't know anyone or if you can completely escape it, but I think intentionality

01:10:29.580 --> 01:10:34.300
[Guest]: and again, I give all the credit to my diary that it just tells you what are your thick

01:10:34.300 --> 01:10:35.300
[Guest]: desires?

01:10:35.300 --> 01:10:37.700
[Guest]: Aap kya chase kar rahe ho and kyun?

01:10:37.700 --> 01:10:41.940
[Guest]: Because when you're honest to yourself, I think, I think Neil Postman had this quote

01:10:41.940 --> 01:10:48.420
[Guest]: that I'm forgetting the specifics, but something like this essence was, you know, there are

01:10:48.420 --> 01:10:54.060
[Guest]: a lot of bullshitters in the world, but we like to ourselves, we are the biggest bullshitters

01:10:54.060 --> 01:10:57.180
[Guest]: to ourselves about the stories we tell, right?

01:10:57.180 --> 01:11:03.780
[Guest]: So that way, I think I observed a lot of my, I've overanalyzed my Instagram activity.

01:11:03.780 --> 01:11:05.040
[Guest]: So wahaan se yeh sab aaya.

01:11:05.040 --> 01:11:10.060
[Guest]: And then I remembered in my notes, I had this quote from Warren Buffet where he asks, makes

01:11:10.060 --> 01:11:14.080
[Guest]: a distinction between an inner scorecard and an outer scorecard.

01:11:14.080 --> 01:11:20.740
[Guest]: So he poses this question, would you be the world's greatest lover, but the world feels

01:11:20.740 --> 01:11:23.900
[Guest]: you are the world's worst lover or the opposite?

01:11:23.900 --> 01:11:24.900
[Guest]: What would you want?

01:11:24.900 --> 01:11:25.900
[Amit Varma]: Beautiful.

01:11:25.900 --> 01:11:26.900
[Guest]: Right?

01:11:26.900 --> 01:11:31.000
[Guest]: So that is his distinction between inner scorecard and outer scorecard.

01:11:31.000 --> 01:11:33.100
[Guest]: What is the scorecard that works for you?

01:11:33.100 --> 01:11:39.300
[Guest]: So when I heard that, I was like, that makes so much sense, because the outer scorecard

01:11:39.300 --> 01:11:40.920
[Guest]: is never ending.

01:11:40.920 --> 01:11:41.920
[Guest]: It never ends.

01:11:41.920 --> 01:11:46.940
[Guest]: You talk about our profession, right, it's, again, I love all my journalist friends.

01:11:46.940 --> 01:11:52.560
[Guest]: But sometimes, you know, this whole thing about awards and retweets, and all of that,

01:11:52.560 --> 01:11:56.420
[Guest]: it is not, it's not why I do the work I do.

01:11:56.420 --> 01:11:59.700
[Guest]: And one thing I can tell, actually, I should say this in public.

01:11:59.700 --> 01:12:04.100
[Guest]: I think this was 2020, COVID time, yeah.

01:12:04.100 --> 01:12:08.340
[Guest]: This editor, there's a story I wrote, and he told me that, you know, his Ramnath Goenka

01:12:08.340 --> 01:12:09.340
[Guest]: awards are coming.

01:12:09.340 --> 01:12:11.220
[Guest]: So it's a great story.

01:12:11.220 --> 01:12:13.020
[Guest]: You should apply.

01:12:13.020 --> 01:12:18.300
[Guest]: And I, I thought, and I said, I won't apply.

01:12:18.300 --> 01:12:20.700
[Guest]: And he was like, why won't you apply?

01:12:20.700 --> 01:12:24.000
[Guest]: I said, boss, I have thought about it.

01:12:24.000 --> 01:12:26.140
[Guest]: I don't want to get stuck in this award business.

01:12:26.140 --> 01:12:32.140
[Guest]: Okay, I have, there's a philosophical reason where I think that awards perpetuate inequality.

01:12:32.140 --> 01:12:35.180
[Guest]: And you know, the myth of meritocracy that is separate.

01:12:35.180 --> 01:12:38.860
[Guest]: But apart from that, there was this thing that I never want to be known as an award

01:12:38.860 --> 01:12:39.860
[Guest]: winning journalist.

01:12:39.860 --> 01:12:45.420
[Guest]: I want to be a journalist because, again, it might be stupid, but to me, you know, this

01:12:45.420 --> 01:12:46.420
[Guest]: is an isolation.

01:12:46.420 --> 01:12:52.660
[Guest]: If you don't apply to an award, right, so you will just feel happy about everyone winning

01:12:52.660 --> 01:12:56.820
[Guest]: awards around you, right?

01:12:56.820 --> 01:13:01.460
[Guest]: And that just gave me such deep sense of comfort in my head that, you know, okay, I am a journalist,

01:13:01.460 --> 01:13:08.380
[Guest]: not because I want this award, but you know, just stay true to like why I joined this profession

01:13:08.380 --> 01:13:09.380
[Guest]: in the first place.

01:13:09.380 --> 01:13:11.140
[Guest]: Because to me, it just sticks to you.

01:13:11.140 --> 01:13:16.140
[Guest]: I don't know how long it will last, you know, but I'm saying this is the zone of wants and

01:13:16.140 --> 01:13:25.020
[Guest]: desires that every time I start seeing that there is an external influence that will affect

01:13:25.020 --> 01:13:28.980
[Guest]: my thick desires, I try to just get rid of it.

01:13:28.980 --> 01:13:33.840
[Guest]: Now, whether it happens or not is a different story, but that's the framing.

01:13:33.840 --> 01:13:37.620
[Guest]: And I think that has really helped me because now, you know, when I see like, you know,

01:13:37.620 --> 01:13:42.060
[Guest]: in journalism, one of the things I find, I don't know if it's generic, I don't want to

01:13:42.060 --> 01:13:46.380
[Guest]: generalize, but somehow I feel that among reporters and journalists, if someone else

01:13:46.380 --> 01:13:57.700
[Guest]: breaks a story, you know, you know, so you're like, you feel that sense of envy, you know,

01:13:57.700 --> 01:14:00.020
[Guest]: you know, okay, he got published there.

01:14:00.020 --> 01:14:04.300
[Guest]: He got like, I remember back in the day when I was at the Hindu, I heard this conversation

01:14:04.300 --> 01:14:08.620
[Guest]: between a couple of colleagues, they were discussing salary of a columnist whom I really

01:14:08.620 --> 01:14:09.660
[Guest]: like.

01:14:09.660 --> 01:14:11.260
[Guest]: And I felt so disgusted.

01:14:11.260 --> 01:14:14.300
[Guest]: I was like, oh, you know, this guy is making that much money.

01:14:14.300 --> 01:14:16.780
[Guest]: Uska toh bahut sahi hai, aisa aisa ho raha hai.

01:14:16.780 --> 01:14:21.660
[Guest]: And I feel like, what are these conversations, you know, I just, you know, I just didn't

01:14:21.660 --> 01:14:24.980
[Guest]: like it that why are these conversations happening.

01:14:24.980 --> 01:14:29.340
[Guest]: So the point I'm trying to make here is that, so I'm saying that when I saw that, that kind

01:14:29.340 --> 01:14:34.100
[Guest]: of conversation was happening, when I started seeing that, you know, when someone wins an

01:14:34.100 --> 01:14:42.500
[Guest]: award, or you know, someone breaks a story, everyone is not happy about it in a way.

01:14:42.500 --> 01:14:46.900
[Guest]: It's like, you know, you just look at Twitter patterns of what stuff we share up, you know,

01:14:46.900 --> 01:14:50.740
[Guest]: you retweet stuff of your friends from your organization, you know, you just promote stuff

01:14:50.740 --> 01:14:56.020
[Guest]: that your, you people, you know, personally, they have done, I don't know, it's my observation,

01:14:56.020 --> 01:14:57.100
[Guest]: I may be wrong.

01:14:57.100 --> 01:15:03.900
[Guest]: But that's a sense I got when I was in Delhi, that people are always like, I have some really

01:15:03.900 --> 01:15:06.380
[Guest]: accomplished friends.

01:15:06.380 --> 01:15:10.060
[Guest]: And those who know that I know these people, they will come and ask me, okay, do you know

01:15:10.060 --> 01:15:11.060
[Guest]: how much they make?

01:15:11.060 --> 01:15:12.940
[Guest]: How are they getting these assignments?

01:15:12.940 --> 01:15:15.540
[Guest]: Not in the sense of curiosity, but with a sense of envy.

01:15:15.540 --> 01:15:16.540
[Guest]: Right?

01:15:16.540 --> 01:15:17.540
[Guest]: I don't like it, Amit.

01:15:17.540 --> 01:15:20.460
[Guest]: I don't know, kitna common hai, but that's what I experienced.

01:15:20.460 --> 01:15:25.380
[Guest]: So then when I thought about it, it just struck me one over a period of time, not one day,

01:15:25.380 --> 01:15:33.020
[Guest]: that actually the work that we do as journalists, right, there is no meaning of my work in isolation.

01:15:33.020 --> 01:15:36.460
[Guest]: This profession matters only as a collective.

01:15:36.460 --> 01:15:40.420
[Guest]: If tomorrow I stop reporting, it doesn't matter.

01:15:40.420 --> 01:15:41.420
[Guest]: It doesn't matter.

01:15:41.420 --> 01:15:42.420
[Guest]: There's nothing going to happen.

01:15:42.420 --> 01:15:47.460
[Guest]: But if 1000 people like me exit this profession, it is going to matter a lot.

01:15:47.460 --> 01:15:51.980
[Guest]: Because in collective is where the power of reporting really comes in our profession,

01:15:51.980 --> 01:15:55.180
[Guest]: not in as individuals.

01:15:55.180 --> 01:16:01.220
[Guest]: So that's why the moment I started saying ki, you know, iss award race mein nahi jaana

01:16:01.220 --> 01:16:03.100
[Guest]: hai, follower ki race mein nahi jaana hai.

01:16:03.100 --> 01:16:05.820
[Guest]: And I remember there's this alumni who came to our campus, Ashish Gupta.

01:16:05.820 --> 01:16:10.020
[Guest]: He's a very, Helion Ventures, like he was the early investor in Flipkart.

01:16:10.020 --> 01:16:12.900
[Guest]: And when that exit happened, he's a very, very smart guy.

01:16:12.900 --> 01:16:14.460
[Guest]: And he gave a talk at campus.

01:16:14.460 --> 01:16:18.380
[Guest]: So he used this term called anti-matrix, you know.

01:16:18.380 --> 01:16:24.300
[Guest]: So he was explaining what, he says, he had this great talk on risk in thinking about

01:16:24.300 --> 01:16:25.500
[Guest]: life.

01:16:25.500 --> 01:16:27.740
[Guest]: And waha pe wo matrix, anti-matrix ki baat kar rahe the.

01:16:27.740 --> 01:16:32.700
[Guest]: Toh tab unhone samjhaya that, you know, there are some anti-matrix that you should not chase,

01:16:32.700 --> 01:16:35.260
[Guest]: like your salary, you know, like a designation.

01:16:35.260 --> 01:16:37.260
[Guest]: Yeh mere fourth year ki baat hai.

01:16:37.260 --> 01:16:39.900
[Guest]: Toh this word anti-matrix just stuck in my head.

01:16:39.900 --> 01:16:40.900
[Amit Varma]: Beautiful term.

01:16:40.900 --> 01:16:46.300
[Guest]: So I started now mapping out in my profession in journalism, what are the anti-matrix, right?

01:16:46.300 --> 01:16:50.100
[Guest]: And you realize and you're like, get out of it, you know, anti-matrix chahiye hi nahi.

01:16:50.100 --> 01:16:53.940
[Guest]: And I am a human, I have those, matlab main kitna bhi abhi bolnu, right?

01:16:53.940 --> 01:16:58.780
[Guest]: I will go back and there is a possibility that, you know, my theory about all of these

01:16:58.780 --> 01:17:01.580
[Guest]: things is that they're always in tension.

01:17:01.580 --> 01:17:04.220
[Guest]: You know, one part overtakes the other, woh ho raha hai, right?

01:17:04.220 --> 01:17:09.540
[Guest]: The more I can resist the impulses I do not want, the better.

01:17:09.540 --> 01:17:11.060
[Guest]: So that's the frame.

01:17:11.060 --> 01:17:16.820
[Guest]: So usme if you can fundamentally eliminate, agar aapne soch liya hai, mereko toh awards

01:17:16.820 --> 01:17:19.780
[Guest]: mein apply hi nahi karna hai, toh you're sorted.

01:17:19.780 --> 01:17:22.860
[Guest]: Because the next time a friend tells you, you know, I won this award, you will feel

01:17:22.860 --> 01:17:25.660
[Guest]: so happy about the person.

01:17:25.660 --> 01:17:28.020
[Guest]: They get a fellowship, something happens.

01:17:28.020 --> 01:17:31.620
[Guest]: And the, I don't know the tragedy, but again, the cognitive dissonance in all of this is

01:17:31.620 --> 01:17:35.500
[Guest]: that throughout my career, I keep getting opportunities.

01:17:35.500 --> 01:17:40.260
[Guest]: So I can never feel like that, ki mere saath kuch bura ho raha hai.

01:17:40.260 --> 01:17:43.460
[Guest]: Because I, you know, I just feel the world is rigged to push me forward.

01:17:43.460 --> 01:17:46.020
[Guest]: Sab kuch hoye jaa raha hai, mere saath toh sab acha hi ho raha hai.

01:17:46.020 --> 01:17:50.760
[Guest]: So on one hand, I will say, you know, I don't want, you know, I'm not cheesing this.

01:17:50.760 --> 01:17:52.300
[Guest]: But then things also come to me, right?

01:17:52.300 --> 01:17:59.300
[Guest]: So this whole calculus is that ki haan, agar mene wo chhod bhi diya, right, still things

01:17:59.300 --> 01:18:00.300
[Guest]: are happening to me.

01:18:00.300 --> 01:18:02.380
[Guest]: Toh then you realize ki actually uska point hi nahi hai.

01:18:02.380 --> 01:18:05.340
[Guest]: Like in 2017, I quit Twitter, okay?

01:18:05.340 --> 01:18:09.540
[Guest]: I read this book Deep Work by Cal Newport, usme ek chapter tha Quit Social Media.

01:18:09.540 --> 01:18:13.900
[Guest]: I don't know if any book has led me to a direct impact right after reading.

01:18:13.900 --> 01:18:17.340
[Guest]: Maine wo pada chapter, agle din mein gaya and I deleted my Twitter, not deactivated.

01:18:17.340 --> 01:18:19.100
[Guest]: Abhi mera deactivated hai.

01:18:19.100 --> 01:18:22.900
[Guest]: Uswaqt I deleted ki go.

01:18:22.900 --> 01:18:26.620
[Guest]: And I was away from Twitter for at least eight months, no presence.

01:18:26.620 --> 01:18:30.260
[Guest]: In that duration Amit, when eight months I was not on Twitter, I was not on Facebook,

01:18:30.260 --> 01:18:33.060
[Guest]: I got the best opportunity in my career.

01:18:33.060 --> 01:18:36.900
[Guest]: I got selected for this fellowship at the Wall Street Journal.

01:18:36.900 --> 01:18:42.860
[Guest]: And that day I was thinking ki I am always told that, you know, aapko apna brand banana

01:18:42.860 --> 01:18:46.740
[Guest]: padega, aapko you have to show your work, which is not wrong.

01:18:46.740 --> 01:18:52.940
[Guest]: I am saying in that phase, there is a fellowship I got purely out of like, I think it had very

01:18:52.940 --> 01:18:53.940
[Guest]: little to do with me.

01:18:53.940 --> 01:18:56.780
[Guest]: It was more about circumstances, not my effort.

01:18:56.780 --> 01:18:57.780
[Guest]: But I got it, right?

01:18:57.780 --> 01:18:58.780
[Guest]: When I was not on Twitter.

01:18:58.780 --> 01:19:04.860
[Guest]: So when you see these examples that you don't have followers, your story, aapka share ho

01:19:04.860 --> 01:19:09.740
[Guest]: raha hai, but you are not tagged, your name is coming that Samarth Bansal wrote this story.

01:19:09.740 --> 01:19:15.180
[Guest]: So I'm not gaining followers, nothing, I'm just, but I'm looking at Twitter, right?

01:19:15.180 --> 01:19:16.180
[Guest]: And it's not affecting.

01:19:16.180 --> 01:19:20.860
[Guest]: Then you start saying ki haan yeh anti-metric hi hai, you know, so I'm saying you get that

01:19:20.860 --> 01:19:24.500
[Guest]: framework and then you try to apply it and it kind of works.

01:19:24.500 --> 01:19:30.500
[Guest]: So it's that theory, plus you see it in practice and then it just illuminates that, you know,

01:19:30.500 --> 01:19:33.140
[Guest]: actually that guy was right, this is an anti-metric.

01:19:33.140 --> 01:19:38.180
[Guest]: And then, you know, you, I have my own framework on how I think about career, toh that's it.

01:19:38.180 --> 01:19:43.500
[Guest]: I think that's where, I think I've digressed quite a bit, but that's the, I think the,

01:19:43.500 --> 01:19:46.220
[Guest]: I'm just giving you a glimpse into how I think about some of these things.

01:19:46.220 --> 01:19:49.300
[Amit Varma]: No, I love this because I haven't thought of this frame before and I'm actually after

01:19:49.300 --> 01:19:53.140
[Amit Varma]: the recording probably going to sit down and think about what are the anti-metrics that

01:19:53.140 --> 01:19:54.140
[Amit Varma]: I should ignore.

01:19:54.140 --> 01:19:58.420
[Amit Varma]: Like maine bhi awards ke liye enter ki hai waise, pehle jeeta bhi hoon, lekin looking

01:19:58.420 --> 01:20:02.380
[Amit Varma]: back, it's not like, it's not something I would do today, but I've done it because you

01:20:02.380 --> 01:20:04.580
[Amit Varma]: are sort of insecure.

01:20:04.580 --> 01:20:07.660
[Amit Varma]: There are times you feel underappreciated, toh matlab uska faida hota hai.

01:20:07.660 --> 01:20:12.340
[Amit Varma]: I remember, you know, in the 1990s, someone who was a good friend of mine then and is

01:20:12.340 --> 01:20:15.780
[Amit Varma]: a famous novelist now, told me something when we were having dinner.

01:20:15.780 --> 01:20:20.580
[Amit Varma]: And he said that Amit every time a friend of mine does well, a part of me dies, right?

01:20:20.580 --> 01:20:28.020
[Amit Varma]: And I appreciate the brutal honesty in that because I think that in a sense it is true

01:20:28.020 --> 01:20:29.020
[Amit Varma]: for all of us.

01:20:29.020 --> 01:20:34.780
[Amit Varma]: And, and I've kind of realized that, that wo hai and especially when, you know, and

01:20:34.780 --> 01:20:38.940
[Amit Varma]: I think it'd probably be more true for a third world country, like, you know, that old apocryphal

01:20:38.940 --> 01:20:41.460
[Amit Varma]: thing about crabs pulling each other down.

01:20:41.460 --> 01:20:45.300
[Amit Varma]: And and the reason the story is told about India is that we've grown up in the culture

01:20:45.300 --> 01:20:50.060
[Amit Varma]: of scarcity, where because you are not doing well, we are playing negative sum games or

01:20:50.060 --> 01:20:52.780
[Amit Varma]: zero sum games, you want to pull other people down.

01:20:52.780 --> 01:20:56.700
[Amit Varma]: And hopefully, as a cultural mindset that is changing today.

01:20:56.700 --> 01:20:58.620
[Amit Varma]: And that's sort of something to watch out for.

01:20:58.620 --> 01:21:03.260
[Amit Varma]: Like another thing that I try to do in my own life is I try to get away from toxicity

01:21:03.260 --> 01:21:04.260
[Amit Varma]: and negativity.

01:21:04.260 --> 01:21:08.980
[Amit Varma]: Like maine ek dekha hai ki there are WhatsApp groups I used to be part of, where the whole

01:21:08.980 --> 01:21:12.260
[Amit Varma]: conversation poora din would just be negative.

01:21:12.260 --> 01:21:17.300
[Amit Varma]: They would be shitting on someone, kisi ka screenshot laga diya, and, you know, all of

01:21:17.300 --> 01:21:18.300
[Amit Varma]: that.

01:21:18.300 --> 01:21:21.300
[Amit Varma]: And obviously shitting on someone makes you feel good about yourself, right?

01:21:21.300 --> 01:21:23.020
[Amit Varma]: And that was a whole damn conversation.

01:21:23.020 --> 01:21:24.380
[Amit Varma]: This is your friend's group.

01:21:24.380 --> 01:21:25.380
[Amit Varma]: It is a friend's group.

01:21:25.380 --> 01:21:26.380
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:21:26.380 --> 01:21:30.340
[Amit Varma]: And, and I left many of these groups and I said, I don't want to be around toxicity,

01:21:30.340 --> 01:21:33.420
[Unknown]: where you're just shitting on the world all the time.

01:21:33.420 --> 01:21:38.060
[Amit Varma]: And I'm not saying be mindlessly positive and all of that, but didn't want that.

01:21:38.060 --> 01:21:41.860
[Amit Varma]: But then, you know, the one group that I take pleasure from being part of is, you know,

01:21:41.860 --> 01:21:45.580
[Amit Varma]: all my writing students formed this online group called the clear writing community,

01:21:45.580 --> 01:21:47.700
[Amit Varma]: and we have our WhatsApp group.

01:21:47.700 --> 01:21:50.540
[Amit Varma]: And there I realized that it's positivity.

01:21:50.540 --> 01:21:53.540
[Amit Varma]: I mean, there's no negativity, there's an absence of negativity.

01:21:53.540 --> 01:21:57.540
[Amit Varma]: And you realize that if anybody does well, everybody else will be happy for that person,

01:21:57.540 --> 01:21:58.540
[Amit Varma]: genuinely happy.

01:21:58.540 --> 01:22:02.820
[Amit Varma]: You know, yeh koi feeling nahi hogi peeche ki, arey yaar yeh toh yasa hai, isko kaise

01:22:02.820 --> 01:22:04.140
[Amit Varma]: ho gaya, you know.

01:22:04.140 --> 01:22:09.540
[Amit Varma]: And that might be, and I'm just thinking aloud, because we are not playing any one of those

01:22:09.540 --> 01:22:14.100
[Amit Varma]: competitive games, we're not in the same game, we are not, you know, we happen to be there

01:22:14.100 --> 01:22:16.220
[Amit Varma]: together because of a shared interest.

01:22:16.220 --> 01:22:17.220
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:22:17.220 --> 01:22:20.580
[Amit Varma]: But, you know, I would imagine, for example, a cooking group on Facebook would be something

01:22:20.580 --> 01:22:23.740
[Amit Varma]: like this, where you would not have that negativity.

01:22:23.740 --> 01:22:29.740
[Amit Varma]: Because kuch competition nahi hai, you know, you're all engaged in different games.

01:22:29.740 --> 01:22:34.220
[Amit Varma]: And the only way that any interaction makes sense is if you can learn a nice recipe from

01:22:34.220 --> 01:22:37.460
[Unknown]: someone or if you can say ki yaha kya karna hai, waha kya karna hai.

01:22:37.460 --> 01:22:39.740
[Amit Varma]: And I'm just sort of thinking aloud.

01:22:39.740 --> 01:22:43.860
[Amit Varma]: You've told me about these anti-metrics, and I think we can all figure out what our anti-metrics

01:22:43.860 --> 01:22:44.860
[Amit Varma]: are.

01:22:44.860 --> 01:22:45.860
[Amit Varma]: What are your metrics?

01:22:45.860 --> 01:22:47.860
[Guest]: What are my metrics?

01:22:47.860 --> 01:22:52.180
[Guest]: Okay, so my metrics, let's, I mean, I can tell you about now.

01:22:52.180 --> 01:23:01.340
[Guest]: So now I am, I'll tell you, so, so, okay, where I am right now, I am, I've decided just

01:23:01.340 --> 01:23:07.500
[Guest]: recently, actually, you know, I had this courage to write in my journal, these words, I want

01:23:07.500 --> 01:23:08.500
[Guest]: to be a writer.

01:23:08.500 --> 01:23:14.220
[Guest]: You know, I, you know, I think I've, my whole journey since I started my blog, you know,

01:23:14.220 --> 01:23:19.020
[Guest]: and became a journalist, I never, you know, could use this word for myself, as like mein

01:23:19.020 --> 01:23:22.140
[Guest]: reporter hoon, mein article likhta hoon, but mein writer nahi hoon.

01:23:22.140 --> 01:23:28.340
[Guest]: You know, there's this whole sense of, like, I don't belong, you know, to like, there's

01:23:28.340 --> 01:23:32.700
[Guest]: something, you know, I don't know, it's just weird, but because I love reading books and

01:23:32.700 --> 01:23:40.060
[Guest]: writers, so like, bhai wo, that's not me, you know, so that sense, but somehow I got

01:23:40.060 --> 01:23:45.220
[Guest]: the courage to tell myself that, you know, ab jo hoga dekhenge, ab apne aapko toh bol

01:23:45.220 --> 01:23:49.380
[Guest]: diya maine, that, you know, I want to be a writer, ab bol diya toh karo, you know what

01:23:49.380 --> 01:23:53.460
[Guest]: I mean, that you have declared to yourself, like, you know, when I declared to myself

01:23:53.460 --> 01:23:58.060
[Guest]: in grade 7, that I want to be a software engineer, and you work towards it, right, ab jo hoga

01:23:58.060 --> 01:24:00.500
[Guest]: dekhenge, so that happened recently.

01:24:00.500 --> 01:24:04.980
[Guest]: So I was then thinking that, okay, ab bol diya hai, toh ab iska meaning kya hai, right,

01:24:04.980 --> 01:24:05.980
[Guest]: what does it mean?

01:24:05.980 --> 01:24:10.660
[Guest]: So then I started thinking that ismein, this whole tension between, that I observed in

01:24:10.660 --> 01:24:18.580
[Guest]: any creative field, is that it's very hard to have a objective metric, it's, you know,

01:24:18.580 --> 01:24:23.820
[Guest]: so I dabbled two worlds, I'm a journalist, but I'm still a software, like, I love writing

01:24:23.820 --> 01:24:29.220
[Guest]: software, it's just that over the period of time, my love for words overtook my love for

01:24:29.220 --> 01:24:30.220
[Guest]: writing code.

01:24:30.220 --> 01:24:32.100
[Guest]: Okay, so that has happened.

01:24:32.100 --> 01:24:34.340
[Guest]: But that one point I was thinking, okay, you know, there are comparisons between these

01:24:34.340 --> 01:24:35.340
[Guest]: two things.

01:24:35.340 --> 01:24:39.940
[Guest]: Fundamentally, both are acts of creation, you think something, yahan pe aap code se kar

01:24:39.940 --> 01:24:43.300
[Guest]: rahe ho, wahan shabdo se kar rahe ho, right, so they are acts of creation, it's just that

01:24:43.300 --> 01:24:44.760
[Guest]: one overtook the other.

01:24:44.760 --> 01:24:50.980
[Guest]: In my other world, in the computer science world, you can still see some metrics, right,

01:24:50.980 --> 01:24:54.660
[Guest]: after you have created something, right?

01:24:54.660 --> 01:24:59.420
[Guest]: You know, it's just bits and atoms kind of thing, right, you can, chahe aapne product

01:24:59.420 --> 01:25:04.180
[Guest]: banaya ho, toh you can see users, if it's in a business setting, you can see revenue,

01:25:04.180 --> 01:25:05.740
[Guest]: all sorts of things.

01:25:05.740 --> 01:25:13.900
[Guest]: In this world, I said, it's a tension because I want to be read, but that I don't want the

01:25:13.900 --> 01:25:18.740
[Guest]: want to be read to take over the fundamental desire of creation, right?

01:25:18.740 --> 01:25:22.220
[Guest]: So jab mein yeh sab pe, I was thinking about it, I got this brilliant frame from Ira Glass.

01:25:22.220 --> 01:25:23.220
[Guest]: Do you know Ira Glass?

01:25:23.220 --> 01:25:24.220
[Guest]: I've heard the name.

01:25:24.220 --> 01:25:28.440
[Guest]: So Ira Glass is this master of radio storytelling in the US.

01:25:28.440 --> 01:25:33.100
[Guest]: He started this podcast in the, not radio at the time, This American Life, and then

01:25:33.100 --> 01:25:36.300
[Guest]: Serial, which I think Serial just exploded, right?

01:25:36.300 --> 01:25:40.180
[Guest]: So I've read a lot about Ira's work and how he thinks.

01:25:40.180 --> 01:25:45.980
[Guest]: And I saw this, his two minute clip on YouTube, and I think anyone in creative profession

01:25:45.980 --> 01:25:46.980
[Amit Varma]: should watch it.

01:25:46.980 --> 01:25:48.500
[Amit Varma]: I think I know the one you're talking about.

01:25:48.500 --> 01:25:49.500
[Guest]: Taste and talent.

01:25:49.500 --> 01:25:50.620
[Guest]: Yeah, exactly.

01:25:50.620 --> 01:25:51.620
[Guest]: So that is the thing.

01:25:51.620 --> 01:25:53.060
[Guest]: So I'll just describe it.

01:25:53.060 --> 01:25:57.260
[Guest]: So Ira says that the reason why people start doing creative work is that they have some

01:25:57.260 --> 01:26:02.440
[Guest]: idea of, you know, the taste that they have about, okay, like, for me, what is that piece

01:26:02.440 --> 01:26:08.220
[Guest]: of writing I want to do, but my talent is not at par to deliver that taste.

01:26:08.220 --> 01:26:14.380
[Guest]: So it's a journey that you take to bridge that gap between where your talent is and

01:26:14.380 --> 01:26:15.620
[Guest]: where your taste is.

01:26:15.620 --> 01:26:20.900
[Guest]: But he says the problem is that the gap is so huge, and it takes years to fill that gap

01:26:20.900 --> 01:26:24.800
[Guest]: that a lot of people just give up because they feel they are not good enough.

01:26:24.800 --> 01:26:29.500
[Guest]: And Ira said this, that I want to tell every creator out there that every single person

01:26:29.500 --> 01:26:32.060
[Guest]: goes through this journey of filling that gap.

01:26:32.060 --> 01:26:35.420
[Guest]: And the only way to fill that gap is to keep creating.

01:26:35.420 --> 01:26:37.900
[Guest]: Put yourself on a deadline and put out stuff.

01:26:37.900 --> 01:26:41.760
[Guest]: And honestly, Amit, you have spoken about this multiple times in your podcast.

01:26:41.760 --> 01:26:45.020
[Guest]: And when I think about my newsletter, I took inspiration from you when you said that, you

01:26:45.020 --> 01:26:50.460
[Guest]: know, don't overthink quality, you know, keep doing stuff, keep doing stuff.

01:26:50.460 --> 01:26:55.580
[Guest]: But when that frame hit me, it just changed the way I think because I'm saying, ha, you

01:26:55.580 --> 01:26:56.700
[Guest]: know, I have a taste.

01:26:56.700 --> 01:26:59.180
[Guest]: There is this kind of piece that I want to write.

01:26:59.180 --> 01:27:01.300
[Guest]: I can't write it today, right?

01:27:01.300 --> 01:27:02.300
[Guest]: But someday I will.

01:27:02.300 --> 01:27:06.780
[Guest]: And, you know, in this whole process, something brilliant happened in 2018.

01:27:06.780 --> 01:27:11.340
[Guest]: And I have a page in my diary where I described a certain kind of piece I wanted to write.

01:27:11.340 --> 01:27:12.940
[Guest]: And I don't want to get into details.

01:27:12.940 --> 01:27:14.220
[Guest]: It's very personal.

01:27:14.220 --> 01:27:18.540
[Guest]: But I wrote something this year that met that bar, you know.

01:27:18.540 --> 01:27:23.980
[Guest]: And of course, as your own evolution of your own creative process and what you want, you

01:27:23.980 --> 01:27:26.020
[Guest]: know, that thing keeps changing.

01:27:26.020 --> 01:27:31.580
[Guest]: So that gave me confidence that if after 4 years, what I wrote in 2018, that I want to

01:27:31.580 --> 01:27:33.380
[Guest]: write a piece like this.

01:27:33.380 --> 01:27:38.220
[Guest]: And the world will not recognize this because that is, that is like, who will know what

01:27:38.220 --> 01:27:43.060
[Guest]: I wanted to write and I have created, you know, 5 people may say it's great work, you

01:27:43.060 --> 01:27:44.500
[Guest]: know, 10 may say it's not that great.

01:27:44.500 --> 01:27:46.300
[Guest]: It's an ordinary piece of writing.

01:27:46.300 --> 01:27:52.740
[Guest]: But even those appreciation of 5 cannot, you know, match with the feeling that something

01:27:52.740 --> 01:27:55.580
[Guest]: I thought 4 years ago is today in front of me.

01:27:55.580 --> 01:28:01.460
[Guest]: So I have, and because I'm this math nerd, and you know, the world, like the world looks

01:28:01.460 --> 01:28:03.700
[Guest]: like a set of metrics, etc.

01:28:03.700 --> 01:28:09.460
[Guest]: I had to work very hard on myself to get out of that zone and take comfort in abstract

01:28:09.460 --> 01:28:12.180
[Guest]: where there is no objective metric.

01:28:12.180 --> 01:28:20.580
[Guest]: But there are metrics and the metric is on a day-to-day basis, like, am I creating?

01:28:20.580 --> 01:28:25.320
[Guest]: Is my writing better than what I was writing a month ago, right?

01:28:25.320 --> 01:28:29.000
[Guest]: Is there something, you know, it's very hard to put in words, but there is something intrinsic

01:28:29.000 --> 01:28:30.300
[Guest]: in that process.

01:28:30.300 --> 01:28:35.100
[Guest]: You know, like, for example, you read a, I read a piece I wrote, is there a sentence

01:28:35.100 --> 01:28:40.620
[Guest]: that I wrote, which just feels that, wow, I was able to write the sentence.

01:28:40.620 --> 01:28:46.780
[Guest]: It just gives me joy if that sentence comes, if the sound of a paragraph, to me, sounds

01:28:46.780 --> 01:28:50.620
[Guest]: like, oh, I actually could not write this paragraph a year ago.

01:28:50.620 --> 01:28:56.420
[Guest]: So I have tuned my, I don't know, feelings, brain, whatever, to take comfort in this.

01:28:56.420 --> 01:29:01.380
[Guest]: Though, of course, like, I think I would not deny that it matters that, you know, I recently

01:29:01.380 --> 01:29:05.780
[Guest]: launched a newsletter with a friend on food and fitness, something different I'm trying

01:29:05.780 --> 01:29:06.780
[Guest]: to do.

01:29:06.780 --> 01:29:10.500
[Guest]: And of course, like, you know, I'm observing, like, yesterday, the first issue went out

01:29:10.500 --> 01:29:12.780
[Guest]: and we are trying to create something unique in our heads.

01:29:12.780 --> 01:29:15.500
[Guest]: Now, what that will be, we will know from reader feedback.

01:29:15.500 --> 01:29:18.740
[Guest]: So I'm looking forward to how many people are replying to the email, right?

01:29:18.740 --> 01:29:22.860
[Guest]: I just checked this morning, are people sharing it on Twitter, right?

01:29:22.860 --> 01:29:23.860
[Guest]: Is it working?

01:29:23.860 --> 01:29:25.660
[Guest]: I shared it on my Instagram.

01:29:25.660 --> 01:29:26.660
[Guest]: What is the feedback?

01:29:26.660 --> 01:29:27.660
[Guest]: Right.

01:29:27.660 --> 01:29:33.300
[Guest]: And when someone just says, you know, as a writer, there is a, and writer not like I

01:29:33.300 --> 01:29:34.940
[Guest]: don't write fiction or, you know, any abstract things.

01:29:34.940 --> 01:29:38.940
[Guest]: I just write like informative stuff in a way I want to tell a story.

01:29:38.940 --> 01:29:47.260
[Guest]: If someone gets the intent that, you know, this is what I was trying to do, like the

01:29:47.260 --> 01:29:52.140
[Guest]: feeling I wanted someone to take back, ye take away tha, if this, the response comes,

01:29:52.140 --> 01:29:58.460
[Guest]: that, you know, oh, this part of my brain clicked, this is what I felt after it, then

01:29:58.460 --> 01:30:05.420
[Guest]: I get a deep sense of satisfaction that what I was trying to do with my words has happened.

01:30:05.420 --> 01:30:10.420
[Guest]: You know, that it's not unclear, like I have, there's an objective with which I went into

01:30:10.420 --> 01:30:11.420
[Guest]: a piece.

01:30:11.420 --> 01:30:14.340
[Guest]: Either I'm editing it or I'm writing it.

01:30:14.340 --> 01:30:15.340
[Guest]: And that was delivered.

01:30:15.340 --> 01:30:19.700
[Guest]: Now those three people say it, but you know, if those three people don't say it, it hurts.

01:30:19.700 --> 01:30:23.580
[Guest]: There's a practical example I wrote, my last story of my newsletter, after which I discontinued

01:30:23.580 --> 01:30:26.060
[Guest]: was on polling, forecasting, election forecasting.

01:30:26.060 --> 01:30:29.460
[Guest]: Amit, on that piece, that's one of the hardest stories I've worked on.

01:30:29.460 --> 01:30:33.620
[Guest]: I spent a whole month, one full month of effort to write that piece.

01:30:33.620 --> 01:30:38.500
[Guest]: And I got the least feedback on email on that piece because it was a nerdy piece.

01:30:38.500 --> 01:30:43.180
[Guest]: And back end I knew it was a nerdy piece, but I really, you know, my own, in my head,

01:30:43.180 --> 01:30:46.820
[Guest]: I try to do things to make it interesting, whatever, whatever.

01:30:46.820 --> 01:30:50.260
[Guest]: But there was, I got very little feedback, right?

01:30:50.260 --> 01:30:53.780
[Guest]: So I got, I got a little bit of feedback, but it was great.

01:30:53.780 --> 01:30:56.380
[Guest]: But it was only from people who know the subject.

01:30:56.380 --> 01:31:04.060
[Guest]: So I was like, okay, job done, I mean, I cracked it for myself, but the itch remained that,

01:31:04.060 --> 01:31:07.740
[Guest]: you know, I just didn't want to write it for people who are interested in forecasting.

01:31:07.740 --> 01:31:08.900
[Guest]: I wanted to do something else.

01:31:08.900 --> 01:31:11.860
[Guest]: So now I have it in my head that I'm done for now.

01:31:11.860 --> 01:31:14.900
[Guest]: Now I will write a piece on election forecasting after five years.

01:31:14.900 --> 01:31:19.900
[Guest]: I know the thing, but I want to write it in a way that people who did not respond now,

01:31:19.900 --> 01:31:22.340
[Guest]: maybe they connect with it, you know, something like that.

01:31:22.340 --> 01:31:27.900
[Guest]: So this is, I know, I mean, that's a metric, that's like, I can't quantify it, but I feel

01:31:27.900 --> 01:31:28.900
[Guest]: it.

01:31:28.900 --> 01:31:29.900
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:31:29.900 --> 01:31:33.740
[Amit Varma]: I was thinking while you were answering, I asked that question to myself, what's my metric?

01:31:33.740 --> 01:31:39.020
[Amit Varma]: And then I realized that for the things that I want to do, my metric is just getting it

01:31:39.020 --> 01:31:40.020
[Unknown]: done.

01:31:40.020 --> 01:31:41.020
[Unknown]: Yeah.

01:31:41.020 --> 01:31:42.020
[Amit Varma]: You know, and nothing more than that.

01:31:42.020 --> 01:31:47.420
[Amit Varma]: I actually come at it, you know, without using the terms Ira Glass does, I talk about the

01:31:47.420 --> 01:31:50.860
[Amit Varma]: same kind of thing in my writing course, where I talk about process and I come at it from

01:31:50.860 --> 01:31:54.020
[Amit Varma]: a poker point of view and therefore a probabilistic point of view.

01:31:54.020 --> 01:31:59.420
[Amit Varma]: So you'll appreciate that, which is that in poker, we know that while it's a game of skill,

01:31:59.420 --> 01:32:03.900
[Amit Varma]: the quantum of luck is so high that you cannot focus on short-term results, right?

01:32:03.900 --> 01:32:08.940
[Amit Varma]: You have to put in volume only over large sample sizes, does your edge manifest itself?

01:32:08.940 --> 01:32:13.700
[Amit Varma]: So the first mantra of a good poker player always is don't be results oriented, the process

01:32:13.700 --> 01:32:14.700
[Amit Varma]: matters.

01:32:14.700 --> 01:32:15.700
[Amit Varma]: Process matters.

01:32:15.700 --> 01:32:16.700
[Amit Varma]: And where is this relevant in writing?

01:32:16.700 --> 01:32:21.500
[Amit Varma]: This is relevant because what often happens is that you will write something and you will

01:32:21.500 --> 01:32:23.620
[Amit Varma]: feel like it is shit, right?

01:32:23.620 --> 01:32:28.300
[Amit Varma]: And a beginning writer will use this as a reason to give up.

01:32:28.300 --> 01:32:29.300
[Unknown]: Yes.

01:32:29.300 --> 01:32:30.300
[Amit Varma]: Right.

01:32:30.300 --> 01:32:32.500
[Amit Varma]: And my contention always is twofold, right?

01:32:32.500 --> 01:32:37.020
[Amit Varma]: Number one, and this I feel very, very strongly and passionately about, there are a lot of

01:32:37.020 --> 01:32:43.580
[Amit Varma]: things in which a natural talent is needed, like if you want to be a musician, you want

01:32:43.580 --> 01:32:48.980
[Amit Varma]: to be a batsman, you need some hand-eye coordination, all of those things are not needed in writing.

01:32:48.980 --> 01:32:52.260
[Amit Varma]: You know, anybody can work hard and lift that level.

01:32:52.260 --> 01:32:57.340
[Amit Varma]: And the other thing, just using different terms in glass, but pretty much the same idea

01:32:57.340 --> 01:33:02.740
[Amit Varma]: is that when you don't like something that you have written, all it means is that your

01:33:02.740 --> 01:33:05.660
[Amit Varma]: judgment is better than your ability.

01:33:05.660 --> 01:33:10.860
[Amit Varma]: You have these two things, your judgment is better than your ability.

01:33:10.860 --> 01:33:15.780
[Amit Varma]: The question to then ask is, how does my ability rise to the level of my judgment or at least

01:33:15.780 --> 01:33:16.780
[Amit Varma]: get closer?

01:33:16.780 --> 01:33:17.780
[Amit Varma]: Right?

01:33:17.780 --> 01:33:20.180
[Amit Varma]: Because your judgment will just keep going up, obviously.

01:33:20.180 --> 01:33:25.420
[Amit Varma]: And there is only one answer to that and that answer is to keep writing, to trust the process

01:33:25.420 --> 01:33:27.420
[Amit Varma]: and therefore don't be results oriented.

01:33:27.420 --> 01:33:29.620
[Amit Varma]: Sometimes what happens is you write something you think is shit, you're just being hard

01:33:29.620 --> 01:33:30.620
[Amit Varma]: on yourself.

01:33:30.620 --> 01:33:35.100
[Amit Varma]: But my point is that especially when you're learning writing or anything for that matter,

01:33:35.100 --> 01:33:38.380
[Amit Varma]: you will suck at the beginning, always, right?

01:33:38.380 --> 01:33:41.540
[Amit Varma]: So the important thing is to recognize that, yes, I suck.

01:33:41.540 --> 01:33:43.340
[Unknown]: It is good that I know I suck.

01:33:43.340 --> 01:33:46.220
[Unknown]: Now let me work at it and get somewhere.

01:33:46.220 --> 01:33:50.260
[Amit Varma]: And in that trade-off between getting it done and getting it right, the important thing

01:33:50.260 --> 01:33:51.260
[Amit Varma]: is to get it done.

01:33:51.260 --> 01:33:52.260
[Amit Varma]: Right.

01:33:52.260 --> 01:33:53.260
[Amit Varma]: Absolutely.

01:33:53.260 --> 01:33:56.220
[Amit Varma]: And the only way to get it right is to get it done again and again.

01:33:56.220 --> 01:34:01.100
[Amit Varma]: Like it's almost like quantity having a quality of its own, you know, you'll reach there.

01:34:01.100 --> 01:34:07.180
[Guest]: I read a short story, I don't know if it's fiction, it's a very short story on quantity

01:34:07.180 --> 01:34:12.980
[Guest]: quality where there was this pottery class and I'm just paraphrasing, so there was this

01:34:12.980 --> 01:34:18.860
[Guest]: divided into two groups, one was told to focus on quality, one was told on quantity.

01:34:18.860 --> 01:34:23.740
[Guest]: And then they saw results and like the quantity group had created like 50 pots and this quality

01:34:23.740 --> 01:34:29.220
[Guest]: group was thinking about how to make it, they theorized, you know, they were going all directions

01:34:29.220 --> 01:34:31.020
[Guest]: and they came up with one pot.

01:34:31.020 --> 01:34:35.860
[Guest]: And the 50th pot from the quantity group was significantly better than the quality group

01:34:35.860 --> 01:34:40.540
[Guest]: because they were just creating, creating, creating.

01:34:40.540 --> 01:34:43.860
[Guest]: They just created, found their mistake, created the next one.

01:34:43.860 --> 01:34:48.700
[Guest]: And in that progression, you know, the 50th one was just better than the one that the

01:34:48.700 --> 01:34:50.460
[Guest]: quality group created.

01:34:50.460 --> 01:34:56.340
[Guest]: So when I read that, I was like, I had this whole anxiety in the middle, you know, I want

01:34:56.340 --> 01:34:58.700
[Guest]: a time when I can just write one story in four months.

01:34:58.700 --> 01:35:01.340
[Guest]: Kitna maza aayega, you know, I should have that liberty.

01:35:01.340 --> 01:35:04.860
[Guest]: I mean, I'm not saying that I don't want it, maybe it would be great.

01:35:04.860 --> 01:35:09.420
[Guest]: But when I started, I observed that agar main har do hafte mein if I'm publishing, you know,

01:35:09.420 --> 01:35:12.860
[Guest]: on a day to day basis, it's like, you know, it's like being in a gym that if you're lifting

01:35:12.860 --> 01:35:17.900
[Guest]: weight and you know, you're adding muscle, to agar aap teen mehne ke liye chhod doge,

01:35:17.900 --> 01:35:22.580
[Guest]: then you start again, you know, I don't know if the analogy works clearly for a creative

01:35:22.580 --> 01:35:26.860
[Guest]: process, but at least that's, that's what I saw that it's just like muscle building

01:35:26.860 --> 01:35:29.180
[Guest]: that you keep doing it.

01:35:29.180 --> 01:35:32.020
[Guest]: And you'll get better, there is.

01:35:32.020 --> 01:35:34.740
[Amit Varma]: And that's where the importance of journaling also comes in.

01:35:34.740 --> 01:35:37.140
[Amit Varma]: Because if you go to a gym, the key is regularity.

01:35:37.140 --> 01:35:41.300
[Amit Varma]: Aisa nahi hai ki aapne annual membership le liye, aap chaar din gaye aur phir aapki body

01:35:41.300 --> 01:35:42.300
[Unknown]: ban gayi.

01:35:42.300 --> 01:35:44.300
[Unknown]: And you're saying, maine toh paise de diye, body kyun nahi bani?

01:35:44.300 --> 01:35:45.300
[Amit Varma]: Right?

01:35:45.300 --> 01:35:46.300
[Amit Varma]: Right.

01:35:46.300 --> 01:35:47.740
[Amit Varma]: You got to build a habit and go every day and get the job done.

01:35:47.740 --> 01:35:49.220
[Amit Varma]: And writing is exactly like that.

01:35:49.220 --> 01:35:53.900
[Amit Varma]: And a habit of journaling is a good way of doing that.

01:35:53.900 --> 01:35:57.940
[Amit Varma]: Because then you don't have to, you're not in a position where you don't have anything

01:35:57.940 --> 01:35:58.940
[Amit Varma]: to write about.

01:35:58.940 --> 01:35:59.940
[Unknown]: And you're saying ki kya likhu?

01:35:59.940 --> 01:36:03.140
[Amit Varma]: If you're doing a daily journal, you always have something to write about, because you

01:36:03.140 --> 01:36:04.780
[Amit Varma]: always have yourself.

01:36:04.780 --> 01:36:09.900
[Amit Varma]: And the advice I give my writing students is ki aap target mat banao, ki din meh 1000

01:36:09.900 --> 01:36:11.140
[Unknown]: word likhne hai, 2000 word.

01:36:11.140 --> 01:36:17.100
[Amit Varma]: You know, the target you should set yourself is 200 words, 200 words.

01:36:17.100 --> 01:36:20.900
[Amit Varma]: And because 200 words is something we speak in a minute, right?

01:36:20.900 --> 01:36:22.020
[Amit Varma]: Ek minute ki baat hai.

01:36:22.020 --> 01:36:25.700
[Amit Varma]: So even if you're, you know, going going to the airport, you have two flights to catch

01:36:25.700 --> 01:36:30.260
[Amit Varma]: in a day, you can type 200 words on your smartphone, kuch hai hi nahi, maine toh column sholums

01:36:30.260 --> 01:36:33.100
[Amit Varma]: bhi likhiye apne phone pe, perhaps not to good effect.

01:36:33.100 --> 01:36:36.300
[Amit Varma]: But you can, 200 word toh smartphone pe bhi kar sakte hai.

01:36:36.300 --> 01:36:40.180
[Amit Varma]: And the important thing is number one, if you fall off the wagon, you know, you can

01:36:40.180 --> 01:36:41.180
[Amit Varma]: get back on easily.

01:36:41.180 --> 01:36:42.180
[Amit Varma]: Kya hoda na?

01:36:42.180 --> 01:36:47.260
[Amit Varma]: If people set themselves target of 1000 words a day, right, likhte hai, 3-4 din likhte hai,

01:36:47.260 --> 01:36:50.100
[Amit Varma]: then they fall off the wagon, then they find it hard to get on.

01:36:50.100 --> 01:36:54.740
[Amit Varma]: And then it becomes a vicious circle where they tell themselves ki yeh toh mere se nahi

01:36:54.740 --> 01:36:55.740
[Amit Varma]: hoga.

01:36:55.740 --> 01:36:57.500
[Amit Varma]: You know, being a writer is not in me.

01:36:57.500 --> 01:37:02.100
[Amit Varma]: And it becomes a vicious circle where their failure to maintain a habit affects their

01:37:02.100 --> 01:37:03.420
[Amit Varma]: self-image.

01:37:03.420 --> 01:37:05.260
[Amit Varma]: And it's just a race to the bottom.

01:37:05.260 --> 01:37:06.660
[Amit Varma]: And they never end up doing it.

01:37:06.660 --> 01:37:08.980
[Amit Varma]: While 200 words is nothing.

01:37:08.980 --> 01:37:12.380
[Amit Varma]: And obviously, you will not write only 200 words.

01:37:12.380 --> 01:37:16.700
[Amit Varma]: If the 200 word is and, you are not going to say ki aaj ka quota khatam.

01:37:16.700 --> 01:37:17.900
[Amit Varma]: You continue.

01:37:17.900 --> 01:37:19.240
[Amit Varma]: And very often you'll write more.

01:37:19.240 --> 01:37:24.540
[Amit Varma]: But the important thing is, number one, 200 words a day for a year is about 75,000 words.

01:37:24.540 --> 01:37:25.540
[Unknown]: That's a lot of words.

01:37:25.540 --> 01:37:28.060
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, that's a lot of words, right?

01:37:28.060 --> 01:37:32.380
[Amit Varma]: And number two, aapki writing muscle kya se kya ho jayegi?

01:37:32.380 --> 01:37:36.180
[Amit Varma]: You know, so at the end of a year, and I've told many of my students this, and some of

01:37:36.180 --> 01:37:40.860
[Amit Varma]: them have, you know, carried it out, I'm proud to say, and at the end of a year, you look

01:37:40.860 --> 01:37:45.980
[Amit Varma]: back on what you wrote on day one, and you're like, you realize how powerful the force of

01:37:45.980 --> 01:37:46.980
[Amit Varma]: habit is.

01:37:46.980 --> 01:37:49.620
[Guest]: Can I ask you a question?

01:37:49.620 --> 01:37:56.460
[Guest]: So you know, I have this big circle who have like no connection in the world of journalism

01:37:56.460 --> 01:37:57.460
[Guest]: and writing.

01:37:57.460 --> 01:37:58.460
[Guest]: That's the world I come from.

01:37:58.460 --> 01:38:02.060
[Guest]: So they asked me for advice that, how do you get published?

01:38:02.060 --> 01:38:05.260
[Guest]: Okay, they want to like, you know, I think so many people want to write.

01:38:05.260 --> 01:38:10.060
[Guest]: And one of the things that irritates me is that, when they know to aap kitab likhoge

01:38:10.060 --> 01:38:11.060
[Guest]: kya?

01:38:11.060 --> 01:38:13.500
[Guest]: And I was like, no, boss, I don't write because I want to be a book writer.

01:38:13.500 --> 01:38:15.820
[Guest]: I just write because of other reasons.

01:38:15.820 --> 01:38:20.860
[Guest]: So people ask me ki hai hume na, I have this viewpoint, main koi akbaar mein chhap wana

01:38:20.860 --> 01:38:21.860
[Guest]: hai.

01:38:21.860 --> 01:38:22.860
[Guest]: Toh kaise karte hain?

01:38:22.860 --> 01:38:23.860
[Guest]: Like, how do you get published in a newspaper?

01:38:23.860 --> 01:38:26.740
[Guest]: Because aapka naam aata hain akbaar mein.

01:38:26.740 --> 01:38:30.500
[Guest]: So then, like, I want to know what advice would you give them?

01:38:30.500 --> 01:38:32.620
[Guest]: I'll tell you what I tell them.

01:38:32.620 --> 01:38:39.620
[Guest]: So I try to tell them that, write as if, abhi aap likho, don't think about getting published

01:38:39.620 --> 01:38:45.940
[Guest]: in a, you know, a Hindustan Times or The Print, kyuki ye aata hai ki, you know, news laundry

01:38:45.940 --> 01:38:46.940
[Guest]: mein chal jayega, yahan chal jayega.

01:38:46.940 --> 01:38:52.980
[Guest]: Toh aapko likhna chalu karna hai na, so start a blog, and in your head think, 10 people

01:38:52.980 --> 01:38:53.980
[Guest]: will read it.

01:38:53.980 --> 01:38:54.980
[Guest]: Thek hai?

01:38:54.980 --> 01:38:59.900
[Guest]: 8, like, 5 baar tum khud padhoge, 3 tumhare dost padhenge, and 2 random people, medium

01:38:59.900 --> 01:39:01.980
[Guest]: mein kisi ne dhoond liya, whatever.

01:39:01.980 --> 01:39:05.060
[Guest]: And just start writing and putting out stuff.

01:39:05.060 --> 01:39:12.700
[Guest]: Don't think of, ki, whether, like, don't let, if a publication is not responding, don't

01:39:12.700 --> 01:39:15.580
[Guest]: stop writing because of that, because it works the other way around.

01:39:15.580 --> 01:39:21.220
[Guest]: And Amit, you know what I have observed, koi karta hi nahi, they don't, if they are not

01:39:21.220 --> 01:39:24.700
[Guest]: getting hearing back from a publication, they just stop writing.

01:39:24.700 --> 01:39:29.300
[Guest]: And I observed similarly in, like, I really love to help anyone who wants to get started

01:39:29.300 --> 01:39:35.700
[Guest]: with writing code, like, it's one of my deep desires to, you know, teach people writing

01:39:35.700 --> 01:39:36.700
[Guest]: Python code.

01:39:36.700 --> 01:39:41.100
[Guest]: Main second year se likh raha hoon, apne college mein, I love the language, you know, it's

01:39:41.100 --> 01:39:43.660
[Guest]: just, you can do anything on the internet with that.

01:39:43.660 --> 01:39:48.700
[Guest]: So I can't tell you the number of people who say, you know, we want to learn this language,

01:39:48.700 --> 01:39:53.940
[Guest]: and then I write them emails, ki aap kuch mat socho, go to this source, then you do

01:39:53.940 --> 01:40:00.220
[Guest]: this, and aapko kahin atak jao na, I am, I'll come on a call and help you, okay.

01:40:00.220 --> 01:40:04.620
[Guest]: Don't think that programming is some, you know, this thing that you need a degree nahi

01:40:04.620 --> 01:40:08.700
[Guest]: chahiye, it's like, agar aap Angrezi bol sakte ho, toh aap Python bhi likh sakte ho, kuch

01:40:08.700 --> 01:40:09.860
[Guest]: bhi nahi hai usme, right.

01:40:09.860 --> 01:40:13.420
[Guest]: It's just if-else statements, that's what's happening.

01:40:13.420 --> 01:40:19.140
[Guest]: That step doesn't happen, like, it's just weird in the last 10 years, I've told so many

01:40:19.140 --> 01:40:23.620
[Guest]: people about code and this starter blog, not a single person has come back.

01:40:23.620 --> 01:40:28.380
[Guest]: So I often wonder, am I giving the wrong advice, or like, what is behind this?

01:40:28.380 --> 01:40:32.220
[Guest]: So do you have any suggestions on, is my approach wrong?

01:40:32.220 --> 01:40:36.780
[Guest]: Because I want to help, and you know, that they become better writers, they're able to

01:40:36.780 --> 01:40:38.260
[Guest]: write code.

01:40:38.260 --> 01:40:40.460
[Guest]: But step one doesn't happen, because no one comes back to me.

01:40:40.460 --> 01:40:42.020
[Amit Varma]: So what would you suggest I do?

01:40:42.020 --> 01:40:47.100
[Amit Varma]: Couple of things here, one, it might be their thin desire, and they don't want it badly

01:40:47.100 --> 01:40:48.100
[Amit Varma]: enough.

01:40:48.100 --> 01:40:51.300
[Amit Varma]: In which case, it doesn't matter what advice you give, woh hoga nahi, because it's driven

01:40:51.300 --> 01:40:52.860
[Amit Varma]: by validation.

01:40:52.860 --> 01:40:56.380
[Amit Varma]: But two, maybe they really want it, let's give them the benefit of the doubt, maybe

01:40:56.380 --> 01:40:57.740
[Amit Varma]: they really want it, ho nahi raha hai.

01:40:57.740 --> 01:41:00.700
[Amit Varma]: I don't think the problem is your advice, I think your advice is great.

01:41:00.700 --> 01:41:04.940
[Amit Varma]: I agree with your advice, but I want to elaborate a bit on the whys of the advice.

01:41:04.940 --> 01:41:09.100
[Amit Varma]: Like, I would give people exactly the same advice as you just gave, but I want to elaborate

01:41:09.100 --> 01:41:10.100
[Amit Varma]: on the why.

01:41:10.100 --> 01:41:14.100
[Amit Varma]: Ab kya tha ki 90s mein when I was starting out, obviously, as a writer, what you want

01:41:14.100 --> 01:41:16.780
[Amit Varma]: to do is you want to, you want your byline.

01:41:16.780 --> 01:41:21.740
[Amit Varma]: Toh then what you think in those days is ki TOI mein bhejo, Express mein bhejo, koi lega,

01:41:21.740 --> 01:41:23.220
[Amit Varma]: bhi nahi lega, all of that.

01:41:23.220 --> 01:41:27.140
[Amit Varma]: Today, I think there's, it's a bad idea for a number of reasons.

01:41:27.140 --> 01:41:30.340
[Amit Varma]: And I want to elaborate why even for a young writer, it's, you know, obviously, it's easy

01:41:30.340 --> 01:41:34.580
[Amit Varma]: for someone like people like you and me to have newsletters, because kuch toh brand hai,

01:41:34.580 --> 01:41:36.180
[Amit Varma]: kuch toh log jaante hai.

01:41:36.180 --> 01:41:37.300
[Amit Varma]: What is a beginner to do?

01:41:37.300 --> 01:41:41.020
[Amit Varma]: I would say even a beginner should start a newsletter or a blog.

01:41:41.020 --> 01:41:42.940
[Amit Varma]: And I'll explain why.

01:41:42.940 --> 01:41:47.820
[Amit Varma]: Number one, what happens when you are sending your work out to these platforms is you're

01:41:47.820 --> 01:41:52.420
[Amit Varma]: going through gatekeepers, those gatekeepers have specific tastes of their own specific

01:41:52.420 --> 01:41:53.860
[Amit Varma]: biases of their own.

01:41:53.860 --> 01:41:57.700
[Amit Varma]: They are often looking for only what is newsworthy or in the news cycle.

01:41:57.700 --> 01:41:59.940
[Amit Varma]: And all of those are restrictions.

01:41:59.940 --> 01:42:04.620
[Amit Varma]: They are looking for only a particular form, like 800 word mein likhna hai, that much space

01:42:04.620 --> 01:42:05.620
[Amit Varma]: they have.

01:42:05.620 --> 01:42:09.980
[Amit Varma]: And all of those are restrictions of form, the necessity to be part of the news cycle,

01:42:09.980 --> 01:42:15.260
[Amit Varma]: the house style that they might have, their particular biases and tastes, all those kind

01:42:15.260 --> 01:42:18.340
[Amit Varma]: of get in the way and you want to avoid those.

01:42:18.340 --> 01:42:23.460
[Amit Varma]: The second thing is that if you go down that circle that I will send op-ed idea, koi achcha

01:42:23.460 --> 01:42:28.820
[Amit Varma]: bolega, phir mein publish karunga, then the point is that you won't be writing enough.

01:42:28.820 --> 01:42:30.500
[Unknown]: You'll be writing once in a while, right?

01:42:30.500 --> 01:42:34.820
[Amit Varma]: You know, TOI aaj lega toh aisa nahi ki agli hafte aur ek piece aapko denge, you'll have

01:42:34.820 --> 01:42:39.860
[Amit Varma]: enough of a network ki kahi na kahi aapka har week aa raha hai, you know, very established

01:42:39.860 --> 01:42:40.940
[Amit Varma]: people can build that.

01:42:40.940 --> 01:42:43.340
[Amit Varma]: But otherwise, you won't be writing enough.

01:42:43.340 --> 01:42:45.980
[Amit Varma]: And the key to writing good as we were discussing is write a lot.

01:42:45.980 --> 01:42:49.060
[Amit Varma]: You have to write a lot, you have to go to the writing gym, you got to work out, work

01:42:49.060 --> 01:42:51.900
[Amit Varma]: out, work out, work out, itse wo nahi hoga.

01:42:51.900 --> 01:42:55.420
[Amit Varma]: And also if you're writing sporadically, only when an op-ed editor says ki theek hai kuch

01:42:55.420 --> 01:43:00.340
[Amit Varma]: likho, then you won't even be able to write a good piece kyuki aapki wo habit nahi hai,

01:43:00.340 --> 01:43:04.980
[Amit Varma]: aapki sirf desire hai, lekin wo habit nahi hai ki aap regularly likh rahe ho.

01:43:04.980 --> 01:43:06.820
[Amit Varma]: And this becomes an impediment.

01:43:06.820 --> 01:43:11.940
[Amit Varma]: The third thing is that you are missing out on what I think is a unique opportunity for

01:43:11.940 --> 01:43:15.580
[Amit Varma]: creators in the modern age of building communities of their readers.

01:43:15.580 --> 01:43:18.940
[Amit Varma]: Pehle kya ho raha hai, aapka TOI mein piece aa raha hai, koi dekh raha hai aur bol raha

01:43:18.940 --> 01:43:23.420
[Amit Varma]: hai ki yaar yeh Samarth Bansal tu bahut achcha likha hai, change my mind about data.

01:43:23.420 --> 01:43:24.780
[Amit Varma]: And but they forget about you.

01:43:24.780 --> 01:43:25.780
[Amit Varma]: That's where it is.

01:43:25.780 --> 01:43:28.900
[Amit Varma]: You know, a month later, they look at you in the Indian Express and they'll be like,

01:43:28.900 --> 01:43:31.700
[Amit Varma]: haan matlab naam suna suna lag raha hai, achcha piece hai.

01:43:31.700 --> 01:43:33.140
[Amit Varma]: And then they forget about you.

01:43:33.140 --> 01:43:37.420
[Amit Varma]: But what happens is if somebody comes across a link to your newsletter, they click, they

01:43:37.420 --> 01:43:38.460
[Amit Varma]: read the link.

01:43:38.460 --> 01:43:40.460
[Amit Varma]: And they're saying, yeah, this guy's a good guy.

01:43:40.460 --> 01:43:41.820
[Amit Varma]: And they put their email.

01:43:41.820 --> 01:43:44.860
[Amit Varma]: And everything else you write now goes to them, right?

01:43:44.860 --> 01:43:46.900
[Amit Varma]: It goes into their email box.

01:43:46.900 --> 01:43:48.980
[Amit Varma]: And that email database belongs to you.

01:43:48.980 --> 01:43:51.340
[Amit Varma]: It doesn't belong to a substack or whoever the host is.

01:43:51.340 --> 01:43:53.380
[Amit Varma]: The email database belongs to you.

01:43:53.380 --> 01:43:58.700
[Amit Varma]: And what you have done through this is you formed a community of Samarth Bansal fans.

01:43:58.700 --> 01:44:00.900
[Amit Varma]: And you are always in touch with them.

01:44:00.900 --> 01:44:05.980
[Amit Varma]: Abhi toh aap newsletter likh rahe ho, parsu supposing you have some interesting project,

01:44:05.980 --> 01:44:10.100
[Amit Varma]: you can crowdsource funds, you can write to these guys, aapne agar YouTube channel shuru

01:44:10.100 --> 01:44:15.100
[Amit Varma]: hai, you can, you know, write to these guys and subscribe to this, you've built that community

01:44:15.100 --> 01:44:16.860
[Amit Varma]: that network of people.

01:44:16.860 --> 01:44:20.380
[Amit Varma]: So for that reason, if there is a young person listening to this, and they want to write,

01:44:20.380 --> 01:44:23.940
[Amit Varma]: I will say, first of all, have a bias for action.

01:44:23.940 --> 01:44:27.740
[Amit Varma]: Don't let yourself hold back by what will people think of you right now a nobody's thinking

01:44:27.740 --> 01:44:28.820
[Amit Varma]: of you.

01:44:28.820 --> 01:44:33.300
[Amit Varma]: And it'll take a lot of iteration for you to achieve excellence.

01:44:33.300 --> 01:44:37.140
[Amit Varma]: And the important thing is you can achieve excellence, you will achieve excellence if

01:44:37.140 --> 01:44:38.780
[Amit Varma]: you stick at it long enough.

01:44:38.780 --> 01:44:40.980
[Amit Varma]: So my advice would be go out and write.

01:44:40.980 --> 01:44:46.300
[Amit Varma]: And initially, aap newsletter is I would recommend it over a blog because people don't go to

01:44:46.300 --> 01:44:51.460
[Amit Varma]: destination websites anymore, clicking on you indiancut.com kaun karta hai, to have

01:44:51.460 --> 01:44:56.220
[Amit Varma]: a newsletter, so that every time you're hooking those people in your work goes to their mailbox,

01:44:56.220 --> 01:45:01.460
[Amit Varma]: you're forming a community of fans, and write as regularly as you can.

01:45:01.460 --> 01:45:08.100
[Amit Varma]: Don't overthink ki log kya sochenge, just keep writing and and experiment with form.

01:45:08.100 --> 01:45:13.260
[Amit Varma]: Don't put yourself in a box and say ki, you know, op-ed toh maine dekha hai, 800 word

01:45:13.260 --> 01:45:14.260
[Amit Varma]: hota hai.

01:45:14.260 --> 01:45:20.100
[Amit Varma]: Or I think creators think in terms of boxes of the past, that kitab hai toh 100,000 words,

01:45:20.100 --> 01:45:22.460
[Amit Varma]: article hai toh this much, and so on.

01:45:22.460 --> 01:45:25.660
[Amit Varma]: And I think one of the things about blogging that I loved and that freed me up is that

01:45:25.660 --> 01:45:27.380
[Amit Varma]: you can think beyond form.

01:45:27.380 --> 01:45:31.980
[Amit Varma]: Earlier conventions of forms were because of physical restrictions, right?

01:45:31.980 --> 01:45:37.500
[Amit Varma]: In music as well, in films, in everything, those restrictions don't exist anymore, right?

01:45:37.500 --> 01:45:41.300
[Amit Varma]: So just embrace a world where you have the freedom, you can do anything you want.

01:45:41.300 --> 01:45:45.500
[Amit Varma]: So in a nutshell, so in a nutshell, I would give them exactly the same advice you're giving,

01:45:45.500 --> 01:45:48.420
[Guest]: you're giving them, but these would be my whys.

01:45:48.420 --> 01:45:50.980
[Guest]: Yeah, that makes so much sense.

01:45:50.980 --> 01:45:52.780
[Guest]: And now, I mean, we have spoken for a while.

01:45:52.780 --> 01:45:58.460
[Guest]: So I'll just tell you one anxiety, like I had this dream, I'm recording in December

01:45:58.460 --> 01:45:59.460
[Guest]: 2020.

01:45:59.460 --> 01:46:02.660
[Guest]: I know these dates, because diary.

01:46:02.660 --> 01:46:06.900
[Guest]: So you know, Amit, there's some publication which was commissioning me a story.

01:46:06.900 --> 01:46:09.300
[Guest]: And I absolutely loved, you know, we discussed the idea.

01:46:09.300 --> 01:46:13.220
[Guest]: But then, one day I had this dream, it was a it's a long story that I had to write, you

01:46:13.220 --> 01:46:16.060
[Guest]: know, 4000-5000 word, some narrative piece.

01:46:16.060 --> 01:46:24.020
[Guest]: And I had this dream that the editors of this publication called me, and they say, you know,

01:46:24.020 --> 01:46:30.460
[Guest]: Samarth, we got a, we connected with the person who edited you at the Hindu Sunday magazine.

01:46:30.460 --> 01:46:35.700
[Guest]: My first job was at the Hindu and I wrote one, you know, magazine story.

01:46:35.700 --> 01:46:38.980
[Guest]: And that, Amit, that magazine story was almost entirely rewritten.

01:46:38.980 --> 01:46:43.380
[Guest]: Her sentence, I mean, for good, because my writing was shit.

01:46:43.380 --> 01:46:49.340
[Guest]: You know, I did this unfortunate thing of looking at my first drafts that I wrote seven

01:46:49.340 --> 01:46:50.340
[Guest]: years ago.

01:46:50.340 --> 01:46:51.660
[Guest]: And I was like, how did the Hindu hire me?

01:46:51.660 --> 01:46:55.660
[Guest]: I mean, why did they, like, how could they do it with this, right?

01:46:55.660 --> 01:46:56.700
[Guest]: That's the sense you get.

01:46:56.700 --> 01:46:59.180
[Guest]: And like, you feel a bit good that progress has been made.

01:46:59.180 --> 01:47:04.900
[Guest]: But I'm saying, that thing never went away in my head that I have a byline on it.

01:47:04.900 --> 01:47:13.060
[Guest]: But every sentence, you know, it just, you know what I mean, it just, it's painful, you

01:47:13.060 --> 01:47:16.620
[Guest]: know, I wrote it all, the name is mine, but the article is not mine.

01:47:16.620 --> 01:47:18.780
[Guest]: But people are saying that you wrote it, all of that.

01:47:18.780 --> 01:47:23.420
[Guest]: So the dream was that these editors, they got a call from, or somehow they connected

01:47:23.420 --> 01:47:28.300
[Guest]: and they said, Samarth, we heard that you can't write magazine pieces.

01:47:28.300 --> 01:47:30.900
[Guest]: You know, every line of yours has been edited.

01:47:30.900 --> 01:47:31.900
[Guest]: How do we know?

01:47:31.900 --> 01:47:32.900
[Guest]: We have seen your other work.

01:47:32.900 --> 01:47:35.100
[Guest]: How do we do have not spoken to other people?

01:47:35.100 --> 01:47:40.580
[Guest]: So we think you are not capable to write for us.

01:47:40.580 --> 01:47:41.580
[Guest]: Interesting dream.

01:47:41.580 --> 01:47:42.580
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:47:42.580 --> 01:47:44.860
[Guest]: And I don't know what happened after that.

01:47:44.860 --> 01:47:48.580
[Guest]: And no, no, I tell you, one thing happened, then I started giving them explanations that

01:47:48.580 --> 01:47:52.020
[Guest]: no, no, no, no, no, actually, you know, that was like 2016.

01:47:52.020 --> 01:47:53.020
[Guest]: I was new.

01:47:53.020 --> 01:47:56.700
[Guest]: But you know, I've worked so hard, I've done this, now you should read my other pieces.

01:47:56.700 --> 01:48:03.140
[Guest]: I went from there to now my pieces are published, you know, with 10% editing in the best of

01:48:03.140 --> 01:48:04.140
[Guest]: Indian newspapers.

01:48:04.140 --> 01:48:06.420
[Guest]: So you should say no, no, no, no, something was happening.

01:48:06.420 --> 01:48:09.860
[Guest]: So I don't know what happened after that, in that dream.

01:48:09.860 --> 01:48:15.340
[Guest]: But the reason I was telling this is that even when you know that things are on track,

01:48:15.340 --> 01:48:20.500
[Guest]: you know, with the whole framework I gave you, if that dream is coming, you know, there

01:48:20.500 --> 01:48:21.500
[Guest]: is something there, right?

01:48:21.500 --> 01:48:22.500
[Guest]: There is something.

01:48:22.500 --> 01:48:23.500
[Guest]: There is something.

01:48:23.500 --> 01:48:29.420
[Guest]: I mean, I can't describe it, but you know, like I'm the only reason I mentioned this

01:48:29.420 --> 01:48:38.220
[Guest]: is that now I feel relatively slightly bit more confident to put my work out in the public

01:48:38.220 --> 01:48:43.820
[Guest]: because you know, when you work on the technicalities of language, all of those things, right, it's

01:48:43.820 --> 01:48:50.380
[Guest]: not maybe the best piece of writing or whatever, you know, like a very smart, like if Amit Verma

01:48:50.380 --> 01:48:55.260
[Guest]: reads my piece, then he will see it, you know, like I wrote a piece, then, you know, there's

01:48:55.260 --> 01:48:59.220
[Guest]: someone who was really helping me with my editing and the piece was not edited.

01:48:59.220 --> 01:49:03.740
[Guest]: So the next day I asked him on the phone what I had done, he said, boss, you messed up at

01:49:03.740 --> 01:49:04.740
[Guest]: the end.

01:49:04.740 --> 01:49:10.620
[Guest]: I said, damn, she caught it because I knew I fucked up and she because she knew my writing,

01:49:10.620 --> 01:49:15.500
[Guest]: she could just point out that you played the game early here, I said, yes, I did, you know,

01:49:15.500 --> 01:49:19.740
[Guest]: and it just pained me, I said, if they see it, so others will also see it, right?

01:49:19.740 --> 01:49:25.380
[Guest]: So I'm saying that people who know, who think about the craft of writing, they can catch,

01:49:25.380 --> 01:49:30.820
[Guest]: but still it is beyond something that's, it's okay, I don't feel embarrassed to put things

01:49:30.820 --> 01:49:34.500
[Guest]: out in the world, you know, that's what I'm saying, you know, that's like, threshold wise,

01:49:34.500 --> 01:49:40.060
[Guest]: it just crossed that, uske baad bhi, agar yeh sapna aa raha hai, that means that there

01:49:40.060 --> 01:49:44.780
[Guest]: is some anxiety, kuch toh hai, so that's, I just, I'm just sharing that this was a dream

01:49:44.780 --> 01:49:49.820
[Guest]: I got, even though I feel a bit more comfortable in putting out my work.

01:49:49.820 --> 01:49:54.420
[Amit Varma]: Main jab college mein tha, I did my BA from Ferguson College, Pune, and my, the reason

01:49:54.420 --> 01:49:59.140
[Amit Varma]: I chose to do a BA in English Literature is ki class nahi jaana parega, toh teen saal

01:49:59.140 --> 01:50:03.060
[Amit Varma]: mein class hi nahi gaya, malabar ek do baar gaya honga just to check out ki kaun hai,

01:50:03.060 --> 01:50:07.420
[Amit Varma]: kya ho raha hai, but class hi nahi gaya and I would study on the day before the exam and

01:50:07.420 --> 01:50:11.580
[Amit Varma]: I kind of sailed through and that was my blas attitude, right?

01:50:11.580 --> 01:50:15.380
[Amit Varma]: But for 10 years after that, I would have this recurring nightmare that I have failed

01:50:15.380 --> 01:50:20.420
[Guest]: at final exam, and I have absolutely no idea why, because I didn't, I didn't, because

01:50:20.420 --> 01:50:25.460
[Amit Varma]: a conscious me didn't give a damn, couldn't care less, you know, took pride in being mediocre

01:50:25.460 --> 01:50:28.940
[Amit Varma]: as far as that anti metric of Marx was concerned, right?

01:50:28.940 --> 01:50:32.580
[Amit Varma]: The conscious me never gave a shit, lekin wo sapna aata tha, so I don't know whether

01:50:32.580 --> 01:50:37.900
[Amit Varma]: the sapna came because of something ingrained from parental expectation, or whatever, so

01:50:37.900 --> 01:50:42.220
[Amit Varma]: that that's, that's kind of sort of interesting there. So, so your dreams are fascinating,

01:50:42.220 --> 01:50:46.420
[Amit Varma]: you know, yeah, dreams are sort of dreams are so fascinating. And when what he was saying

01:50:46.420 --> 01:50:51.300
[Amit Varma]: about, you know, sending a piece to your friend and realizing and knowing you made a mistake

01:50:51.300 --> 01:50:55.940
[Amit Varma]: in the craft, and then she catches it and says, end mein kya kya hai. And sometimes

01:50:55.940 --> 01:51:01.220
[Amit Varma]: and what's happened with this podcast is ki yeh genre thora naya hai, chaar ghante ki

01:51:01.220 --> 01:51:05.540
[Amit Varma]: conversation, paanch ghante ki conversation kaun karta hai. Now, as you would expect,

01:51:05.540 --> 01:51:10.020
[Amit Varma]: there's a lot of intentionality behind what I do. And I have figured out guidelines of

01:51:10.020 --> 01:51:14.740
[Amit Varma]: craft for myself. And the whole thing is a moving thing, it keeps changing. And there's

01:51:14.740 --> 01:51:18.540
[Amit Varma]: nothing like it outside, because nobody does it. It's almost like a new form. How do you

01:51:18.540 --> 01:51:22.860
[Amit Varma]: do a five hour conversation. And I will often look back on older episodes I've done and

01:51:22.860 --> 01:51:28.460
[Amit Varma]: I'll think of mistakes I made in terms of craft, in terms of the directions I went down

01:51:28.460 --> 01:51:32.860
[Amit Varma]: or the way I structured it. And I know that literally nobody else will see those. I mean,

01:51:32.860 --> 01:51:36.620
[Amit Varma]: they might have an effect on the listener, but they won't see it as a mistake of craft

01:51:36.620 --> 01:51:43.260
[Amit Varma]: because matlab, it's, you know, there is no guideline that yeh craft hai, while writing

01:51:43.260 --> 01:51:49.960
[Amit Varma]: in journalism have textbooks on craft and all of that. But my principle is ki, you just

01:51:49.960 --> 01:51:55.940
[Amit Varma]: barrel on, you do episode after episode, just barrel on. So I never look back, you just

01:51:55.940 --> 01:52:00.220
[Amit Varma]: barrel on. And that's again, in a sense, as far as at least my podcasting is concerned,

01:52:00.220 --> 01:52:05.380
[Amit Varma]: I think I'm embodying the advice I give others that karte rao, just keep doing, you know,

01:52:05.380 --> 01:52:09.460
[Amit Varma]: unfortunately, I haven't been able to follow that advice enough in my own writing, because

01:52:09.460 --> 01:52:13.460
[Amit Varma]: I would like to write much more. And I've had issues with process and discipline and

01:52:13.460 --> 01:52:18.700
[Amit Varma]: all of that. But at least in this, it has worked for me, that you keep doing it, you

01:52:18.700 --> 01:52:23.020
[Amit Varma]: will get better over time, you will realize you've gotten better over time. In retrospect,

01:52:23.020 --> 01:52:28.140
[Amit Varma]: you will see that I went from A to B to C or whatever. But in the moment, sometimes

01:52:28.140 --> 01:52:32.780
[Amit Varma]: you can't and there's a danger in paralyzing yourself by being too self critical.

01:52:32.780 --> 01:52:38.060
[Guest]: Yeah, and I remember, you know, in my coaching in my 12th class, so in the coaching center,

01:52:38.060 --> 01:52:42.060
[Guest]: and again, I mean, you know, the when I read narratives in the press about coaching, it's

01:52:42.060 --> 01:52:46.020
[Guest]: just like I can't relate. It's like hai bechare bachche, bachpan chheen liya, you know, that's

01:52:46.020 --> 01:52:50.380
[Guest]: the narrative, you know, and I'm like, I don't know, I am not commenting on it as a reporter,

01:52:50.380 --> 01:52:54.260
[Guest]: but I'm like, this is not me yaar, mera toh, we had a blast at coaching, we had a great

01:52:54.260 --> 01:52:58.460
[Guest]: time. So anyway, that was so, our chemistry teacher, unhone ek cheez batai, I think, you

01:52:58.460 --> 01:53:03.780
[Guest]: know, he was just trying to motivate us. He says, you know, success is boring. Like, what

01:53:03.780 --> 01:53:08.220
[Guest]: does that mean? He says, think about Sachin Tendulkar. He said, what does this guy do?

01:53:08.220 --> 01:53:14.060
[Guest]: This guy, every day, goes to the field, you know, takes a bat and hits the ball. Right?

01:53:14.060 --> 01:53:19.420
[Guest]: That is all this guy does day in day out. And that's why he's Sachin. Toh hum like,

01:53:19.420 --> 01:53:24.940
[Guest]: baat toh sahi hai, kar kya raha hai? Ball hi toh hit kar raha hai. So, he was just trying

01:53:24.940 --> 01:53:28.180
[Guest]: to tell us that, like, you know, study, you know, focus on the process, don't think about,

01:53:28.180 --> 01:53:32.860
[Guest]: you know, have a goal, but like, solve your problems. And don't, like, you know, because

01:53:32.860 --> 01:53:38.420
[Guest]: everyone around us kind of telling nahi, these nerds, bachche, parte rehte hain, all of those

01:53:38.420 --> 01:53:44.540
[Guest]: things, right? So, like, ignore, ignore, you know, just, you have a goal, you want to,

01:53:44.540 --> 01:53:48.260
[Guest]: you know, want to get to that institute. So, just study. And like, if, if, if you think

01:53:48.260 --> 01:53:51.940
[Guest]: it's boring, it's because boring is the norm. I mean, that's how he was trying to tell us

01:53:51.940 --> 01:53:57.740
[Guest]: about exams. We didn't find our math, physics, chemistry problems boring. We loved it. That's

01:53:57.740 --> 01:54:00.940
[Guest]: why wo hum kar rehte hain. So, same thing abhi bhi hota hai that, you know, aise kuch

01:54:00.940 --> 01:54:04.700
[Guest]: pada nahi chal raha hai that, you know, what's happening idhar udhar. But it's just that,

01:54:04.700 --> 01:54:07.780
[Guest]: if someone thinks ki outcome ikdum se nahi mil raha hai. So, I just remember that story

01:54:07.780 --> 01:54:11.980
[Guest]: ki, you know, Sachin bhi, you know, ground pe jaake, bas, he's just hitting the ball.

01:54:11.980 --> 01:54:16.740
[Guest]: Toh aap bhi, you know, computer pe baith ke likte rao. Whatever happens is.

01:54:16.740 --> 01:54:21.660
[Amit Varma]: That's a lovely way to put it that Sachin is boring. And the other point I'll sometimes

01:54:21.660 --> 01:54:25.420
[Amit Varma]: make is, I mean, that's the importance of hard work and also the importance of humility.

01:54:25.420 --> 01:54:30.420
[Amit Varma]: Like I'll tell people that, you know, you think that Virat Kohli is an arrogant brat

01:54:30.420 --> 01:54:35.340
[Amit Varma]: and all that jaisa uska image hai. But when it comes to his craft, I guarantee you that

01:54:35.340 --> 01:54:40.180
[Amit Varma]: he is a humblest person around because the only way you get that good is by playing thousands

01:54:40.180 --> 01:54:45.220
[Amit Varma]: of balls in the nets, focusing only on what you're doing wrong. Right. Focusing only like,

01:54:45.220 --> 01:54:49.140
[Amit Varma]: why am I missing that swinging ball outside the off stump? You examine, your coaches will

01:54:49.140 --> 01:54:53.740
[Amit Varma]: tell you, your fellow batsmen will tell you, you focus on your mistakes. So people might

01:54:53.740 --> 01:54:58.140
[Amit Varma]: be arrogant outside of their domain where they've achieved excellence. But my belief

01:54:58.140 --> 01:55:02.340
[Amit Varma]: is that to achieve excellence, you have to be incredibly humble in that domain, because

01:55:02.340 --> 01:55:06.380
[Amit Varma]: nahi toh nahi hone wala hai. You know, you have to. And at the same level of the same

01:55:06.380 --> 01:55:10.340
[Amit Varma]: time, you perhaps also need a level of, you know, self delusion helps. Like when I think

01:55:10.340 --> 01:55:15.740
[Amit Varma]: of myself as a young person, my ability and my judgment were both bad. So I would write

01:55:15.740 --> 01:55:21.380
[Amit Varma]: shit and I would think it's great. This is like when? India ka time? No, no, 20s, I guess.

01:55:21.380 --> 01:55:25.700
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. So I would write shit and I would think it's great. But self delusion helps, you know,

01:55:25.700 --> 01:55:30.460
[Guest]: you fake it till you make it. I've been there. Absolutely. You know, when I was a blogger

01:55:30.460 --> 01:55:34.620
[Guest]: in college, toh uss waqt mujhe kuchh pata nahi tha. It's just that I wanted to express.

01:55:34.620 --> 01:55:40.660
[Guest]: Aur mera, you know, archives mere paas hain. And like, like, forget quality of ideas. Ideas

01:55:40.660 --> 01:55:44.980
[Guest]: toh the hi nahi. They were grammatical mistakes. So once, you know, we had a college fest aur

01:55:44.980 --> 01:55:49.260
[Guest]: hum railway station gaye we the. And this friend of mine, in I think the third semester

01:55:49.260 --> 01:55:54.540
[Guest]: or something, he comes and tells me that, do you know what people in the English Literary

01:55:54.540 --> 01:56:00.140
[Guest]: Society say about your blog? I was like, what do they say? He says like, that, you know,

01:56:00.140 --> 01:56:04.180
[Guest]: it's like written like this, it's written like that. You know, that one person was telling

01:56:04.180 --> 01:56:10.740
[Guest]: me, you know, samarth ka blog toh matlab, what is it? Toh uss waqt mujhe, I was like,

01:56:10.740 --> 01:56:15.220
[Guest]: those arrogant people, unko kya bata, main toh likhunga, right? I didn't realize it until

01:56:15.220 --> 01:56:21.820
[Guest]: very late that technically they were right. Matlab, it was objectively bad piece of writing

01:56:21.820 --> 01:56:26.660
[Guest]: in sense of grammar. Everything was broken. But uss waqt main kare ja raha tha because,

01:56:26.660 --> 01:56:32.340
[Guest]: you know, for me, the blog was just a, you know, what the name of my blog was. And you

01:56:32.340 --> 01:56:36.620
[Guest]: will know when I say it's self-expression. Don't tell me it's random musings or something

01:56:36.620 --> 01:56:43.700
[Guest]: that was a cliche of those days. It's, it's embarrassing. But my name of the, my blog's

01:56:43.700 --> 01:56:49.060
[Guest]: name was Crazy Sam. Okay, with the crazy ka spelling tha, K-R-A-Z-Z-Y, because I just

01:56:49.060 --> 01:56:53.900
[Guest]: loved Hrithik Roshan's dance in this movie game, Crazy 4. Toh you know, when I started

01:56:53.900 --> 01:57:01.220
[Guest]: my blog after my coaching, I was like Crazy Sam. Toh at 17, you know, matlab ab 13 saal

01:57:01.220 --> 01:57:04.620
[Guest]: ki umar mein aapko samajh aata hai, you know, email addresses, all of us have those. Toh

01:57:04.620 --> 01:57:09.580
[Guest]: mujhe kabhi samajhi nahi aaya. And even when it hit me, till I became a journalist, I didn't

01:57:09.580 --> 01:57:13.980
[Guest]: change the name of the blog because mujhe laga haan woh, it was some madness, jisme

01:57:13.980 --> 01:57:17.060
[Guest]: woh blog aaya tha. And the blog will reflect that madness. So, I am not going to change

01:57:17.060 --> 01:57:24.620
[Guest]: the name. Right? So, but over time, I saw that at least I was true to self-expression.

01:57:24.620 --> 01:57:29.460
[Guest]: Agar maine blog ka naam bhi nahi change kara, right? I knew like what, like I knew it was

01:57:29.460 --> 01:57:35.420
[Guest]: funny, you know. But tha ki, you know, this is for self-expression. Language can go to

01:57:35.420 --> 01:57:40.260
[Guest]: hell. Malabh woh, pata bhi nahi tha ki language kharab ho rahi hai, right? And one day, like

01:57:40.260 --> 01:57:44.260
[Guest]: I recently, you know, you will say, you know, kitna narcissistic banda hai. But I don't

01:57:44.260 --> 01:57:49.580
[Guest]: have my journal from college. So, you know, what's the best archive? Facebook messages.

01:57:49.580 --> 01:57:54.100
[Guest]: Because us waqt, I used to have these long, ab kaun hi Facebook use karta hai? And even

01:57:54.100 --> 01:57:57.940
[Guest]: on Instagram, I don't text. Us waqt toh, you know, we're in college, aap heart to heart

01:57:57.940 --> 01:58:01.780
[Guest]: kare ja rahe ho apne doston ke saath, right? So, I have snapshots of what I was writing

01:58:01.780 --> 01:58:06.580
[Guest]: to my friends. Like, so it's just brilliant, like for me to time travel. So, yeah, that's

01:58:06.580 --> 01:58:10.580
[Guest]: why I'm saying you could feel that bahut narcissistic, you know, apne waare mein sochta raha tha.

01:58:10.580 --> 01:58:14.900
[Guest]: But whatever is the case, I enjoy doing that. I, you know, want to travel in time.

01:58:14.900 --> 01:58:18.260
[Amit Varma]: Probably the opposite of narcissistic, because when you look at all the, like when I look

01:58:18.260 --> 01:58:22.660
[Amit Varma]: at all the shit I wrote once upon a time, it lends itself to humility, no? Because then

01:58:22.660 --> 01:58:28.020
[Amit Varma]: you realize ki yaar main toh samjhta tha main itna top hoon and then you look at your, that

01:58:28.020 --> 01:58:32.100
[Unknown]: embarrassing rubbish and you're like ki theek hai yaar, abhi just chill, don't take it too

01:58:32.100 --> 01:58:36.340
[Guest]: far. Yeah, usmein I saw that how people are very generous, because there's this post I

01:58:36.340 --> 01:58:40.980
[Guest]: put up, which had some reference to my friend. And this friend's girlfriend, who was not

01:58:40.980 --> 01:58:47.300
[Guest]: from our college, I swear, and we were not even Facebook friends, okay? She read my blog

01:58:47.300 --> 01:58:53.380
[Guest]: and she sent me this long message saying that, you know, Samar, you wrote this. I, you know,

01:58:53.380 --> 01:58:56.900
[Guest]: as a, it was something about festival that I wrote something, something. She said, you

01:58:56.900 --> 01:59:01.700
[Guest]: know, as a girl, I relate with what you wrote, tak tak tak. But I think that, you know, you

01:59:01.700 --> 01:59:07.940
[Guest]: could work on your language. It feels like you are translating your thought in Hindi

01:59:07.940 --> 01:59:12.820
[Guest]: to just English. And main abhi padha hai do hafta pehle. And I was like, she was damn

01:59:12.820 --> 01:59:20.020
[Guest]: right. She was damn right. Because I was just thinking. And in IIT, at least Kanpur, the

01:59:20.020 --> 01:59:25.220
[Guest]: culture is not to speak in English. You know, it's very Hindi focused, like in our hostels,

01:59:25.220 --> 01:59:29.140
[Guest]: etc. Hindi mein baat karte hain. Toh poora tha. Now, I don't know how that happened,

01:59:29.140 --> 01:59:32.820
[Guest]: but now I think in English. Uswaq main Hindi mein sochta tha. Toh whatever used to come

01:59:32.820 --> 01:59:37.540
[Guest]: in my head, I used to just, she, I don't know how, but she picked it. She said, it looks

01:59:37.540 --> 01:59:42.900
[Guest]: like you are just translating your raw thought in Hindi on your blog, which is admirable

01:59:42.900 --> 01:59:48.180
[Guest]: because I get your sentiment. But on that process, you know, you can work on your language,

01:59:48.180 --> 01:59:55.220
[Guest]: you know, your grammar is going off, you know. And I read it and I was so thankful to her

01:59:55.220 --> 02:00:00.660
[Guest]: that, you know, she took the time to read and give, like kaun itna acha feedback deta

02:00:00.660 --> 02:00:04.420
[Guest]: hai aaj ke time pe. It's beautiful, but how did you react at the time? Haan, so I was

02:00:04.420 --> 02:00:09.780
[Guest]: listening. So I, so I honestly don't remember the specifics of what I felt, but I just thanked

02:00:09.780 --> 02:00:14.820
[Guest]: her uswaqt that, you know, thank you so much for reading. I will think about it. You're right.

02:00:14.820 --> 02:00:21.540
[Guest]: But I don't think that I had that appreciation of what that message meant until now, because

02:00:21.540 --> 02:00:28.340
[Guest]: in retrospection, now that I can see that, that she caught it, that, you know, and why I,

02:00:28.340 --> 02:00:32.820
[Guest]: unfortunately, I didn't know it. Like I was in Bombay in May and, you know, this couple lives

02:00:32.820 --> 02:00:37.620
[Guest]: in Bombay and I was there and I met her after eight years. I first met, you know, when they

02:00:37.620 --> 02:00:42.420
[Guest]: just started dating and I was in Bombay for my work, for my internship. So we were meeting after

02:00:42.420 --> 02:00:47.140
[Guest]: eight years and we just had this chat. Uske baad jaake mene, and you know, I remember in that,

02:00:47.140 --> 02:00:51.220
[Guest]: you know, we were in that restaurant and talking and she just said, I'm hearing that, you know,

02:00:51.220 --> 02:00:55.140
[Guest]: now you're getting published in places, very glad to know. So when I saw that message,

02:00:56.500 --> 02:01:00.340
[Guest]: I just felt that, you know, if I knew it that time, you know, I would have thanked her that,

02:01:00.340 --> 02:01:07.140
[Guest]: you know, like people like, and like, we don't, we haven't spoken at all, but you know what I'm

02:01:07.140 --> 02:01:12.020
[Guest]: trying to say. It's just beautiful that, that's what I'm saying, generosity, that, you know,

02:01:12.980 --> 02:01:18.180
[Guest]: people, and that's, you know, some of, one of my faiths that even that, you know, if I fuck up,

02:01:18.180 --> 02:01:25.700
[Guest]: if I put out a bad piece of writing, but the intent is visible to people, you know,

02:01:25.700 --> 02:01:31.700
[Amit Varma]: they will, they will support you. And I'm just thinking aloud, that such generosity

02:01:31.700 --> 02:01:37.060
[Amit Varma]: from someone at that age is likely to come more from women, because men get so competitive.

02:01:37.780 --> 02:01:41.220
[Amit Varma]: Do you feel that that's something that you've sort of noticed?

02:01:41.780 --> 02:01:44.420
[Guest]: I know that now that you mentioned it, I'm just trying to think about

02:01:45.380 --> 02:01:50.740
[Guest]: the feedback that I've received from women, right? And it's true. Like, actually, I can give you one

02:01:50.740 --> 02:01:54.980
[Guest]: more story on this when, so I've been in this newslettering, I've been fascinated by this

02:01:54.980 --> 02:02:01.700
[Guest]: and fascinated by newsletters since early 2018. Okay, 2018, like, when no one knew Substack,

02:02:01.700 --> 02:02:06.740
[Guest]: I was on Substack, I was trying to do something. While having a job at HT, I started something.

02:02:06.740 --> 02:02:11.940
[Guest]: Again, let's not get into it, I'll always say it's bad, but whatever. So one day, what I did,

02:02:11.940 --> 02:02:17.540
[Guest]: I wrote a newsletter and I tried to be funny. And I'm not funny, as a person. I'm not, you know,

02:02:18.100 --> 02:02:22.500
[Guest]: wit and, you know, funny. I mean, that's not me. I was never that person, you know,

02:02:22.500 --> 02:02:28.100
[Guest]: but I tried to be smart. You know, then I was recommending, actually, I was,

02:02:28.100 --> 02:02:32.740
[Guest]: that was post where I was recommending a list of podcasts. Okay, ki aaj mein par kuch nahi hai,

02:02:32.740 --> 02:02:37.300
[Guest]: Diwali ki chhutti hai, something like that. Aur uska intro tha na, I was pretending to be smart,

02:02:37.300 --> 02:02:42.820
[Guest]: that you know, witty. And then this someone I knew from college, she was a postgraduate student.

02:02:43.780 --> 02:02:48.180
[Guest]: She wrote me a long email. Okay, she said, look Samarth, I'll be honest with you.

02:02:48.180 --> 02:02:54.900
[Guest]: What have you written? This is not you. Okay, I have seen what you, so I was the editor of the,

02:02:54.900 --> 02:02:59.780
[Guest]: like, my favorite memory from college is that I revamped my campus newspaper and I wrote,

02:02:59.780 --> 02:03:04.580
[Guest]: she said, I know what you did there. What, something, something that, I'm not, I'm forgetting

02:03:04.580 --> 02:03:09.060
[Guest]: the specifics, but her, and see, I've seen what you're doing in other newsletters. And usse pehle

02:03:09.060 --> 02:03:14.980
[Guest]: she has responded saying that, great piece, why don't you do this? Yeh kya likha hai tumne? This

02:03:14.980 --> 02:03:22.900
[Guest]: is not you. You're trying to be someone who you're not, and it's visible. And it was,

02:03:24.420 --> 02:03:28.900
[Guest]: and I was like, I could not say anything because she was right. But I would not have realized this

02:03:28.900 --> 02:03:34.900
[Guest]: because in my head, I was trying to be, you know, this smart guy, witty person. But jab usme hai

02:03:34.900 --> 02:03:39.780
[Guest]: nahi, so I'm saying that someone would be like, someone can say na, haan chalo, bad piece chalo,

02:03:39.780 --> 02:03:45.780
[Guest]: aagey bado. The fact that someone takes the effort, and in today's age, you can always be

02:03:45.780 --> 02:03:52.660
[Guest]: doubtful na ki, mai criticize karunga, to how will the other person take it? Like you've, she,

02:03:52.660 --> 02:03:59.940
[Guest]: I don't know, but I just loved it that people do this. And you're an outlier boss, because I have

02:03:59.940 --> 02:04:05.380
[Amit Varma]: gotten burnt more than once giving honest feedback to people I thought were friends and who would be

02:04:05.380 --> 02:04:11.140
[Amit Varma]: receptive towards it. Because, and this is something I, I'm at pains to tell anyone who

02:04:11.140 --> 02:04:15.540
[Amit Varma]: participates in my writing course about that if there is one thing that you should not do,

02:04:15.540 --> 02:04:20.340
[Amit Varma]: you should not react with anger to criticism. Yeah, you know, even if you feel criticism is

02:04:20.340 --> 02:04:25.460
[Amit Varma]: coming from a bad place, never ever react. And reacting with anger is actually reflexive and

02:04:25.460 --> 02:04:31.060
[Amit Varma]: understandable. Because often we put so much emotional energy into what we write, that it

02:04:31.060 --> 02:04:36.180
[Amit Varma]: becomes tied up with our sense of self. Toh kisi ne mere piece ko criticize kiya, toh personal

02:04:36.180 --> 02:04:39.540
[Amit Varma]: attack lagta hai. So that's a natural instinct. Yeah, that's a natural instinct. But you got to

02:04:39.540 --> 02:04:45.860
[Amit Varma]: fight the natural instinct, and take a step back and not react with anger and then think about it.

02:04:45.860 --> 02:04:50.580
[Amit Varma]: And very few people do that. So you know, and perhaps she knew you were that kind of person.

02:04:50.580 --> 02:04:55.940
[Amit Varma]: So she felt emboldened to sort of send you that like, you know, before this episode started,

02:04:55.940 --> 02:05:00.260
[Amit Varma]: you gifted me this book by Robert Sapolsky, Behave. And I think one of the point which I'm

02:05:00.260 --> 02:05:04.180
[Amit Varma]: really looking forward to digging into and one of the points Sapolsky has made in this,

02:05:04.180 --> 02:05:09.700
[Amit Varma]: if I remember correctly, in his episode with Sam Harris is about, you know, how the reason there

02:05:09.700 --> 02:05:17.220
[Amit Varma]: is so much violence among young males is that the male brain really develops fully only by the age

02:05:17.220 --> 02:05:23.060
[Amit Varma]: of 25. I think it's a frontal cortex, which is responsible for that socializing part of behavior

02:05:23.060 --> 02:05:28.980
[Amit Varma]: and all of that. And that really develops only by, you know, 25, which is why you have so much

02:05:28.980 --> 02:05:35.060
[Amit Varma]: violence among, you know, teenage males, and the bulk of violence in society really comes from young

02:05:35.060 --> 02:05:40.420
[Amit Varma]: males. And that's interesting. And that may also speak to, you know, the observation,

02:05:40.420 --> 02:05:45.460
[Amit Varma]: which otherwise seems to be a stereotype, and I avoid them. But the fact is that young women are

02:05:45.460 --> 02:05:48.660
[Guest]: just more mature than young men. Do you think it's also goes otherwise,

02:05:48.660 --> 02:05:54.020
[Amit Varma]: in terms of receiving feedback? Yeah, I think men would be worse at receiving feedback.

02:05:54.020 --> 02:06:00.500
[Amit Varma]: But having said that, women already have, you know, what is known as a confidence gap. Yeah,

02:06:00.500 --> 02:06:06.100
[Amit Varma]: the imposter syndrome is so much more likely in women. So they could actually react the other

02:06:06.100 --> 02:06:10.980
[Amit Varma]: way and not think independently about feedback and let it get them down. You know, even if the

02:06:10.980 --> 02:06:16.340
[Amit Varma]: feedback is unwarranted. So I think that is a danger the other way. Yeah, I was recently listening

02:06:16.340 --> 02:06:19.860
[Guest]: to this podcast by Michael Lewis is one of my favorite writers, my writing inspiration,

02:06:19.860 --> 02:06:25.140
[Guest]: actually. So his season three of his podcast, Against the Rules is on experts. So he had one

02:06:25.140 --> 02:06:31.700
[Guest]: episode on mansplaining, you know, that he was on history. So I you know, that what I think was

02:06:31.700 --> 02:06:34.900
[Amit Varma]: the writer Rebecca Solnit, I'm forgetting. Rebecca Solnit wrote this book.

02:06:34.900 --> 02:06:36.660
[Amit Varma]: Men Explain Things to Me, right? Yeah.

02:06:36.660 --> 02:06:42.020
[Guest]: So she was the intro, like, she was explaining what happened, the origins that she was in this

02:06:42.020 --> 02:06:48.660
[Guest]: party. And this guy, you know, this dude is telling her about the book about, you know,

02:06:48.660 --> 02:06:52.820
[Guest]: like she said, you know, my writer and makes nasty comments and ends up talking about a book that she

02:06:52.820 --> 02:06:57.620
[Guest]: wrote. Yeah, right. And it was she and he clearly hadn't read the book. So they were describing

02:06:57.620 --> 02:07:01.780
[Guest]: that. And then Lewis goes into he starts a story that this was the origin of mansplaining,

02:07:01.780 --> 02:07:08.260
[Guest]: and ends with some research on exactly this point that this whole business of mansplaining

02:07:08.260 --> 02:07:16.740
[Guest]: comes from, you know, the sense of men feeling superior in a group about bullshitting that they

02:07:16.740 --> 02:07:22.420
[Guest]: know, and women not adequately responding to it. And the the point he was trying to make,

02:07:22.420 --> 02:07:27.780
[Guest]: actually, his core point was that after you have done this, you don't realize what you have done.

02:07:28.500 --> 02:07:36.500
[Guest]: So you become, the gap increases. It's not that you feel embarrassed that oh, you know,

02:07:39.940 --> 02:07:44.420
[Guest]: no, you don't feel embarrassed about it. You double down on it. And when you double down on it,

02:07:44.420 --> 02:07:48.260
[Guest]: your habit keeps on perpetuating, it doesn't go down. So there was some research that he

02:07:48.260 --> 02:07:52.980
[Guest]: was quoting, which I found pretty interesting, because he said that doesn't go back the other

02:07:52.980 --> 02:07:59.300
[Guest]: way. That once in that research, I think I'm, maybe you can link it in the show notes. But

02:07:59.300 --> 02:08:03.620
[Guest]: that's what he was saying that it doesn't happen the other way that when that woman realizes that

02:08:03.620 --> 02:08:10.180
[Guest]: what this guy is doing, that it's not that the guy is doubling down on his overconfidence,

02:08:10.180 --> 02:08:15.940
[Guest]: right? But that's the same thing is not happening on the side of women. So the gap kind of increases

02:08:15.940 --> 02:08:19.780
[Guest]: and mansplaining keeps becoming a thing. Yeah, there's this lovely cartoon I like where this

02:08:19.780 --> 02:08:24.020
[Amit Varma]: man is at dinner with a woman and he's telling her across the table, let me interrupt your

02:08:24.020 --> 02:08:30.180
[Unknown]: expertise with my confidence. And that kind of says everything that women don't have enough faith

02:08:30.180 --> 02:08:35.700
[Amit Varma]: in their expertise. And men have too much unwarranted self confidence. But Amit, can I

02:08:35.700 --> 02:08:42.420
[Guest]: ask a tough question here? And maybe politically incorrect, but why don't we bring it up?

02:08:42.420 --> 02:08:46.820
[Guest]: So there's another effect that happens with me. And I want to know what, so I'll again give you

02:08:46.820 --> 02:08:52.020
[Guest]: an incident. Oh my God, I you know, I hope this person is not listening to it. Because I'm

02:08:52.020 --> 02:08:56.340
[Amit Varma]: describing a scenario. I think by so many times you've said I hope so and so is not listening

02:08:56.340 --> 02:08:59.700
[Amit Varma]: to it that I think you have the impression no one listens to the podcast mechanical.

02:08:59.700 --> 02:09:05.780
[Unknown]: Oh my God, I didn't mean that. Anyway. So anyway, so there was this time in the newsroom,

02:09:05.780 --> 02:09:09.300
[Guest]: when there was this, I think it was seven o'clock in the evening. And there was a story.

02:09:09.300 --> 02:09:15.540
[Guest]: I don't go into details, because details don't matter. And there was this my colleague at HT,

02:09:16.660 --> 02:09:21.300
[Guest]: she was supposed to report the story, some development had happened. And I also used to

02:09:21.300 --> 02:09:25.860
[Guest]: cover similar things. And so you know, the 7pm news had broken something, something, something,

02:09:25.860 --> 02:09:32.420
[Guest]: we had to write a story. And there was a confusion, what is happening? So then she said that,

02:09:32.420 --> 02:09:38.900
[Guest]: you know, this is the story. And because it was something related to tech, which is something I've

02:09:38.900 --> 02:09:44.580
[Guest]: deeply thought about and worked on. So I was like, this is wrong. It's not like that, right? And she

02:09:44.580 --> 02:09:49.700
[Guest]: was like, no, this is it. So there was almost this debate. And I regret that I think I don't remember,

02:09:49.700 --> 02:09:58.660
[Guest]: but I think I, my voice, you know, I think it was not like I shouted is not my, I raised my voice a

02:09:58.660 --> 02:10:05.700
[Guest]: bit. You know, I was just frustrated, that why don't you understand that? Like, you're wrong.

02:10:06.340 --> 02:10:10.500
[Guest]: That you know, that's not the story. This is the story and I'm telling you. It was a confusion.

02:10:10.500 --> 02:10:17.140
[Guest]: Then for some reason, you know, I think my thing prevailed. Fortunately, next day,

02:10:17.140 --> 02:10:21.060
[Guest]: I was right that, you know, I was, I was hitting the right story. But that incident

02:10:23.060 --> 02:10:30.260
[Guest]: stuck with me because I always felt that, you know, I was right, but I somehow like,

02:10:30.260 --> 02:10:35.700
[Guest]: I don't know this tension between how do I isolate that whether I'm just being,

02:10:35.700 --> 02:10:43.140
[Guest]: you know, this overconfident man in a setting, or, you know,

02:10:43.140 --> 02:10:47.460
[Guest]: it's just like, you know, right, like, this is the story. This is not the story. Like,

02:10:47.460 --> 02:10:52.820
[Guest]: I, you know, something like, I actually know more than you on this, you know. And this is the so,

02:10:52.820 --> 02:10:57.780
[Guest]: I don't know where the tension goes. But sometimes you just feel and that, which is why I'm saying

02:10:57.780 --> 02:11:04.100
[Guest]: it's politically incorrect. Because I know when you are in in a structure of privilege in a larger

02:11:04.100 --> 02:11:09.220
[Guest]: scheme of things, right? How do you isolate whether you're acting as the quote unquote oppressor,

02:11:09.220 --> 02:11:15.460
[Guest]: or, you know, the powerful in the dynamics, or you are outside that structure on the fundamentals,

02:11:15.460 --> 02:11:19.700
[Guest]: I think you, you know, you can take it about religion, like, I'll give you another example.

02:11:19.700 --> 02:11:25.540
[Guest]: There's someone wrote a column saying that you can't upper caste Hindu man can't criticize a

02:11:25.540 --> 02:11:30.100
[Guest]: Muslim woman journalist. Okay, I read that. And I read the book of I don't want to take names here.

02:11:30.900 --> 02:11:37.220
[Guest]: And I in my notes, I have criticism of this specific person. And I don't want to take names

02:11:37.220 --> 02:11:43.940
[Guest]: of this specific person. And I went into this deep thought here. I am in my head not thinking

02:11:43.940 --> 02:11:49.700
[Guest]: in terms of identity. I am again, I as I said, I try to think that I'm a first principles thinker.

02:11:50.980 --> 02:11:56.340
[Guest]: This is journalism 101. It's not mapping up. So what I want to ask you is that have you ever

02:11:56.340 --> 02:12:07.300
[Guest]: this tension between identity? And like, that I'm not behaving, my identity is not overpowering me

02:12:07.300 --> 02:12:11.860
[Guest]: in this situation. It's independent of that. So I don't know, I've not figured out a way.

02:12:12.500 --> 02:12:16.260
[Guest]: Because, you know, I just feel that, you know, I'm on the other side. So like, I just know,

02:12:16.260 --> 02:12:20.180
[Amit Varma]: want to know what you think of it. So yeah, but what thinking about there are three

02:12:20.180 --> 02:12:25.700
[Amit Varma]: sort of thoughts which come to mind. And one thought is that in the instance of the discussion

02:12:25.700 --> 02:12:30.660
[Amit Varma]: you had with your colleague about the tech thing, you actually knew more than her, or, you know,

02:12:30.660 --> 02:12:35.380
[Amit Varma]: at least, it wasn't as if it was her expertise, and you were mansplaining to her. Mansplaining

02:12:35.380 --> 02:12:39.700
[Amit Varma]: typically is when the man knows nothing, and the woman is the expert, and he's telling her something

02:12:39.700 --> 02:12:45.700
[Amit Varma]: that she knows more about. So, you know, those are the bare facts. I think every time you explain

02:12:45.700 --> 02:12:51.700
[Amit Varma]: something to somebody, it's not an act of splaining, necessarily. So just to apply that

02:12:51.700 --> 02:12:57.940
[Amit Varma]: hammer to every nail may not always be fair, but we need to watch out for ourselves doing that,

02:12:57.940 --> 02:13:04.580
[Amit Varma]: and make sure that we don't kind of do that. The other thing is that there is this, like at,

02:13:06.100 --> 02:13:10.980
[Amit Varma]: like I tell everyone who interacts with me that take me at face value, that mere kuch, you know,

02:13:10.980 --> 02:13:16.500
[Amit Varma]: beyond what I say, there is no, you know, don't read subtext into it, don't think that I intend

02:13:16.500 --> 02:13:21.540
[Amit Varma]: something I didn't say, take me at face value, don't add a layer to it. I didn't get it.

02:13:21.540 --> 02:13:25.940
[Amit Varma]: Don't, we should not take you at face value. No, take me at face value. Yeah, take me at

02:13:25.940 --> 02:13:30.740
[Amit Varma]: face value. And always assume goodwill. Assume that what I am saying is what I mean.

02:13:35.940 --> 02:13:41.620
[Amit Varma]: So I like to have a conversation without layers. Like now when we are speaking to each other,

02:13:41.620 --> 02:13:44.100
[Amit Varma]: I don't think we are thinking things like,

02:13:44.100 --> 02:13:51.060
[Amit Varma]: Amit, why did you ask this? You know, what does this mean? And so there is, it's just face value.

02:13:51.060 --> 02:13:56.180
[Amit Varma]: And that's the kind of conversation I like to have. However, the thing is that sometimes there

02:13:56.180 --> 02:14:02.260
[Amit Varma]: are other layers, even if you don't want there to be. So for example, if you are, you know,

02:14:02.260 --> 02:14:07.060
[Amit Varma]: like I remember once I was driving with a couple of friends to a mall in Bombay,

02:14:07.700 --> 02:14:12.580
[Amit Varma]: and I was weaving my way through traffic. I'm a typical Bombay driver. In fact, I think I'm the

02:14:12.580 --> 02:14:16.580
[Amit Varma]: best driver in the world in Bombay. So I'm a typical Bombay driver, lane change.

02:14:18.740 --> 02:14:23.620
[Amit Varma]: And we reached a mall. And as we got into the mall, these two women got into the lift with us,

02:14:23.620 --> 02:14:27.540
[Amit Varma]: and one of them started shouting at me that you only overtook me because I'm a woman.

02:14:30.500 --> 02:14:33.860
[Amit Varma]: Because I didn't look inside the other cars, I was just doing my thing.

02:14:34.580 --> 02:14:37.220
[Amit Varma]: And so I was just about to respond that no, ma'am,

02:14:37.220 --> 02:14:40.900
[Amit Varma]: aisi koi baat nahi hai, aisa nahi tha. When the friend who was with me,

02:14:40.900 --> 02:14:44.180
[Amit Varma]: he kind of just tapped me on the shoulder and said, you know, don't argue back.

02:14:44.740 --> 02:14:48.820
[Amit Varma]: And then later, he told me that you have to understand where she's coming from.

02:14:48.820 --> 02:14:54.260
[Amit Varma]: She's coming from a place where she's at the receiving end of a lot of shit from men,

02:14:54.260 --> 02:15:00.660
[Amit Varma]: literally all women are, right. So it is natural for her on a bad traffic day to feel ki oh shit,

02:15:00.660 --> 02:15:06.820
[Amit Varma]: there's another man just going past me. Right? So don't argue back. Just take it. There's no point

02:15:06.820 --> 02:15:11.940
[Amit Varma]: in, you know, have some sympathy and some empathy for where she is from. And I thought that was an

02:15:11.940 --> 02:15:18.660
[Amit Varma]: important lesson for me. Ki waha pe face value doesn't work. Waha pe you have to realize that

02:15:18.660 --> 02:15:24.420
[Amit Varma]: there is a layer. And maybe you have to step back and realize that there is a layer. However,

02:15:24.420 --> 02:15:29.540
[Amit Varma]: obviously, in a case of an argument in a newsroom, you can't step back from the truth. You know,

02:15:29.540 --> 02:15:33.540
[Amit Varma]: when you when you're arguing something like what you're arguing, I would say you have to argue that

02:15:33.540 --> 02:15:36.820
[Guest]: but perhaps you have to watch out for your tone. Yeah, tone. That's what I'm saying.

02:15:39.380 --> 02:15:45.140
[Amit Varma]: So to another guy, it's okay, it's a conversation to a girl, you know, she would just shrink back.

02:15:45.780 --> 02:15:51.780
[Amit Varma]: It's so I think recognizing those layers are important. And as far and my third thought on

02:15:51.780 --> 02:15:57.060
[Amit Varma]: this is that when you talk about, you know, somebody saying that you don't have a right

02:15:57.060 --> 02:16:03.460
[Amit Varma]: to criticize somebody because of your identity of birth. Yeah, I feel that if it's a particular

02:16:03.460 --> 02:16:10.500
[Amit Varma]: person, you know, it's okay to be aware of that context and tailor your tone and conversation

02:16:10.500 --> 02:16:15.380
[Amit Varma]: accordingly. But if a third person is giving that criticism, I feel it's bullshit. And it's

02:16:15.380 --> 02:16:21.380
[Amit Varma]: bullshit. Because I feel the problem with a lot of modern identity politics is people get reduced

02:16:21.380 --> 02:16:26.660
[Amit Varma]: to identities of birth. Whereas we contain multitudes, we are deeply complex, I find it

02:16:26.660 --> 02:16:32.900
[Amit Varma]: offensive if someone reduces me to an identity over which I had no control. Right. And I also

02:16:32.900 --> 02:16:39.060
[Amit Varma]: find it not helpful when someone less privileged than me is also pigeonholed and imprisoned in an

02:16:39.060 --> 02:16:44.740
[Amit Varma]: identity trap and given a narrative of victimhood when they are also a lot more than that. Absolutely.

02:16:44.740 --> 02:16:50.580
[Amit Varma]: So I just feel that this kind of politics is toxic to the discourse that we have to be aware

02:16:50.580 --> 02:16:56.100
[Amit Varma]: of privileges. Obviously, we have to be aware of all of that and mindful of that. But to reduce

02:16:56.100 --> 02:17:01.060
[Amit Varma]: all interactions to just being an interaction between identities of birth, I think can be

02:17:01.060 --> 02:17:06.980
[Amit Varma]: really toxic. And it is offensive to everybody involved. Because we are not just one thing.

02:17:06.980 --> 02:17:10.820
[Amit Varma]: We are many things. So these are my sort of thinking allowed kind of responses.

02:17:10.820 --> 02:17:16.260
[Guest]: Have you ever been has there ever been a phase where you felt guilty about your privilege?

02:17:16.260 --> 02:17:17.060
[Guest]: Has that ever happened?

02:17:17.940 --> 02:17:25.060
[Amit Varma]: I haven't felt guilty about my privilege, because it is what it is. But I have been guilty of the

02:17:25.060 --> 02:17:30.340
[Amit Varma]: blindness that my privilege has given me in certain contexts, like in this specific context,

02:17:30.340 --> 02:17:35.300
[Amit Varma]: where, you know, my friend Salil told me that, no, you know, there are times you just got to sit

02:17:35.300 --> 02:17:41.380
[Amit Varma]: back and listen, right? Right. So, so I might have felt I felt guilty, not of my privilege itself,

02:17:41.380 --> 02:17:46.180
[Amit Varma]: but ways in which it has made me behave. Like looking back today, much the same way that you

02:17:46.180 --> 02:17:50.500
[Amit Varma]: look back through your journaling, looking back to my childhood, I can see that, you know, because

02:17:50.500 --> 02:17:56.100
[Amit Varma]: of family background, and because of all of that, I had both a social arrogance and an intellectual

02:17:56.100 --> 02:18:01.620
[Amit Varma]: arrogance. And both of them were unwarranted. And I would assume that, of course, they might have

02:18:01.620 --> 02:18:06.500
[Amit Varma]: made me behave in ways which are absolutely obnoxious. You know, and I think that, hey,

02:18:06.500 --> 02:18:11.060
[Amit Varma]: I wouldn't want to know that person today. And it is possible I behave today in ways that I

02:18:11.700 --> 02:18:16.740
[Amit Varma]: might find obnoxious 10 years later, who knows, but not by privilege itself, because that is luck,

02:18:16.740 --> 02:18:21.060
[Amit Varma]: right? And both of us understand probability well enough to know that he gets mostly everything is

02:18:21.060 --> 02:18:27.780
[Amit Varma]: luck, right? And it is what it is, you know, it's not like I did something to be guilty about it.

02:18:27.780 --> 02:18:33.300
[Amit Varma]: But the question is, how do I behave now? Which is because you got to judge people by their actions.

02:18:33.300 --> 02:18:36.660
[Guest]: Yeah, I think this happened, you know, because I asked this because there was a phase when it

02:18:36.660 --> 02:18:42.260
[Guest]: hit me, you know, like, you know, it is a time when just it hits you that boss, you're privileged.

02:18:42.260 --> 02:18:49.860
[Guest]: There is so much because you tend to give yourself too much credit.

02:18:49.860 --> 02:18:52.260
[Guest]: Yeah. But then I saw other things started happening.

02:18:52.260 --> 02:18:58.100
[Guest]: Okay. If I start attributing everything to privilege, then I feel like I have no agency.

02:18:58.100 --> 02:19:00.500
[Guest]: Yeah. You know, so it's a tension, right?

02:19:02.260 --> 02:19:03.060
[Guest]: In other, you're saying,

02:19:04.740 --> 02:19:10.340
[Guest]: So then, like, who you are, like, is there, does that mean that I don't have any agency?

02:19:10.340 --> 02:19:13.140
[Amit Varma]: So you mentioned free will earlier. Yeah. And my take on free will is,

02:19:13.140 --> 02:19:17.940
[Amit Varma]: I don't believe it exists. It cannot possibly exist, but we must behave as if it does.

02:19:18.660 --> 02:19:20.180
[Amit Varma]: Okay. Because then how will we live?

02:19:20.180 --> 02:19:23.140
[Guest]: How will we live? Yeah, absolutely. That's actually a good frame.

02:19:24.500 --> 02:19:30.020
[Guest]: Interesting. But yeah, so, then one day I said, okay, now it is there.

02:19:30.020 --> 02:19:34.660
[Guest]: So what will I do? Guilt is, I think, the worst feeling, you know, in guilt and jealousy.

02:19:34.660 --> 02:19:41.780
[Guest]: I think these two are, like, very bad human emotions. So then I said, you know, be conscious.

02:19:41.780 --> 02:19:44.580
[Guest]: And then, Amit, one thing that I still struggle with is that, in fact,

02:19:46.340 --> 02:19:48.820
