05:18:01.140 --> 05:18:01.460
[Guest]: you know,

05:18:01.460 --> 05:18:02.900
[Guest]: I make sure that

05:18:04.020 --> 05:18:04.580
[Guest]: like I do,

05:18:04.580 --> 05:18:06.740
[Guest]: because I think this needs to be made more normalized.

05:18:07.300 --> 05:18:08.660
[Guest]: It's not that,

05:18:08.660 --> 05:18:08.900
[Guest]: oh,

05:18:08.900 --> 05:18:09.620
[Guest]: fitness is for,

05:18:09.620 --> 05:18:09.860
[Guest]: you know,

05:18:09.860 --> 05:18:11.380
[Guest]: these actors

05:18:11.380 --> 05:18:12.820
[Guest]: and people who won't know.

05:18:12.820 --> 05:18:13.940
[Guest]: Because one day,

05:18:13.940 --> 05:18:14.180
[Guest]: you know,

05:18:14.180 --> 05:18:14.980
[Guest]: friend asked me,

05:18:14.980 --> 05:18:17.060
[Guest]: if you have to choose between your body and your mind,

05:18:17.060 --> 05:18:18.100
[Guest]: what would you choose?

05:18:18.100 --> 05:18:18.660
[Guest]: I was like,

05:18:18.660 --> 05:18:19.460
[Guest]: idiot,

05:18:19.460 --> 05:18:20.740
[Guest]: this is such a terrible question.

05:18:21.460 --> 05:18:23.220
[Guest]: These things are connected.

05:18:24.980 --> 05:18:26.020
[Guest]: And I see,

05:18:26.020 --> 05:18:27.780
[Guest]: because when my body,

05:18:27.780 --> 05:18:28.820
[Guest]: like my body supports,

05:18:28.820 --> 05:18:29.540
[Guest]: how I think,

05:18:29.540 --> 05:18:31.540
[Guest]: how I work on a day to day basis.

05:18:31.540 --> 05:18:34.340
[Guest]: So that way I'm saying that it changed my life.

05:18:34.340 --> 05:18:36.900
[Guest]: It became such a central fulcrum of everything that I do.

05:18:37.700 --> 05:18:38.100
[Guest]: And yeah,

05:18:38.100 --> 05:18:40.420
[Guest]: I think everyone should really think about it.

05:18:40.420 --> 05:18:40.580
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

05:18:40.580 --> 05:18:44.180
[Amit Varma]: And I think there is this flawed impression

05:18:44.180 --> 05:18:46.340
[Amit Varma]: that if you shift to a healthier lifestyle,

05:18:46.340 --> 05:18:47.860
[Amit Varma]: that there is some pain involved,

05:18:47.860 --> 05:18:49.380
[Amit Varma]: that it is not enjoyable.

05:18:49.380 --> 05:18:50.660
[Amit Varma]: And that's absolute nonsense.

05:18:50.660 --> 05:18:53.060
[Amit Varma]: Like I went through this really nice phase three years back

05:18:53.060 --> 05:18:54.100
[Amit Varma]: till I lost discipline

05:18:54.100 --> 05:18:55.140
[Amit Varma]: and I came out of it

05:18:55.140 --> 05:18:57.540
[Amit Varma]: and COVID made me sedentary and lose my habits.

05:18:57.540 --> 05:18:58.180
[Amit Varma]: But I was,

05:18:58.180 --> 05:19:00.980
[Amit Varma]: I lost 20 kgs in a similar period of time as you did.

05:19:00.980 --> 05:19:02.980
[Amit Varma]: I was on keto plus intermittent fasting

05:19:02.980 --> 05:19:04.420
[Amit Varma]: and I loved that food.

05:19:04.420 --> 05:19:05.620
[Amit Varma]: I was running every day.

05:19:05.620 --> 05:19:07.540
[Amit Varma]: And I remember that initially,

05:19:07.540 --> 05:19:09.300
[Amit Varma]: it was difficult to discipline myself,

05:19:09.300 --> 05:19:10.260
[Amit Varma]: 5.30 in the morning,

05:19:10.260 --> 05:19:11.220
[Amit Varma]: you're going to run.

05:19:11.220 --> 05:19:12.660
[Amit Varma]: But then I read a quote,

05:19:12.660 --> 05:19:13.300
[Amit Varma]: which was so,

05:19:13.300 --> 05:19:14.020
[Amit Varma]: so true.

05:19:14.020 --> 05:19:16.100
[Amit Varma]: And this quote was all about that.

05:19:16.660 --> 05:19:20.100
[Amit Varma]: Every time you feel like not going out to run,

05:19:20.100 --> 05:19:22.820
[Amit Varma]: just remind yourself that once you go out,

05:19:22.820 --> 05:19:26.260
[Unknown]: you will never regret having run after you come back.

05:19:26.260 --> 05:19:27.700
[Amit Varma]: And I have found that to be true.

05:19:27.700 --> 05:19:30.820
[Amit Varma]: Every single time I have done exercise of any kind,

05:19:30.820 --> 05:19:33.460
[Unknown]: every single time that I've never regretted it,

05:19:33.460 --> 05:19:34.020
[Amit Varma]: you know?

05:19:34.020 --> 05:19:36.420
[Amit Varma]: And so once you get into the habit,

05:19:36.420 --> 05:19:38.340
[Amit Varma]: once you sort of own it,

05:19:38.340 --> 05:19:38.660
[Amit Varma]: you know,

05:19:38.660 --> 05:19:39.540
[Amit Varma]: it becomes easy.

05:19:39.540 --> 05:19:42.180
[Amit Varma]: Like I often tell my writing students

05:19:42.180 --> 05:19:44.580
[Amit Varma]: that if you want to read the dangerous way

05:19:44.580 --> 05:19:46.740
[Amit Varma]: to become a better reader is to say that,

05:19:46.740 --> 05:19:49.540
[Amit Varma]: okay, to set yourself a goal to do something

05:19:49.540 --> 05:19:51.620
[Amit Varma]: that every evening I'll read between six and seven.

05:19:51.620 --> 05:19:53.060
[Amit Varma]: And you might do it for two, three days,

05:19:53.060 --> 05:19:55.860
[Amit Varma]: but you fall off the wagon and vicious circle sets in.

05:19:55.860 --> 05:19:56.980
[Amit Varma]: It affects your self-image.

05:19:56.980 --> 05:19:57.700
[Amit Varma]: And then you say,

05:19:57.700 --> 05:19:58.980
[Amit Varma]: I'm a Netflix kind of person.

05:20:00.260 --> 05:20:03.060
[Amit Varma]: But if you take the approach of saying that,

05:20:03.940 --> 05:20:05.620
[Amit Varma]: if you think of the best version of yourself

05:20:05.620 --> 05:20:08.180
[Amit Varma]: and you tell yourself that I'm a reader,

05:20:08.180 --> 05:20:08.980
[Amit Varma]: you know, when I'm bored,

05:20:08.980 --> 05:20:09.700
[Amit Varma]: I reach for a book.

05:20:09.700 --> 05:20:11.220
[Amit Varma]: I don't reach for my smartphone.

05:20:11.220 --> 05:20:13.460
[Amit Varma]: If you internalize that self-image,

05:20:13.460 --> 05:20:15.060
[Amit Varma]: the habit comes from there.

05:20:15.060 --> 05:20:17.940
[Amit Varma]: And I feel that the same can work with fitness.

05:20:17.940 --> 05:20:20.500
[Amit Varma]: That if you just internalize that self-image,

05:20:21.060 --> 05:20:21.540
[Amit Varma]: you know,

05:20:21.540 --> 05:20:22.980
[Amit Varma]: it can come from there

05:20:22.980 --> 05:20:25.140
[Amit Varma]: and there is no punishment involved.

05:20:25.140 --> 05:20:27.060
[Amit Varma]: The exercise is not punishment.

05:20:27.060 --> 05:20:28.420
[Amit Varma]: The food is not punishment.

05:20:28.420 --> 05:20:30.980
[Amit Varma]: You know, that's my sort of great discovery.

05:20:30.980 --> 05:20:32.740
[Amit Varma]: And I'm sort of hitting myself over the head,

05:20:32.740 --> 05:20:34.180
[Amit Varma]: keep, you know, all my life.

05:20:34.180 --> 05:20:36.180
[Guest]: Manic unique, you live a healthy lifestyle.

05:20:36.180 --> 05:20:36.900
[Guest]: That is the thing, right?

05:20:36.900 --> 05:20:38.580
[Guest]: People always want to know the perfect thing.

05:20:39.460 --> 05:20:40.420
[Amit Varma]: There's no perfect thing.

05:20:40.420 --> 05:20:41.780
[Unknown]: It's like, what works for you?

05:20:41.780 --> 05:20:42.020
[Unknown]: Yeah.

05:20:42.020 --> 05:20:42.980
[Unknown]: You don't have to figure out,

05:20:42.980 --> 05:20:44.580
[Guest]: oh, the perfect workout.

05:20:44.580 --> 05:20:46.340
[Guest]: Okay, what is Alia Bhatt doing?

05:20:46.340 --> 05:20:48.180
[Guest]: No, you just figure out,

05:20:48.180 --> 05:20:50.340
[Guest]: because all of us have complicated lives.

05:20:50.340 --> 05:20:50.900
[Guest]: Things happen.

05:20:51.460 --> 05:20:53.300
[Guest]: Sometimes we'll fall off the track.

05:20:53.300 --> 05:20:53.780
[Guest]: Okay.

05:20:53.780 --> 05:20:56.260
[Guest]: You know, I very consciously also do emotional eating.

05:20:56.260 --> 05:20:58.100
[Guest]: Because once I realize what is emotional eating,

05:20:58.100 --> 05:21:00.100
[Guest]: when I'm stressed, I want to eat.

05:21:00.100 --> 05:21:02.020
[Guest]: So now I have a framework that when I'm stressed,

05:21:02.020 --> 05:21:03.700
[Guest]: I know, you know, Samarth, you are stressed

05:21:04.580 --> 05:21:06.500
[Guest]: and you are going to emotionally eat.

05:21:06.500 --> 05:21:08.100
[Guest]: You know, it's just my voice telling me,

05:21:08.100 --> 05:21:09.780
[Guest]: okay, go eat jalebi today.

05:21:09.780 --> 05:21:11.780
[Guest]: Okay, I go have a jalebi, right?

05:21:11.780 --> 05:21:13.540
[Guest]: And I'm like, I feel good

05:21:13.540 --> 05:21:15.460
[Guest]: because I'm not going to beat myself

05:21:16.020 --> 05:21:18.980
[Guest]: for having a gulab jamun and a jalebi when I want to.

05:21:18.980 --> 05:21:21.220
[Guest]: You know, it's not some purist stand

05:21:21.220 --> 05:21:23.060
[Guest]: that I've taken good food, bad food.

05:21:23.060 --> 05:21:27.300
[Guest]: That's a very unhealthy distinction to make.

05:21:27.300 --> 05:21:29.140
[Guest]: So I think you take, you build habits,

05:21:29.140 --> 05:21:30.500
[Guest]: you build your attitude.

05:21:30.500 --> 05:21:34.180
[Guest]: And then also realize that, you know, we are humans.

05:21:34.180 --> 05:21:36.420
[Guest]: We fall apart and you try.

05:21:36.420 --> 05:21:37.700
[Guest]: But I think that what you said, right?

05:21:37.700 --> 05:21:40.340
[Guest]: That internalizing, that identity,

05:21:40.340 --> 05:21:42.660
[Guest]: that this matters to me more than anything else.

05:21:43.460 --> 05:21:45.300
[Guest]: That I think just does wonders.

05:21:45.300 --> 05:21:46.500
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and I have to keep suppressing

05:21:46.500 --> 05:21:47.780
[Amit Varma]: the half Bengali in myself.

05:21:47.780 --> 05:21:48.820
[Amit Varma]: You know, the other day I said,

05:21:48.820 --> 05:21:50.180
[Amit Varma]: ki chalo push-ups karte hain

05:21:50.180 --> 05:21:52.100
[Amit Varma]: and I laid down on the ground to do push-ups.

05:21:52.100 --> 05:21:54.100
[Amit Varma]: But then once I'm flat on the ground,

05:21:54.100 --> 05:21:55.700
[Amit Varma]: the Bengali half of me is saying ki,

05:21:55.700 --> 05:21:57.700
[Amit Varma]: boss, this is a perfect position.

05:21:57.700 --> 05:21:59.940
[Amit Varma]: Abhi kahe utna hain?

05:21:59.940 --> 05:22:02.260
[Amit Varma]: You know, achhi jaga bhe toh hain.

05:22:02.260 --> 05:22:04.100
[Amit Varma]: Ye toh perfect hain na, ye hi toh,

05:22:04.100 --> 05:22:05.780
[Amit Varma]: isi liye toh sab kuch karte hain.

05:22:05.780 --> 05:22:08.020
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, my penultimate question,

05:22:08.020 --> 05:22:09.700
[Amit Varma]: though I wish we had another five hours,

05:22:09.700 --> 05:22:11.860
[Amit Varma]: but my penultimate question is that

05:22:11.860 --> 05:22:13.300
[Amit Varma]: one of the things I really,

05:22:13.300 --> 05:22:15.860
[Amit Varma]: that interested me about all the reading up

05:22:15.860 --> 05:22:17.380
[Amit Varma]: I was doing of your newsletter and so on,

05:22:17.380 --> 05:22:18.580
[Amit Varma]: and even what you spoke earlier,

05:22:19.620 --> 05:22:22.100
[Amit Varma]: was a desire to learn more.

05:22:22.100 --> 05:22:23.620
[Amit Varma]: You took a sabbatical at one point

05:22:23.620 --> 05:22:25.220
[Amit Varma]: where you said ki main chhe maine baad kya,

05:22:25.220 --> 05:22:27.300
[Amit Varma]: aat maine baad kya, I just want to learn.

05:22:27.300 --> 05:22:29.540
[Amit Varma]: You know, you've written a great piece

05:22:29.540 --> 05:22:31.940
[Amit Varma]: on acquiring new skills in the gig economy,

05:22:31.940 --> 05:22:35.380
[Amit Varma]: which I think is a great way to think about oneself

05:22:35.380 --> 05:22:38.420
[Amit Varma]: as a constantly evolving person with multitudes

05:22:38.420 --> 05:22:41.780
[Amit Varma]: rather than a person trained in a thing, right?

05:22:41.780 --> 05:22:42.420
[Amit Varma]: And I love that.

05:22:42.420 --> 05:22:44.580
[Amit Varma]: And equally, you said when you were in IIT,

05:22:44.580 --> 05:22:47.060
[Amit Varma]: aap Coursera mein gaye the, Udemy mein gaye the,

05:22:47.060 --> 05:22:48.340
[Amit Varma]: you were always doing courses

05:22:48.340 --> 05:22:50.340
[Amit Varma]: and not just in your specific subject,

05:22:50.340 --> 05:22:52.100
[Amit Varma]: lekin Humanities ye woh.

05:22:52.100 --> 05:22:53.940
[Amit Varma]: What is your attitude towards learning

05:22:53.940 --> 05:22:55.780
[Amit Varma]: and how central is it to you?

05:22:55.780 --> 05:22:59.540
[Amit Varma]: Because I think, to me, the key quality,

05:22:59.540 --> 05:23:00.660
[Amit Varma]: and I think this is, again,

05:23:00.660 --> 05:23:04.020
[Amit Varma]: something that you don't need any inborn talent in.

05:23:04.020 --> 05:23:05.540
[Unknown]: I think all of us can learn to learn.

05:23:06.100 --> 05:23:09.380
[Amit Varma]: And I think if we do that, then we are future proof.

05:23:09.380 --> 05:23:12.500
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a little bit about your experiences with this

05:23:12.500 --> 05:23:14.500
[Amit Varma]: in terms of, is it something

05:23:14.500 --> 05:23:15.860
[Amit Varma]: that's a regular part of your life

05:23:15.860 --> 05:23:17.460
[Amit Varma]: that you're always trying to learn something?

05:23:17.460 --> 05:23:19.700
[Amit Varma]: And what advice would you give others

05:23:19.700 --> 05:23:22.420
[Amit Varma]: that should they learn things for instrumental reasons?

05:23:22.420 --> 05:23:24.500
[Amit Varma]: Ki yeh karke humein yeh skill milega,

05:23:24.500 --> 05:23:26.180
[Amit Varma]: iski yeh employability yeh hai.

05:23:26.180 --> 05:23:29.380
[Amit Varma]: Or is it okay to just sit down and learn something

05:23:29.380 --> 05:23:30.420
[Amit Varma]: because you want to learn it

05:23:30.420 --> 05:23:32.580
[Amit Varma]: and then maybe nothing comes out of it?

05:23:32.580 --> 05:23:34.100
[Guest]: So I take the second approach.

05:23:34.100 --> 05:23:38.020
[Guest]: And see, again, I don't know,

05:23:39.460 --> 05:23:41.060
[Guest]: you said how important is learning.

05:23:41.060 --> 05:23:42.980
[Guest]: I think learning is everything.

05:23:42.980 --> 05:23:44.900
[Guest]: Like I told, I do journalism

05:23:44.900 --> 05:23:46.980
[Guest]: because I want to understand the world,

05:23:46.980 --> 05:23:48.020
[Guest]: and it just gives me...

05:23:48.020 --> 05:23:50.740
[Guest]: I've tried to ask why I don't have an answer.

05:23:50.740 --> 05:23:52.500
[Guest]: Uska answer nahi hai ki kyun.

05:23:52.500 --> 05:23:54.020
[Guest]: All I know is this is what I want to do.

05:23:54.020 --> 05:23:57.620
[Guest]: Like as we are talking, I am studying biology.

05:23:58.260 --> 05:24:00.100
[Guest]: Last year, it was for statistics.

05:24:00.100 --> 05:24:02.820
[Guest]: This year, I am doing rigorous courses

05:24:02.820 --> 05:24:04.340
[Guest]: on fundamentals of biology

05:24:04.340 --> 05:24:05.140
[Guest]: because I'm like,

05:24:05.140 --> 05:24:08.020
[Guest]: if I don't understand the fundamentals of biology,

05:24:08.020 --> 05:24:09.860
[Guest]: how will I make sense of CRISPR?

05:24:09.860 --> 05:24:11.380
[Guest]: I just don't want to read someone.

05:24:11.380 --> 05:24:13.780
[Guest]: I want to go back first principles biology

05:24:13.780 --> 05:24:15.140
[Guest]: so that I can think about it.

05:24:15.140 --> 05:24:16.340
[Guest]: And then I'm doing neuroscience,

05:24:16.340 --> 05:24:18.420
[Guest]: which is something that has been in my head,

05:24:18.420 --> 05:24:21.220
[Guest]: but I want to rigorously study it from the ground up.

05:24:21.860 --> 05:24:25.060
[Guest]: Ab I don't have a story, like as a journalist,

05:24:26.820 --> 05:24:28.900
[Guest]: I don't have a story that I want to report.

05:24:28.900 --> 05:24:31.460
[Guest]: It's just that in my framework,

05:24:31.460 --> 05:24:34.660
[Guest]: this is something I feel is important for my growth

05:24:35.620 --> 05:24:37.540
[Guest]: as a person who just wants to figure out things.

05:24:38.500 --> 05:24:40.420
[Guest]: And I think once that hits in,

05:24:41.220 --> 05:24:45.140
[Guest]: ki you know, this will enhance my understanding.

05:24:45.700 --> 05:24:50.740
[Guest]: For me, that in most cases gives me the push to start it.

05:24:51.460 --> 05:24:53.220
[Guest]: Ab iss se again, I don't...

05:24:53.220 --> 05:24:54.820
[Guest]: Actually, you know, now we started the discussion

05:24:54.820 --> 05:24:55.700
[Guest]: with my mom, right?

05:24:55.700 --> 05:24:56.820
[Guest]: So let's end with that also.

05:24:56.820 --> 05:24:58.660
[Guest]: My mom told me back when I was in school,

05:24:58.660 --> 05:24:59.700
[Guest]: she said that, you know,

05:24:59.700 --> 05:25:02.340
[Guest]: kuch bhi tum padhoge na, kuch kharab nahi jaata hai.

05:25:02.340 --> 05:25:03.620
[Guest]: So don't think too much about

05:25:04.180 --> 05:25:08.500
[Guest]: ki agar yeh extra cheez karli, toh iss se hoga kya?

05:25:08.500 --> 05:25:11.140
[Guest]: Don't ask that question.

05:25:11.140 --> 05:25:12.660
[Guest]: If you're learning, just learn.

05:25:12.660 --> 05:25:13.860
[Guest]: Something will happen.

05:25:13.860 --> 05:25:15.540
[Guest]: And that I think is kind of brilliant

05:25:15.540 --> 05:25:17.780
[Guest]: ki aapko sochna nahi padhega yeh main kyu karun.

05:25:17.780 --> 05:25:20.580
[Guest]: And Amit, then what happens over the period of time,

05:25:20.580 --> 05:25:24.020
[Guest]: you keep doing this and you see your,

05:25:24.020 --> 05:25:25.700
[Guest]: you know, you mentioned this point, right?

05:25:25.700 --> 05:25:28.180
[Guest]: About high definition picture as dots connect.

05:25:28.180 --> 05:25:28.740
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, yeah.

05:25:28.740 --> 05:25:29.620
[Amit Varma]: That is what happens.

05:25:29.620 --> 05:25:31.540
[Guest]: Like, I'll give you a practical example,

05:25:31.540 --> 05:25:33.140
[Guest]: which you'll see how organically things happen.

05:25:33.140 --> 05:25:34.260
[Guest]: So I live in the hills.

05:25:34.260 --> 05:25:35.940
[Guest]: And you know, what is the biggest problem in my life?

05:25:36.980 --> 05:25:38.820
[Guest]: You'll see how privileged this dude is.

05:25:38.820 --> 05:25:40.820
[Guest]: My biggest problem in my life are monkeys.

05:25:42.180 --> 05:25:42.500
[Guest]: Okay?

05:25:42.500 --> 05:25:45.140
[Guest]: Because they are in my veranda all the time.

05:25:45.140 --> 05:25:46.660
[Guest]: And you know, they're creating a mess.

05:25:46.660 --> 05:25:46.900
[Guest]: Okay?

05:25:46.900 --> 05:25:48.340
[Guest]: And I have to always be active, how to...

05:25:49.940 --> 05:25:51.220
[Guest]: One day I was thinking that,

05:25:52.260 --> 05:25:54.100
[Guest]: why can't I recognize who are the good guys

05:25:54.100 --> 05:25:54.980
[Guest]: and who are the bad guys?

05:25:54.980 --> 05:25:56.180
[Guest]: You know, who creates the struckers?

05:25:56.180 --> 05:25:58.900
[Guest]: Because I can't like make any distinction

05:25:58.900 --> 05:26:00.500
[Guest]: between these monkeys.

05:26:00.500 --> 05:26:01.140
[Guest]: Maybe I knew.

05:26:02.500 --> 05:26:04.180
[Guest]: Interestingly, just a week after

05:26:04.180 --> 05:26:05.620
[Guest]: I had this question in my head,

05:26:05.620 --> 05:26:07.060
[Guest]: I was doing this neuroscience course,

05:26:07.060 --> 05:26:08.260
[Guest]: which is the question,

05:26:08.260 --> 05:26:09.220
[Guest]: the theme of that course is

05:26:09.220 --> 05:26:11.300
[Guest]: how the brain gives rise to the mind.

05:26:12.020 --> 05:26:12.260
[Guest]: Okay?

05:26:12.820 --> 05:26:13.780
[Guest]: It's a beautiful question.

05:26:13.780 --> 05:26:15.620
[Guest]: Then Nancy Kanwisher, who's the instructor,

05:26:15.620 --> 05:26:18.260
[Guest]: these all, by the way, this course is on YouTube.

05:26:18.260 --> 05:26:21.220
[Guest]: Her introductory lecture has 10 million views, just FYI.

05:26:21.220 --> 05:26:22.740
[Guest]: It's, she's such a brilliant teacher.

05:26:22.740 --> 05:26:26.900
[Guest]: So she was describing about how humans recognize faces.

05:26:27.780 --> 05:26:28.100
[Guest]: Right?

05:26:28.980 --> 05:26:31.940
[Guest]: And there she said about this thing called,

05:26:31.940 --> 05:26:32.820
[Guest]: I'm forgetting the exact term,

05:26:32.820 --> 05:26:34.340
[Guest]: but the other race effect.

05:26:34.340 --> 05:26:36.900
[Guest]: You know, sometimes you say now when we make,

05:26:36.900 --> 05:26:38.020
[Guest]: I mean, this is politically incorrect,

05:26:38.020 --> 05:26:40.260
[Guest]: when we say something about people in China,

05:26:40.260 --> 05:26:42.340
[Guest]: that all of them look the same

05:26:42.340 --> 05:26:44.020
[Guest]: and that we say it's a racist comment,

05:26:44.020 --> 05:26:45.860
[Guest]: but she explained that there is biology to it.

05:26:46.820 --> 05:26:49.460
[Guest]: That, you know, how our brain is structured

05:26:49.460 --> 05:26:52.660
[Guest]: to recognize faces in the communities we go to,

05:26:52.660 --> 05:26:54.340
[Guest]: we grow up, the features that we see, right?

05:26:54.340 --> 05:26:55.380
[Guest]: That becomes our model,

05:26:55.940 --> 05:26:58.100
[Guest]: which is why when we see someone from another race,

05:26:58.100 --> 05:26:59.780
[Guest]: we are not able to make those distinctions.

05:27:00.340 --> 05:27:02.340
[Guest]: So as she described studies, it just hit me.

05:27:02.340 --> 05:27:04.740
[Guest]: And then I realized that is exactly what is happening.

05:27:05.380 --> 05:27:07.860
[Guest]: Why I can't identify these monkeys.

05:27:09.140 --> 05:27:09.860
[Guest]: Right?

05:27:09.860 --> 05:27:11.300
[Guest]: It's not that all monkeys look the same.

05:27:11.300 --> 05:27:12.660
[Guest]: It's that I can't identify.

05:27:13.220 --> 05:27:14.740
[Guest]: So it's a small thing, right?

05:27:14.740 --> 05:27:17.700
[Guest]: But it just gave me some deep joy

05:27:17.700 --> 05:27:19.860
[Guest]: because something I was thinking about,

05:27:19.860 --> 05:27:22.180
[Guest]: I was for my day-to-day life.

05:27:22.180 --> 05:27:25.540
[Guest]: And I'm doing this course out of just curiosity

05:27:25.540 --> 05:27:26.820
[Guest]: and, you know, things just connect.

05:27:26.820 --> 05:27:28.100
[Guest]: So what starts happening, I think,

05:27:28.100 --> 05:27:29.140
[Guest]: when you are in that process,

05:27:29.700 --> 05:27:32.580
[Guest]: at least for me, that out of the blue,

05:27:32.580 --> 05:27:34.180
[Guest]: you know, things start connecting,

05:27:34.820 --> 05:27:35.620
[Guest]: the dots join,

05:27:35.620 --> 05:27:38.020
[Guest]: your high-definition picture starts emerging.

05:27:38.020 --> 05:27:39.380
[Guest]: But I don't start by saying,

05:27:39.380 --> 05:27:41.460
[Guest]: I want a high-definition picture of X.

05:27:41.460 --> 05:27:43.220
[Guest]: Yeah, you gather dots for the love of it.

05:27:43.220 --> 05:27:43.860
[Guest]: You love it.

05:27:43.860 --> 05:27:46.820
[Guest]: And I think that is just pure joy.

05:27:46.820 --> 05:27:50.260
[Guest]: And I think that's why I told you at the conference also

05:27:50.260 --> 05:27:54.020
[Guest]: that, you know, my, again, journaling allows you time travel.

05:27:54.020 --> 05:27:56.740
[Guest]: So in my sessions, when I'm writing,

05:27:56.740 --> 05:27:59.060
[Guest]: Amit, I've been writing this for four years.

05:27:59.060 --> 05:28:01.620
[Guest]: Whenever I'm frustrated about being in a newsroom, whatever,

05:28:02.500 --> 05:28:03.860
[Guest]: I just want to understand that

05:28:03.860 --> 05:28:05.460
[Guest]: why did I come to this profession?

05:28:05.460 --> 05:28:07.380
[Guest]: I didn't, never signed up to save democracy, you know?

05:28:07.380 --> 05:28:08.980
[Guest]: I love, you know, there are people who come with that.

05:28:08.980 --> 05:28:09.700
[Guest]: I didn't come with that.

05:28:09.700 --> 05:28:13.060
[Guest]: I just thought journalism, like which other job pays you

05:28:13.060 --> 05:28:15.300
[Guest]: to learn about the world and tell it to other people?

05:28:15.300 --> 05:28:15.620
[Guest]: Right?

05:28:15.620 --> 05:28:16.900
[Guest]: That's what journalism is in a way, right?

05:28:16.900 --> 05:28:17.540
[Guest]: Good way to put it.

05:28:17.540 --> 05:28:18.100
[Guest]: Yeah.

05:28:18.100 --> 05:28:19.540
[Guest]: So I was like, this is it.

05:28:19.540 --> 05:28:21.700
[Guest]: So when you start saying, yeah, I have an understanding,

05:28:21.700 --> 05:28:23.220
[Guest]: then you break off your identity.

05:28:23.940 --> 05:28:25.300
[Guest]: Journalism is one way to get it.

05:28:25.860 --> 05:28:28.660
[Guest]: But if I have the privilege, if my finances are sorted

05:28:28.660 --> 05:28:31.540
[Guest]: and I can take out time to learn about things and do it.

05:28:32.260 --> 05:28:35.060
[Guest]: So, yeah, that's my approach.

05:28:35.060 --> 05:28:37.300
[Guest]: And it just gives me very deep meaning.

05:28:37.300 --> 05:28:39.140
[Amit Varma]: But did you solve the monkey problem?

05:28:39.140 --> 05:28:39.700
[Guest]: No.

05:28:39.700 --> 05:28:40.100
[Guest]: Monkey problem?

05:28:40.100 --> 05:28:40.980
[Guest]: I mean, monkey problem.

05:28:40.980 --> 05:28:43.780
[Guest]: Now the biology has told me that I can't distinguish

05:28:43.780 --> 05:28:44.500
[Guest]: between the faces.

05:28:44.500 --> 05:28:45.460
[Guest]: So I don't know.

05:28:45.460 --> 05:28:47.860
[Guest]: By the way, you know, monkeys, can I rant about them for a...

05:28:47.860 --> 05:28:48.660
[Guest]: Please, go ahead.

05:28:48.660 --> 05:28:51.460
[Guest]: You know, this is my favorite walk where I go every day.

05:28:51.460 --> 05:28:52.740
[Guest]: Recently, you know, three weeks ago,

05:28:54.500 --> 05:28:58.260
[Guest]: like there was this bunch of 15 monkeys who chased me, Amit.

05:28:58.260 --> 05:29:00.340
[Guest]: Because I was alone, I was walking up the hill.

05:29:00.340 --> 05:29:00.740
[Amit Varma]: Shit, they chased you.

05:29:00.740 --> 05:29:04.580
[Guest]: Yeah, and I sprinted the fastest 200 meter ever in my life.

05:29:04.580 --> 05:29:06.900
[Guest]: Because I felt like they're going to kill me.

05:29:06.900 --> 05:29:09.780
[Guest]: Because they were growling and they were chasing.

05:29:09.780 --> 05:29:10.740
[Guest]: And I don't know why.

05:29:10.740 --> 05:29:11.380
[Guest]: I did nothing.

05:29:12.180 --> 05:29:13.620
[Guest]: So monkey problem can't be solved.

05:29:13.620 --> 05:29:15.540
[Guest]: It is something, you know, when I went to the hills,

05:29:15.540 --> 05:29:19.620
[Guest]: I was like, you know, Samarth, humans need to coexist with animals.

05:29:19.620 --> 05:29:21.620
[Amit Varma]: This is not your home, you know.

05:29:21.620 --> 05:29:22.900
[Amit Varma]: Then the monkeys chase you.

05:29:22.900 --> 05:29:23.860
[Guest]: Then the monkeys chase me.

05:29:23.860 --> 05:29:25.780
[Guest]: And I'm like, I don't know, man.

05:29:25.780 --> 05:29:28.580
[Guest]: I can think about whatever ecology and human relationships,

05:29:28.580 --> 05:29:30.420
[Guest]: but I also want to be alive.

05:29:30.420 --> 05:29:33.940
[Guest]: So monkeys have really complicated my life in that way.

05:29:34.580 --> 05:29:34.820
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

05:29:34.820 --> 05:29:37.700
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, perhaps the biggest problem of them all,

05:29:37.700 --> 05:29:39.540
[Amit Varma]: certainly the biggest problem of them all,

05:29:39.540 --> 05:29:42.180
[Amit Varma]: when at the time you are being chased by monkeys.

05:29:42.180 --> 05:29:43.940
[Amit Varma]: I love your mother's advice, by the way, you know,

05:29:43.940 --> 05:29:45.300
[Amit Varma]: just read everything, you know.

05:29:45.300 --> 05:29:46.980
[Amit Varma]: And that's so nice.

05:29:46.980 --> 05:29:50.260
[Amit Varma]: So I'll end this episode by asking you for recommendations

05:29:50.260 --> 05:29:53.460
[Amit Varma]: for me and my listeners about books, films, music,

05:29:53.460 --> 05:29:56.660
[Amit Varma]: whatever you feel like, any category that you really love

05:29:56.660 --> 05:29:58.180
[Amit Varma]: and you want to share with others.

05:29:58.180 --> 05:29:58.660
[Amit Varma]: You love it.

05:29:58.660 --> 05:30:00.020
[Amit Varma]: You love them so much.

05:30:00.020 --> 05:30:00.340
[Guest]: Sure.

05:30:00.340 --> 05:30:02.340
[Guest]: So I think the book is a no brainer.

05:30:02.340 --> 05:30:04.260
[Guest]: I try to plug it at every possible event.

05:30:05.060 --> 05:30:08.020
[Guest]: Is Neil Postman written a book called

05:30:08.020 --> 05:30:09.700
[Guest]: Amusing Ourselves to Death.

05:30:09.700 --> 05:30:10.260
[Guest]: Have you read it?

05:30:11.300 --> 05:30:13.460
[Amit Varma]: I haven't read it, but it's been in my show notes

05:30:13.460 --> 05:30:16.500
[Amit Varma]: and I have bought the Kindle version and I've intended to read it.

05:30:16.500 --> 05:30:19.380
[Amit Varma]: But it's one of those things, you know, all the books that pile up.

05:30:19.380 --> 05:30:23.220
[Guest]: But I think that book, when I read it in a friend of mine at the Hindu,

05:30:23.220 --> 05:30:24.980
[Guest]: he recommended because, you know,

05:30:24.980 --> 05:30:27.940
[Guest]: I think that was a point when I started asking these questions

05:30:27.940 --> 05:30:29.860
[Guest]: about the press and the media and I could not.

05:30:29.860 --> 05:30:31.460
[Guest]: So he said, start with this.

05:30:32.100 --> 05:30:34.740
[Guest]: And it just changed the way I like it.

05:30:37.140 --> 05:30:40.740
[Guest]: For me, that I don't think anyone has read it,

05:30:40.740 --> 05:30:42.660
[Guest]: but it's a beautiful book.

05:30:42.660 --> 05:30:46.500
[Guest]: And I think all of us who at some point are struggling to understand social media,

05:30:46.500 --> 05:30:48.980
[Guest]: because that's absurdity of modern life, right?

05:30:48.980 --> 05:30:49.620
[Guest]: What is happening?

05:30:50.500 --> 05:30:53.620
[Guest]: This book was written in 1985 when there was no internet.

05:30:53.620 --> 05:30:56.660
[Guest]: It like the thing was TV and you read it.

05:30:57.700 --> 05:31:00.340
[Guest]: The book has stood the test of time.

05:31:00.980 --> 05:31:02.580
[Guest]: So I think that book is brilliant.

05:31:02.580 --> 05:31:05.780
[Guest]: The second book I will say is, again, I love, you know, old books,

05:31:05.780 --> 05:31:10.820
[Guest]: which Future Shock, Elvin Toffler, brilliant book.

05:31:10.820 --> 05:31:14.100
[Guest]: You read it and you say, I think 1970 that was published.

05:31:14.100 --> 05:31:16.180
[Guest]: I'm recalling from memory sometime around that.

05:31:16.820 --> 05:31:20.980
[Guest]: And like what deep thinker, what deep thinking about the future

05:31:20.980 --> 05:31:22.420
[Guest]: and how you think about it.

05:31:22.420 --> 05:31:26.340
[Guest]: The books is about that how in modern society,

05:31:26.340 --> 05:31:29.460
[Guest]: the pace of change has exponentially increased.

05:31:29.460 --> 05:31:33.860
[Guest]: And as humans, we're not designed to cope with that change.

05:31:33.860 --> 05:31:35.060
[Guest]: So what do we do?

05:31:35.060 --> 05:31:37.940
[Guest]: So he talks about all sorts of, you know,

05:31:37.940 --> 05:31:40.900
[Guest]: from where we live to our human relationships, all of those things,

05:31:41.700 --> 05:31:43.700
[Guest]: and talks about how we will adopt in the future.

05:31:43.700 --> 05:31:49.940
[Guest]: And I think it's such a, I think the genre is a futurist,

05:31:49.940 --> 05:31:53.140
[Guest]: but it almost feels like sociological work, right?

05:31:53.140 --> 05:31:54.020
[Guest]: It's so deep.

05:31:54.020 --> 05:31:57.300
[Guest]: It gives you so many ideas about thinking about the future.

05:31:57.300 --> 05:31:59.700
[Guest]: So I think that's the second book that I strongly recommend.

05:32:00.340 --> 05:32:02.260
[Guest]: So I'll stop at, I mean, books, you know,

05:32:02.260 --> 05:32:04.420
[Guest]: are never ending recommendations, but these two.

05:32:05.060 --> 05:32:07.460
[Guest]: Movies, I'll tell you one of my favorite movies is a new one.

05:32:07.460 --> 05:32:09.300
[Guest]: You've seen the trial of Chicago seven.

05:32:09.300 --> 05:32:11.380
[Guest]: No, it's a beautiful film.

05:32:12.260 --> 05:32:16.020
[Guest]: You know, that's a, yeah, I just love the movie

05:32:16.020 --> 05:32:18.020
[Guest]: because it's a very political movie,

05:32:19.220 --> 05:32:21.220
[Guest]: but it really had a deep impact on me.

05:32:21.220 --> 05:32:23.540
[Guest]: So I encourage people to watch it.

05:32:23.540 --> 05:32:26.900
[Guest]: And of course, Dead Poets Society, which we have already mentioned.

05:32:26.900 --> 05:32:28.740
[Guest]: So yeah, I think I'll stop here.

05:32:30.180 --> 05:32:31.940
[Amit Varma]: Samad, thank you so much for, you know,

05:32:31.940 --> 05:32:33.380
[Amit Varma]: spending so much time with me today.

05:32:33.380 --> 05:32:34.740
[Amit Varma]: I think we've actually, I mean,

05:32:34.740 --> 05:32:37.220
[Amit Varma]: I think the recording will be something over five hours,

05:32:37.220 --> 05:32:41.620
[Amit Varma]: but we've been in the studio together for six hours, 40 minutes already.

05:32:41.620 --> 05:32:42.900
[Amit Varma]: So thank you so much.

05:32:42.900 --> 05:32:43.620
[Guest]: Thank you for having me.

05:32:43.620 --> 05:32:48.420
[Guest]: I think it's from being a listener for, I don't know,

05:32:49.300 --> 05:32:54.740
[Guest]: you don't know, we have met at the media rumble in Delhi in 2018 or 19.

05:32:54.740 --> 05:32:55.220
[Amit Varma]: I'm forgetting.

05:32:55.860 --> 05:32:56.260
[Amit Varma]: I'm sorry.

05:32:56.260 --> 05:32:56.820
[Amit Varma]: I'm an old man.

05:32:56.820 --> 05:32:57.620
[Guest]: I forget these things.

05:32:57.620 --> 05:32:58.420
[Guest]: Of course.

05:32:58.420 --> 05:33:02.420
[Guest]: I don't even, I'm saying that like I've been a listener for that long.

05:33:02.980 --> 05:33:06.020
[Guest]: So it's an, it was an absolute pleasure to have this conversation.

05:33:06.020 --> 05:33:08.500
[Guest]: Thank you.

05:33:36.020 --> 05:33:36.500
[Unknown]: Thank you.

